r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-MedicalAccid     08-03 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Medical Accidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai council wants doctors to renew licenses every three years
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Stung by a spate of high-profile
malpractice cases, the Thai Medical Council is considering
requiring doctors to renew their licenses every three years, a
council official said Monday.
	   ``This idea is to assure quality of doctors. We want people to
be confident in our medical standard,'' said Dr. Chumsak
Pruksapong, deputy secretary-general of the Medical Council.
	   If the plan is approved, new doctors will have to renew their
licences every three years. To qualify for renewal, they will have
to take at least 50 hours of additional classes, Dr. Chumsak said.
	   Currently, Thai doctors are granted a lifetime license upon
graduation from medical school.
	   The plan, first raised three years ago, has gained new impetus
because of several recent complaints by people who say they or
their relatives were mistreated by hospitals.
	   They include the case of a retired Swiss banker who was
paralyzed after being injected with a dye for an x-ray examination
at a Bangkok hospital.
	   The victim, Earnst Wynistorf, complained to the council and
Parliament's Human Rights Committee, but did not file a malpractice
suit because he says the laws completely favor the doctors.
	   The hospital, Samitivej in Bangkok, has refused his demand that
it pay for his transport to and treatment in a European hospital,
instead offering its own free treatment.
	   Wynistorf, however, says he fears Samitivej's doctors. 	   
</TEXT>
