w2109 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Russia     08-03 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Russia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Japan's prime minister wants to visit Russia in November
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's new prime minister wants to visit Russia as
early as November to discuss a territorial dispute that has blocked
the two countries from signing a formal peace treaty to end World
War II, a news report said Monday.
	   ``I would definitely like to use such a chance to have (the
territory) returned as soon as possible,'' Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi was quoted as saying by Kyodo News agency.
	   The dispute centers on three small islands and one group of
islets at the end of the Kuril chain off the northern coast of the
Japanese island of Hokkaido.
	   The Soviet army occupied the islands in the closing days of
World War II. Japan has refused to sign a peace treaty until the
islands are returned.
	   Obuchi's predecessor, former Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto,
had planned to visit Russia this fall to hold talks toward signing
a treaty. But he was forced to resign in July after his party
suffered an embarrassing election defeat.
	   Obuchi, who served as Hashimoto's foreign affairs minister, had
met with Russian President Boris Yeltsin to prepare the way for
Hashimoto's visit.
	   While campaigning to replace him, Obuchi promised to continue
progress being made between the two sides in resolving the dispute.
	   Obuchi's own choice of foreign minister, Masahiko Komura, worked
with Obuchi in negotiating with Moscow and is widely seen as
knowledgeable about Russian affairs.
	   Obuchi would be only the third Japanese premier ever to visit
Russia.
 &UR; (mef)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
