<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Toilet Shortage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Millions of Vietnamese farmers lack toilets
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ About 12 million Vietnamese farmers have
no toilets and another 30 million lack proper sanitation
facilities, a Health Ministry official said Monday.
	   A survey conducted by the ministry's Preventive Medicine
Department showed that only 10 million rural residents have proper
toilets, the official said. About 80 percent of Vietnam's 78
million people live in the countryside.
	   The official said the common practice of defecating directly
into ponds to feed fish in rural areas, especially in the southern
Mekong Delta, has resulted in outbreaks of diarrhea, dysentery and
typhoid. Many farmers also use human feces as fertilizer.
	   Statistics showed that Vietnam had nearly 20,000 cases of
typhoid last year, along with more than 90,000 dysentery cases and
974,000 cases of diarrhea.
	   Last year, the government launched a clean-water campaign for
the Mekong Delta, urging people to build more septic systems.
	   The official, however, said it would be difficult to convince
farmers to change generations-old habits. A septic system costs
only about dlrs 50, but that's a huge amount for a country where
the average annual wage is under dlrs 300.
	   A pilot program run by the ministry in the Mekong Delta province
of Can Tho has achieved some good results so far in convincing
farmers to build septic systems, the official said. The ministry
hopes to expand the program to other provinces soon. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
