<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Fighting,0419 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mazar-e-Sharif tense as Taliban army nears
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Mazar-e-Sharif in northern
Afghanistan was reportedly tense Monday, a day after Taliban
fighters captured a nearby town and claimed to be closing in on
their enemies' stronghold from two directions.
	   Azizullah Shasaq, a spokesman for the Hezb-e-Wahadat militia
that controls Mazar-e-Sharif, confirmed his ally warlord Rashid
Dostum had lost Shebergan, about 100 kilometers (60 miles) west of
Mazar-e-Sharif. Taliban sources said they captured many of Dostum's
fighters, but had no firm figures or casualty reports. They said
Taliban forces were advancing on Mazar-e-Sharif from the west.
	   Taliban radio reported Sunday that fighters also had broken
through enemy defense lines at Ahrytan, about 65 kilometers (40
miles) east of Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Red Cross spokesman Michel Schaffner, speaking by telephone from
Peshawar, on Pakistan's border with Afghanistan, said about 10 aid
workers in Mazar-e-Sharif had asked the Red Cross to evacuate them.
Schaffner said Monday the Red Cross would have to ``assess the
security situation'' before flying in.
	   Seven expatriate Red Cross workers flew out of Mazar-e-Sharif to
the Afghan capital of Kabul Sunday, leaving behind a handful of
Afghan staff, Schaffner said. Their departure was routine, he said.
The Red Cross has been overseeing projects in Mazar-e-Sharif from
Kabul because the security in the northern town has long been
considered unpredictable.
	   Taliban fighters briefly held Mazar-e-Sharif last May but
retreated after street battles, mostly with Hezb-e-Wahadat
fighters, that left several hundred Taliban fighters dead. It is
believed that as many as 2,000 Taliban soldiers who were taken
prisoner in that fighting were later massacred.
	   Taliban fighters, who control about 85 percent of Afghanistan,
seem on the verge of taking the rest of the country. Victories in
recent days could give them the momentum to capture the remaining
major opposition strongholds.
	   The Taliban has imposed a strict version of Islamic law in
territory it controls. Since capturing Kabul in 1996, Taliban
officials have barred girls from school, confined most women to
their homes, forbade all music except religious songs and banned
anything published outside Afghanistan.
	   The anti-Taliban coalition is mostly made up of Afghanistan's
minority ethnic and religious groups, factions that sometimes fight
each other as well as the Taliban army. 	   
</TEXT>
