AP-NY-08-03-98 0131EDT
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19980803.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 08/03/1998 01:32:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2117 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Elections 8thLd-1stAdd   08-03 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Elections, 8th Ld-1st Add,0573 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGUASCALIENTES: 6 percent.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ``What we want for Aguascalientes is a transition that does not
hold back its progress, that does not cause a scandal,'' Felipe
Gonzalez Gonzalez of National Action told a news conference after
the nation's media declared him the winner.
	   The vote in Aguascalientes came a month after National Action,
known by its Spanish initials as the PAN, lost one of its six
governor's seats. It was defeated by the governing party, known as
the PRI, in Chihuahua. Aguascalientes was seen as the PAN's best
opportunity to compensate for the loss.
	   The business-oriented National Action has gained strength in
Aguascalientes as the small, relatively prosperous state has become
more urban and middle class in recent years.
	   Martin Diaz de la Vega, 32, a street salesman, said he voted for
the PAN for the first time because he believes the PRI is corrupt.
	   ``We need a change. Even if it's bad, I don't think it can be
any worse,'' he said.
	   Turnout figures among Aguascalientes' 500,000 registered voters
were not immediately available, but the state electoral council
reported earlier in the day that turnout was strong and there were
no major problems.
	   In Veracruz, Miguel Aleman, a wealthy businessman and the son of
a former president, said his victory was assured Sunday night after
the Televisa poll showed him winning with 52 percent of the vote.
	   Aleman promised to create ``a social alliance'' as Veracruz's
new governor during a local television interview broadcast live
into State Electoral Council headquarters as perplexed electoral
officials looked on.
	   By the time Aleman had declared his victory, the first official
numbers had not even be released.
	   Shortly after, electoral officials released the first official
numbers: with 200 of 7,046 polling places counted, the PRI
candidate was ahead with 53 percent, followed by Luis Pazos of
National Action with 28 percent. The Democratic Revolution
candidate trailed with 14 percent.
	   Veracruz, a party stronghold, was seen as essential for the PRI.
With its 4 million voters, Veracruz has the nation's third-largest
electorate and could be crucial in the presidential election.
	   If the final results reflect the showing of the exit poll, the
win could make Aleman a top contender for the PRI's presidential
nomination.
	   The PRI, which long maintained its power through a mix of
patronage, strong-arm tactics and cheating at the ballot box, has
seen devastating electoral losses in recent years following reforms
aimed at cleaning up the vote and making elections more
competitive.
	   The PRI suffered its worst setbacks last year when it lost
control of the lower house of Congress and was defeated in the
Mexico City mayoral race. But it won two of three elections last
month, including the defeat of the PAN in Chihuahua.
	   In Oaxaca, a tighter-than-expected race _ and a possible
electoral dispute _ was shaping up.
	   The first official results, issued by Oaxaca's State Electoral
Council, showed PRI candidate Jose Nelson Murat Casab was ahead,
but with Democratic Revolution candidate Hector Sanchez trailing by
just 6 percentage points.
	   With the votes from 8 percent of the polling places counted,
Murat Casab was leading with 42.7 percent of the vote, followed by
Sanchez with 36.8 percent. The National Action candidate had 17.98
percent.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Elections, 8th Ld-1st Add; CT:i; 
