<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Papua New Guinea-Aid </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia pledges U.S. dlrs 610,000 in additional aid
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia will provide U.S. dlrs
610,000 in extra funding to Papua New Guinea following last month's
tsunami disaster, Prime Minister John Howard said Monday.
	   Howard and his Papua New Guinean counterpart, Bill Skate, held
talks Monday during Skate's official visit. Skate said the official
death toll in the July 17 tsunami was 2,134, with 9,483 people
homeless and 628 in hospital.
	   Howard said Australia would provide money to build two or three
schools, rebuild roads and to construct facilities for the many
disabled people who had lost limbs in the disaster.
	   It would also help to develop new agricultural and fishing
industries as well earthquake monitoring to try to prevent a repeat
of the disaster. 	   
</TEXT>
