<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Rebel Plot,0249 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police thwart Tamil rebel plan to attack Colombo
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Sri Lankan police arrested 50
suspected Tamil rebels in citywide raids last week, claiming to
have thwarted a plan for terrorist attacks on the capital, a
state-run newspaper reported Monday.
	   The arrests were made last Monday, two days before the opening
of a seven-nation regional summit, said the Daily News.
	   Colombo police confirmed the arrests, but declined to give
details.
	   Following the interrogation of four Tamil rebel suspects,
arrested earlier, police picked up 50 suspects in raids on boarding
houses, construction sites, restaurants and jewelry shops, the
Daily News said.
	   It said the network had planned a series of bomb attacks and
assassinations.
	   The paper said police discovered a new strategy of the main
Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, of sending
infiltrators posing as construction workers and gold artisans. The
gold business is dominated by Tamils in Colombo.
	   The Tigers have struck in Colombo several times in the past with
car bombs and suicide squads, and have assassinated a president and
several other leading politicians.
	   Militants among Sri Lanka's 3.3 million Tamils are fighting for
an independent Tamil homeland saying they are discriminated against
in Sri Lanka, a country of 18.5 million people off India's southern
coast. More than 54,000 people have died in the insurrection that
began in 1983. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sri Lanka-Rebel Plot; CT:i; 
