u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Elections 5thLd-Writethru   08-03 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Elections, 5th Ld-Writethru,0658 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Early results show oppposition winning Mexican gubernatorial vote
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with 28 percent of the vote counted in Oaxaca state.
No pickup. Gonzalez Gonzalez is cq in graf 2.
 &UR; AP Photos AGU101-103;OAX101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By KEN GUGGENHEIM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AGUASCALIENTES, Mexico (AP) _ In a crucial victory ahead of the
2000 presidential balloting, partial election results showed the
opposition National Action Party on Sunday capturing the governor's
seat in the central state of Aguascalientes.
	   With 40 percent of the vote counted early Monday, Felipe
Gonzalez Gonzalez of National Action was ahead with 53.12 percent
of the vote, the Aguascalientes State Electoral Council said.
	   The ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party's candidate, Hugo
Hector Hugo Olivares Ventura, trailed with 36.97. Alfonso Bernal
Sahagun of the center-left Democratic Revolution Party had 6
percent.
	   ``What we want for Aguascalientes is a transition that does not
hold back its progress, that does not cause a scandal,'' Gonzalez
Gonzalez told a news conference after the nation's media declared
him the winner.
	   The vote in Aguascalientes came a month after National Action,
known by its Spanish initials as the PAN, lost one of its six
governor's seats. It was defeated by the governing party, known as
the PRI, in Chihuahua. Aguascalientes was seen as the PAN's best
opportunity to compensate for the loss.
	   The business-oriented National Action has gained strength in
Aguascalientes as the small, relatively prosperous state has become
more urban and middle class in recent years.
	   Martin Diaz de la Vega, 32, a street salesman, said he voted for
the PAN for the first time because he believes the PRI is corrupt.
	   ``We need a change. Even if it's bad, I don't think it can be
any worse,'' he said.
	   Final results for Aguascalientes' 500,000 registered voters were
not expected until sometime Monday, but the state electoral council
reported that turnout was strong and there were no major problems.
	   In Veracruz, Miguel Aleman, a wealthy businessman and the son of
a former president, appeared to have won the governorship in that
Gulf state.
	   With 36 percent of the vote counted, Aleman, of the PRI, was
leading with 52 percent of the vote. Luis Pazos of National Action
trailed with 28 percent. The Democratic Revolution candidate
trailed with 14 percent.
	   Aleman declared victory even before the early results were
announced and promised to create ``a social alliance'' as
Veracruz's new governor during a local television interview
broadcast live into State Electoral Council headquarters. Perplexed
electoral officials looked on.
	   Veracruz, a party stronghold, was seen as essential for the PRI.
With its 4 million voters, Veracruz has the nation's third-largest
electorate and could be crucial in the presidential election.
	   As governor of one of Mexico's most important states, Aleman
will automatically become a top contender for the PRI's
presidential nomination for 2000.
	   The PRI, which long maintained its power through a mix of
patronage, strong-arm tactics and cheating at the ballot box, has
seen devastating electoral losses in recent years following reforms
aimed at cleaning up the vote and making elections more
competitive.
	   The PRI suffered its worst setbacks last year when it lost
control of the lower house of Congress and was defeated in the
Mexico City mayoral race. But it won two of three elections last
month, including the defeat of the PAN in Chihuahua.
	   In Oaxaca, a tighter-than-expected race _ and a possible
electoral dispute _ was shaping up.
	   With 28 percent of the vote counted early Monday, PRI candidate
Jose Nelson Murat Casab widened his lead with 44.88 percent of the
vote. Democratic Revolution candidate Hector Sanchez had 35.79
percent. The National Action candidate had just under 12 percent.
</TEXT>
