<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine stocks fall sharply, index loses 4 percent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine stocks fell sharply
Monday, pulled down by a mixture of negative news, particularly the
falling Japanese yen, traders said.
	   The yen hit a seven-week low of 145 yen to the U.S. dollar in
early trading Monday, although the Philippine peso held steady on
strong dollar inflows.
	   Preliminary figures showed the 30-share Philippine Stock
Exchange Index fell 64.54 points, or 4 percent, to 1,543.07, past
the important support level of 1,600 points. On Friday, the index
fell 5.89 points to 1,607.61.
	   The broader All Shares Index also retreated past the 500-point
support, falling 17 points to 494.05 after Friday's 0.05 point
decline.
	   Losers beat gainers 83 to 11, with 34 issues unchanged.
	   Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co., shopping mall operator
SM Prime Holdings Inc. and Ayala Land Inc., all big capital stocks
that are weighted heavily on the main index, were among the victims
of Monday's across-the-board selldown.
	   ``We're following Wall Street and the yen's lead,'' said Noel
Reyes, vice president of research of Anscor Hagedorn Securities
Inc.
	   The Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged 1.6 percent on Friday.
	   Reyes said a technical rally should emerge sometime this week,
although others said the market appeared to be heading for a
further decline.
	   The peso, meanwhile, was marginally higher against the dollar in
morning trading, buoyed by some inflows of foreign funds and slack
demand for the U.S. currency, traders said.
	   The dollar inflows managed to keep the peso stable despite the
Japanese yen's sharp fall against the dollar in early trading.
	   At late morning the dollar averaged 42.063 pesos, down from
Friday's average of 42.080 pesos. 	   
</TEXT>
