<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Missile Accident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Soldier seriously injured after anti-tank missile goes off
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A Japanese soldier was seriously injured Monday
when an anti-tank missile mounted on an armored vehicle went off
during a training exercise, the Defense Agency said.
	   Sgt. Second Class Takahide Yoshiaki, 33, had his right arm blown
off by the blast, which occurred at a training base in the city of
Eniwa on Japan's northern main island of Hokkaido, Defense Agency
spokesman Shingo Nishi said.
	   Yoshiaki was taken to a nearby hospital for treatment, where he
remained in critical condition, Nishi said.
	   It was a second such mishap involving Ground Self-Defense Force
personnel in less than a week.
	   Last Thursday, a Japanese army sergeant was killed after a
cartridge case in the gun barrel of a military vehicle exploded at
a training facility in western Japan. That explosion also caused
slight injuries to two other soldiers.
	   In Monday's blast, Yoshiaki was checking the safety of the
firing device on the Type 89 Infantry Fighting Vehicle when the
missile suddenly shot off, the spokesman said.
	   Military officials were investigating the cause of the blast,
Nishi said.
	   Eniwa is 807 kilometers (500 miles), northwest of Tokyo. 	   
</TEXT>
