<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Mine Rescue </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hope fades for 10 men buried for 17 days in Austrian mine
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ Hopes are fading for 10 men buried last
month in an Austrian mine after cameras and microphones lowered
into an emergency shaft failed to detect signs of life in the
chamber where the men were believed to be trapped.
	   Members of the rescue team were to meet Monday in the mining
village of Lassing, 190 kilometers (120 miles) southwest of Vienna,
to decide their next moves.
	   The 10 were sent into a talc mine in Lassing on July 17 to
rescue miner Georg Hainzl, who was buried in a massive landslide
unleashed by torrential rains. But a second, larger landslide
trapped the nine miners and one geologist.
	   Talc is a soft mineral that is refined into talcum powder and
lubricants.
	   Rescue efforts intensified after Hainzl was found alive and in
relatively good condition July 26. He had taken refuge in another
chamber closer to the surface.
	   After weeks of drilling a 30-centimeter (8 inch) shaft, rescuers
broke through Sunday to the cavern where the 10 men were believed
to have been buried. Hopes increased when preliminary tests
indicated there was enough oxygen for the men to have survived.
	   Cameras and a microphone were lowered down the narrow shaft but
failed to detect any signs of life. A second camera with additional
lighting was lowered into the chamber early Monday.
	   The leader of the rescue team, Hans Dieter Faissner, said crews
``illuminated the cavern as much as possible'' but were still
unable to find the victims.
	   ``We are very disappointed because we could see nothing,'' Fritz
Stangl, deputy mayor of Lassing, told the Austrian Press Agency.
``But we are not giving up hope.''
	   The failure to detect signs of life was the latest setback in
Austria's worst mining accident since World War II.
	   Despite intensified efforts during the past week, the operation
has been delayed by numerous technical problems. The team had
planned to drill a second, wider shaft into the cavern to bring out
the men.
	   But the shaft kept filling with debris and stone and work on it
was suspended late Saturday. Engineers said it might have to be
reinforced with cement, a time-consuming process that could take
days.
	   If the men are found alive, however, rescuers said food and
water could be lowered through the narrow shaft until work on the
wider one is completed.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Austria-Mine Rescue; CT:i; 
