w2159 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-PapuaNewGui     08-03 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Papua New Guinea-Skate </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Skate: Papua New Guinea ready for business
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Papua New Guinean Prime Minister Bill
Skate, making his first official visit to Australia, said Monday
his country offers excellent opportunities to patient investors and
traders.
	   But he said his now 12-month-old government looks for genuine
partnerships that will contribute to nation building, not for what
he called ``spivs and profiteers.''
	   Skate admitted that economic progress in his resource-rich, but
still underdeveloped country, has been slower than he wanted, but
said that progress has been made over the past year.
	   He said his government has agreed to arrangements that will
underpin the building of a natural gas pipeline, from the rich gas
fields of his country's southern highlands, across the Torres
Strait and into the Australian state of Queensland, where it will
fuel both a power station and aluminum refinery.
	   ``My government would like to ensure that the benefits from this
project are shared fairly,'' Skate told a state luncheon with
Australian Prime Minister John Howard.
	   Skate said his own experience _ growing up in one of the large
squatter settlements that surround his country's capital of Port
Moresby _ had influenced his own approach to government.
	   He said Port Moresby had been designed, in colonial days, for
mostly Australian expatriates.
	   While involved in local government in the city, he had employed
members of the city's troublesome youth gangs _ known locally as
rascals _ to build footpaths in the city.
	   That had provided both badly needed employment and important
local facilities for his country's own people, Skate said.
	   Earlier Monday, Howard announced that Australia will provide
U.S. dlrs 610,000 in extra funding to Papua New Guinea following
last month's tsunami disaster.
	   Skate said the official death toll in the July 17 tsunami was
2,134, with 9,483 people homeless and 628 in hospital. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Papua New Guinea-Skate; CT:i; 
