<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Immigration </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australian opposition leader calls for more immigration
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Australian Labor Party leader Kim
Beazley said Monday that increased immigration levels could offer
the solution to many of Australia's long-term problems.
	   Beazley, the country's opposition leader and who would be prime
minister if his party wins the next general election, said Labor
would set up a new Office of Population and Immigration.
	   He said in a speech Monday that the continuing debate over race
and immigration was ugly and described right-wing legislator
Pauline Hanson's One Nation group as ``a racist, xenophobic
party.''
	   ``What I bring to the table is this: Labor believes that
increased immigration levels can be a solution to many of the
problems Australia faces in the long term,'' Beazley said. 	   
</TEXT>
