<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-SilkAir Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: SilkAir crash investigation to continue for 6 more months
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore Communications Minister Mah Bow Tan
said Monday that investigation of the SilkAir crash in Indonesia
last December will take at least six more months.
	   Mah was asked in Parliament to comment on an Asian Wall Street
Journal story last week listing pilot suicide as a likely cause of
the crash, but the question was ruled out of order before the
minister answered.
	   Last Dec. 19, the SilkAir Boeing 737-300 mysteriously dropped
from the sky into the Musi River in the Sumatran jungle, killing
all 104 people aboard. SilkAir is a subsidiary of the flag carrier
Singapore Airlines.
	   The investigation team is led by Indonesian officials, and
includes representatives of Singapore Airlines and Boeing.
	   Mah said the investigation has been made difficult by the damage
to the plane and the lack of data on the jetliner's cockpit voice
recorder and flight data recorder. The jet fell apart in the air
before hitting the river.
	   Further analysis is under way of aircraft systems, as well as of
``human performance aspects'' of the accident, he said.
	   Since the investigation is led by Indonesian officials, they
have the authority to release information, Mah said.
	   So far, the investigation team has examined the recovered
wreckage and a partial reconstruction of the aircraft's tail
section, he said, adding that the team has also carried out tests
in flight simulators.
	   Mah said Indonesia's current economic troubles aren't affecting
the investigation. 	   
</TEXT>
