<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Missile Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Soldier's arm blown off when antitank missile explodes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lead; Minor editing throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ An antitank missile mounted on an armored vehicle
accidentally exploded during a military training exercise Monday in
northern Japan, blowing off a soldier's right arm, the Defense
Agency said.
	   Sgt. Second Class Takahide Yoshiaki, 33, was injured in the
blast at a training base in Eniwa on Japan's northern main island
of Hokkaido, and was in critical condition at a hospital, Defense
Agency spokesman Shingo Nishi said.
	   It was a second accident involving Ground Self-Defense Force
personnel in less than a week.
	   Last Thursday, a Japanese army sergeant was killed after a
cartridge case in the gun barrel of a military vehicle exploded at
a training facility in western Japan. That explosion also caused
slight injuries to two other soldiers.
	   In Monday's blast, Yoshiaki was checking the safety of the
firing device on the Type 89 Infantry Fighting Vehicle when the
missile suddenly shot off, the spokesman said. Military officials
were investigating the cause of the blast.
	   Eniwa is 807 kilometers (500 miles), northwest of Tokyo.
</TEXT>
