<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Croatia Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ulihrach wins Croatian Open, third career title
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UMAG, Croatia (AP) _ Seventh-seeded Bohdan Ulihrach of the Czech
Republic cruised to his third career title Sunday defeating Swede
Magnus Norman 6-3, 7-6 (7-0) in the final of the dlrs 400,000
Croatia Open ATP tournament.
	   Ulihrach, the world's No. 43, adapted better to the sweltering
heat and controlled the 1 1/2 hour match with strong and precise
serving.
	   ``I slept like a baby last night and this is like a dream for
me,'' Ulihrach said after the match.
	   Playing in his seventh finals appearance, Ulihrach raced to a
4-0 lead in the opening minutes and calmly took the first set,
dropping only a handful of points on his serve.
	   ``I knew it would be vital to break early if I wanted to win and
fortunately I managed to do that in both sets,'' he said.
	   Norman buckled down mid-way through the second set, moving his
Czech opponent around the court with a mix of spin and slice shots.
The change of pace and variety allowed the ATP's No. 47 to level
from 3-1 down and push Ulihrach into tie break.
	   However, it was not meant to be for the Swede, who seemed more
drained and worn by the plus-30 heat in his third finals tournament
played at this Adriatic resort. Norman failed to grab even a single
point in the tie-break, going down 7-0.
	   The victory was Ulihrach's third career title and followed more
than a three year drought. He also claimed dlrs 53,000 in prize
money.
	   str/eb
</TEXT>
