<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodia's election committee to recount some results
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GRANT PECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Responding to opposition complaints,
Cambodia's election commission agreed Monday to recount votes from
certain areas in last week's general election.
	   The recount was scheduled later Monday even though preliminary
totals for slightly more than half of the 23 electoral
constituencies have not yet been released.
	   Results released so far for 11 provinces show Co-Premier Hun
Sen's Cambodian People's Party leading in all but three of them.
	   One of the two constituencies captured by the opposition
FUNCINPEC party was the central province of Kampong Cham, the
country's biggest constituency, with 18 of the National Assembly's
122 seats.
	   While the National Election Committee has not estimated the
allocation of seats among the winners, a projection by the
Committee for Free and Fair elections in Cambodia, an independent
election monitoring group, gives the ruling Cambodian People's
Party 64 seats, FUNCINPEC 43 and its ally, the Sam Rainsy Party,
15.
	   A spokesman for the National Election Committee said Monday he
hoped preliminary tallies would be completed for all constituencies
Tuesday or Wednesday, but that the committee had not yet received
all documentation from two provinces, Battambang and Rattanakiri.
	   The spokesman also defended the committee's decision to change
the mathematical formula by which the winners of the July 26 vote
will be allocated their parliamentary seats, explaining at length
that it was approved and publicized well before the election.
	   The change in formula, which was not widely publicized until
late last week, favors the top vote-getting party in any particular
province.
	   In practice, this would work to the advantage of the ruling
party, and is significant because it could provide that party with
enough extra seats _ over the original formula _ to attain a
parliamentary majority.
	   Despite repeated questioning, the spokesman could not explain
why the change had been made, other than saying the allocation was
``done in the highest mathematical way, a very scientific one.''
	   There was no ``political intention, it is technical work,'' he
said.
	   The elections were held one year after Hun Sen ousted Prince
Norodom Ranariddh as his co-premier in a violent coup, shattering a
tense dual premiership formed after the U.N.-sponsored elections in
1993.
	   The opposition parties, Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy
Party, alleging irregularities in voting and ballot counting, have
asked for a recount in suspect areas
	   They also asked that new votes be taken in disputed precincts if
their charges of wrongdoing were found valid, and threatened to
boycott the National Assembly if their complaints were not heeded.
	   Without the opposition's attendance, the assembly is unlikely to
have present the two-thirds of its 122 members needed to conduct
any major business.
	   Hun Sen responded by inviting the opposition to join a coalition
government, but warning that if they carried out their threat not
to attend the assembly, he could lower the constitutional minimum
for the assembly to meet and confirm a government from two-thirds
to 50 percent plus one. He also said his current government could
simply remain in power.	   
</TEXT>
