<HEADLINE>
Philippine military releases five Saudi nationals after
</HEADLINE>
questioning &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) _ The military has released five
Saudi Arabian men suspected of having trained Muslim guerrillas in
the southern Philippines after authorities found no evidence to
support the suspicion, an official said Monday.
	   An army spokesman said the five were taken in for questioning
Saturday in the town of Sultan Kudarat in Maguindanao province and
released the next day.
	   Army Capt. Salih Indanan said soldiers accosted the five at a
checkpoint in a village strongly influenced by guerrillas of the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front. They took the foreigners and their
guide to an army camp in Cotabato city, also in Maguindanao.
	   Indanan said they initially suspected the foreigners of being
military trainers of MILF rebel recruits but found no evidence. He
said the five have valid travel documents and were apparently in
the southern Mindanao region to help Muslim tribal families.
	   Last year, two Middle Eastern men, armed with rifles and
grenades, stormed an army camp near a domestic airport in
Maguindanao, killing two soldiers before being killed by government
troops. Military officials said then the two were seen in an MILF
camp before the attack.
	   The MILF is involved in on-and-off peace talks with the Manila
government but has been accused of continuing attacks against
military and civilian targets.	   
