r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq     08-03 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq,0581 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Butler meets Iraqi officials, Parliament in session
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By WAIEL FALEH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler
opened talks on Monday with Iraqi officials, who have insisted that
inspections be wrapped up and trade sanctions lifted this year.
	   Butler did not speak with reporters before his meeting with
Iraq's deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz, and other Iraqi
officials.
	   On Sunday he told reporters that the U.N. Special Commission,
which is responsible for monitoring Iraqi weapons, wants to wrap up
its work quickly.
	   ``Our steadfast aim is to get this done as soon as possible to
get to the end of the disarmament phase so the Security Council can
consider the sanctions issue,'' Butler told reporters.
	   Last month, Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein said in a nationally
televised speech that the sanctions must be lifted this year _ the
first time he had set a deadline. That statement later was endorsed
by the Revolutionary Command Council, Iraq's collective leadership.
	   Iraq's Parliament was to meet Monday to discuss the weapons
inspections and sanctions.
	   The U.N. Security Council imposed the sanctions _ which ban air
travel to and from the country and limit sales of oil, its main
export _ after Iraq's 1990 invasion of neighboring Kuwait. The
council has said they will not be lifted until the U.N. inspectors
certify that Iraq has eliminated its weapons of mass destruction.
	   Iraq says the sanctions have caused widespread suffering among
its 22 million people.
	   During his previous visit in June, Butler gave Iraq a
``blueprint'' of what it must do to comply with U.N. resolutions.
On Sunday, he called the plan ``an accelerated program of work.''
	   As usual, Iraqi newspapers excoriated Butler in their editorials
on Monday.
	   Al-Thawra, the newspaper of Saddam's ruling Baath party, said
Butler was no longer the representative of an international
organization but ``a man who implements American policies against
Iraq.''
	   Iraq has long accused the United States and Britain of
needlessly prolonging the trade sanctions.
	   Al-Thawra accused the United States of ``igniting a series of
dangerous crises,'' including a standoff earlier this year over
Iraq's refusal to open presidential sites to U.N. inspectors.
	   The United States and Britain sent warplanes and ships to the
Gulf, threatening military action to force Iraq to cooperate. The
crisis was defused in a February agreement negotiated by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
	   The paper called Butler's commission ``not credible'' and
accused him of making statements in Iraq suggesting there was
progress in disarmament, then telling the U.N. Security Council
there were problems.
	   The state-run Al-Jumhuriya repeated allegations that depleted
uranium warheads used by U.S. forces in the Gulf War had poisoned
Iraq's environment. The government says the chemicals have
contributed to birth defects and higher rates of cancer.
	   In an unusual claim, it also accused the Americans of trying to
sabotage Iraq's grain output with rodents.
	   ``Iraqis noticed an unusual increase of mice and rats in Iraq,
which led them to think that this is (the result of) an organized
operation by a foreign side, represented by the American officers
and spies working at the Special Commission,'' Al-Jumhuriya said.
	   It termed the pest problem ``biological warfare'' against Iraq.
</TEXT>
