<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese dissidents push for retrial of corrupt official
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Two Chinese dissidents who believe a corrupt
senior leader got off lightly with a 16-year prison sentence have
launched a petition to have him retried, a human rights group said.
	   Yu Tielong and his son Yu Yuanhong hope to gather 10,000
signatures backing their demand that the former mayor of Beijing,
Chen Xitong, go on trial again in open, televised proceedings, the
Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China
said Sunday.
	   Chen was sentenced Friday after a secret trial to 16 years in
prison for corruption and dereliction of duty. Caught in a massive
graft scandal that engulfed Beijing's city government in 1995,
Chen, who also was Beijing's Communist Party boss, was the most
senior official prosecuted in a five-year government campaign
against corruption.
	   Yu Yuanhong said Chen's sentence ``made people feel that high
officials and ordinary people are not at all equal before the
law,'' the Hong Kong-based Information Center added.
	   Yu claimed the Communist Party treated Chen lightly out of
political considerations and said his sentence made people lose
faith in the government's anti-corruption campaign, the center
said. Yu and his father, from eastern Hangzhou city, are doctors of
Chinese medicine who have taken part in previous signature
campaigns, the center said.
	   A government-run newspaper said Chen's sentence showed the
Communist Party's determination to root out corrupt officials, no
matter how senior.
	   ``The verdict answered the long-lingering suspicions and worries
among ordinary people as to whether Chen ... would be punished by
law,'' the China Daily said in a commentary Monday.
	   The newspaper warned that corruption could hinder China's
economic reforms and trigger social unrest, particularly as
moribund state companies lay off millions of workers in an effort
to reform.
	   It said that simply making examples of high officials like Chen
was not enough to stop corruption. The ``power of the people'' also
was needed, along with more transparent government, stronger
supervisory bodies, and ``a more legalized society,'' it said.	   
</TEXT>
