w2199 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Kidnappings 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Kidnappings, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Suharto relative linked to investigation of kidnappings of
</HEADLINE>
activists &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quote, more comment from military commander &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ A son-in-law of former President
Suharto will be investigated in connection with the kidnappings of
political activists, Indonesia's armed forces chief said Monday.
	   The Suharto relative, Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto, was in charge
of Indonesia's special forces, which have been implicated in the
abductions of government opponents since last year.
	   Human rights activists have accused top military brass of
ordering the abductions while Suharto was in power and have called
for investigations of Prabowo and other senior officials.
	   Under new, reform-minded President B.J. Habibie, the military
has pledged to pursue officers implicated in human rights abuses.
	   Indonesia's military commander, Gen. Wiranto, said military
investigators will examine whether Prabowo, as well as another
general and an officer, were involved. He also said 10
lower-ranking soldiers arrested in the case will be tried in a
military court.
	   ``Honestly, (the armed forces) will investigate the mistakes
made by individuals,'' Wiranto said at a news conference at the
Defense Ministry. A council of seven generals will handle the
probe.
	   Activists who were kidnapped and later released said they were
held in cells while being tortured and questioned about their
political activities. At least 14 are still missing.
	   Prabowo has said he is ready to take responsibility for the
kidnappings, which occurred before Suharto quit in May after 32
years in power.
	   Soon after Suharto resigned amid riots and student protests,
Wiranto transferred Prabowo to a less prestigious post in Bandung
in what was seen as the removal of a rival. He has been placed on
leave pending the result of the investigation.
	   The ambitious and brash Prabowo is a controversial figure whose
fast-rising career was sidelined by the sudden downfall of his
father-in-law.
	   At his news conference, Wiranto also said Indonesia was safe
again for tourists and investments in the wake of the political
turmoil that led to Suharto's downfall. However, fears of more
unrest linger because Indonesia's economic crisis is pushing
millions into poverty.	   
</TEXT>
