w2202 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-USmilitar 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-US military, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Estrada says Albright pledged U.S. ships won't carry nuclear
</HEADLINE>
weapons in exercises &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comments by defense secretary in 6th graf &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright has guaranteed that U.S. ships joining any future joint
military exercises in the Philippines will not carry nuclear
weapons, President Joseph Estrada said Monday.
	   Estrada said Albright made the pledge during a meeting in Manila
last week.
	   ``She guaranteed that,'' Estrada said in a radio interview.
	   He quoted Albright as saying that a policy of deploying only
ships without nuclear weapons in military exercises was adopted
during the term of President George Bush.
	   Philippine Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado met later Monday
with his U.S. counterpart, William Cohen, to discuss a proposed
accord, called the Visiting Forces Agreement, that would allow a
resumption of military exercises between the Philippines and the
United States.
	   ``We feel that these exercises will be of use and benefit to our
country especially now that we are in a bind and unable to pursue
with gusto our (military) modernization program,'' Mercado said.
	   The United States halted all joint exercises on Philippine
territory and visits by U.S. military ships in December 1996, when
the Manila government ended a legal loophole that had shielded U.S.
military personnel from prosecution by the Philippines for crimes
committed here.
	   The Visiting Forces Agreement, signed early this year by U.S.
and Philippines officials, would provide certain legal protections
to U.S. soldiers while on duty in the Philippines. It still must be
ratified by the Philippine Senate, which has not yet begun
deliberations.
	   Several groups, including the Roman Catholic Church, have
opposed the agreement, saying it would infringe on Philippine
sovereignty, promote prostitution and endanger Filipinos if nuclear
weapons are carried on U.S. ships or planes.
	   Critics say the accord limits the Philippine government's right
to prosecute American soldiers who commit crimes in the country.
	   The agreement gives the United States jurisdiction over soldiers
who commit crimes while on duty, and the Philippines jurisdiction
over crimes committed while off-duty.
	   Estrada and Mercado, who as senators voted against extending the
lease on the last U.S. military base in the Philippines in 1992,
support the accord, saying the country must depend on military help
from the United States until it develops a credible deterrent of
its own.
	   ``This is different because we're fighting for the security of
our country this time. We have a very weak military and our
equipment is obsolete and antiquated,'' Estrada said, adding that
the country could be invaded by its neighbors at any time with
ease.
	   ``We can't win _ any time we could be invaded,'' Estrada said,
referring to China, Malaysia, Thailand or Indonesia as possible
aggressors.
	   Estrada said the agreement would allow a U.S. military presence
only during exercises, stressing he is against any form of
permanent stationing of American troops in the country.
	   The two countries used to conduct between six and eight military
exercises a year, involving up to 3,000 U.S. troops at a time.	   
</TEXT>
