<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Armed forces chief says Indonesia is safe for tourists, investors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's military commander called
Monday for the return of much needed foreign capital, declaring the
economically stricken nation to be safe for tourists and investors.
	   In the wake of the turmoil that forced President Suharto from
power, Indonesia has been implementing democratic reforms and
struggling to revive its shattered economy. But fears of fresh
unrest have kept many visitors and their dollars away.
	   ``I declare now that Indonesia is safe for tourists and
investments,'' Gen. Wiranto, head of the armed forces, said at a
news conference. ``This is the time to invest your money again.''
	   Many investors don't agree. The economy remains virtually
paralyzed, with millions of people out of work and prices rising
fast. About 1,200 people were killed in rioting over price
increases in Jakarta in May, and Suharto quit soon after.
	   Much of the violence targeted Indonesia's ethnic Chinese
minority, which controls much of the economy and often becomes a
scapegoat when social tension boils over.	   
</TEXT>
