w2213 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-DefamationS     08-03 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Defamation Suit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore PM moves to collect damages award after defamation
</HEADLINE>
ruling &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong stepped
up efforts Monday to collect a defamation damages award from
political opponent J.B. Jeyaretnam, a move Jeyaretnam said is
likely to drive him into bankruptcy and out of Parliament.
	   The tangled case involves Jeyaretnam's campaign rally statement
that some of his supporters had filed police complaints against
Goh. Although the statement was true, Goh successfully sued
Jeyaretnam, one of only three opposition members in the 84-seat
Parliament.
	   Last month, Singapore's highest court ruled that Jeyaretnam
acted out of malice and awarded Goh 100,000 Singapore dollars (dlrs
58,800) in damages. Jeyaretnam was also sentenced to pay full court
costs, estimated at about 150,000 Singapore dollars (dlrs 88,000).
	   ``Mr. Goh Chok Tong has today served me with a statutory demand
demanding payment of the 100,000 (Singapore dollars) within 21
days,'' Jeyaretnam said in a statement.
	   ``The statutory demand is the first step in bankruptcy
proceedings. If I do not pay, and I have said I do not have the
money, a bankruptcy petition will be served on me,'' he added.
	   Jeyaretnam had said last month he could not pay the award.
	   He has expressed fears that he will be proclaimed bankrupt,
which under the constitution would cause him to lose his Parliament
seat.
	   Seven other senior Singapore officials, including former Prime
Minister Lee Kuan Yew, now a senior minister, are suing Jeyaretnam
over the same statement.
	   The case was used as an example in this year's U.S. State
Department Human Rights Report, which said the Singapore government
uses legal processes such as libel and defamation suits to stifle
freedom of speech and intimidate the political opposition.	   
</TEXT>
