<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Prison Break </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Escaped fugitives still elude police in northeast Russia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Three fugitives remained at-large Monday after
escaping from a prison and into the wilderness of Russia's far
northeast. Authorities said their search on the edge of the Arctic
Circle was hampered by snow, rain and fog.
	   Troops and local police were pursuing the fugitives on a
northern section of the Chukotka peninsula, which extends into the
Bering Strait, across from Alaska.
	   But the bad weather, including an August snow, kept military
helicopters grounded, and prevented Federal Security Service troops
from pinpointing the escapees' location, the ITAR-Tass news agency
said.
	   The troops have orders to shoot the fugitives on sight.
	   A group of 11 convicts killed a police officer and stole a large
number of weapons while escaping from prison Friday and fleeing in
two stolen trucks and an armored vehicle.
	   Two convicts and two police were killed in a shootout that
followed. One escapee committed suicide and five more were
captured.
	   Authorities said they were confident they would track down the
fugitives because there are few places to hide on the tundra, and
the Chukotka Peninsula is so far north that there there is little
darkness this time of year. The nearest human settlement is a
village about 500 kilometers (300 miles) away, officials said.
	   (nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Russia-Prison Break; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
