<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Toxic Fire </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fire at Israeli toxic waste dump leads to call for investigation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ A large-scale fire at a toxic waste dump in
southern Israel led to calls Monday for an investigation into
safety standards at the site.
	   Environment Minister Rafael Eitan said the ministry would
investigate the fire, which began Sunday night at the Ramat Hovav
dump, 7 miles (11 kms) south of the town of Beersheva in the Negev
Desert.
	   Ministry spokesman Yiftah Kramer said the fire broke out when
vats storing lithium batteries in oil fell and exploded.
	   The fire blazed all night, and the last remnants were still
being extinguished Monday morning, Kramer said.
	   Ofer Ben Dov, director of Greenpeace in Israel, said safety at
the site must be given high priority on the national agenda.
	   ``Over the past year and a half, three parliamentary committees
have discussed the subject but nothing has been done,'' he told
Israel Radio. ``The prime minister needs to take matters into his
own hands.''
	   The Yediot Ahronot newspaper published a list of dangerous
incidents that have taken place at the site over the last 10 years,
including several fires and chemical leaks.
 &UR; dk-hla
