w2226 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-SlayingsArre     08-03 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Slayings Arrest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ranariddh charges Khmer Rouge arrest a political ploy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PHN101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ The arrest of a former Khmer Rouge
guerrilla wanted for the killing of three Western tourists in 1994
is a political ploy, Cambodia's ousted co-prime minister Prince
Norodom Ranariddh charged Monday.
	   The arrest of Nuon Paet on Saturday for ordering the slayings of
the young kidnapped travelers was a ``tragic comedy,'' Ranariddh
told reporters at Phnom Penh airport upon his return from a weekend
trip to Bangkok, Thailand.
	   ``Why? Because Hun Sen has known for a long time where Nuon Paet
is, but he didn't do anything,'' Ranaridddh said.
	   He did it now, Ranariddh added, because he wanted ``to please
Australia, Britain and France'' after the elections.
	   The international community provided more than dlrs 30 million
in aid for Cambodia to hold parliamentary elections July 26, and
then gave its stamp of approval, saying the polls could be
considered credible.
	   Hun Sen hopes that the elections will restore his legitimacy and
foreign aid lost after he ousted Ranariddh as his co-prime minister
in a coup last year, shattering a dual premiership formed after the
U.N.-sponsored elections in 1993.
	   Nuon Paet, 52, headed a band of Khmer Rouge guerrillas who
halted a train in the southern province of Kampot and abducted and
killed David Wilson, 29, of Australia, Mark Slater, 28, of Britain
and Jean-Michel Braquet, 27, of France.
	   He was arrested Saturday after the government lured him to Phnom
Penh from the former guerrilla stronghold of Pailin with offers of
a bogus business deal. He is being detained at the capital's
dilapidated T-3 prison.
	   Australia's foreign minister on Sunday denied speculation that
the arrest was part of a deal for Australia's acceptance of Hun
Sen's apparent election victory.
	   The opposition has accused Hun Sen's ruling Cambodian People's
Party of election fraud, and appealed to international election
observers to pressure the government to investigate.
	   Alexander Downer said Australia's decision to recognize the
election outcome would be based on the assessment of the Joint
International Observers Group _ which included 22 Australians _
once all counting was complete and results announced.
	   ``The arrest of Nuon Paet doesn't play into that as far as we
are concerned,'' he said.
	   Although it was the Kampot court that issued the warrant for
Nuon Paet's arrest nearly two years ago, Hun Sen said over the
weekend that he would be tried in Phnom Penh ``for security
reasons.''
	   The deputy of the Phnom Penh municipal court, Nop Sophon, said
Monday that no trial date has been set or formal charges filed.
	   Ranariddh suggested that Nuon Paet's arrest could also be a
warning signal by Hun Sen to the former guerrillas in Pailin, which
was one of the few constituencies won by an opposition party in
last week's election.
	   The province had been expected to favor the ruling Cambodian
People's Party, but instead supported the Sam Rainsy Party.
	   ``Hun Sen is not happy with Pailin,'' Ranariddh said. ``Pailin
voted for Sam Rainsy, so Hun Sen wasn't happy.''	   
</TEXT>
