<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Helicopter Fracas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Row erupts over Bell helicopter deal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ As Prime Minister Radu Vasile inspects
cheaper ways to purchase fighter helicopters, ministers quarreled
over a American helicopter deal which some claim will cripple the
flagging economy, papers reported Monday.
	   Newspapers said Defense Minister Victor Babiuc told Finance
Minister Daniel Daianu on Saturday to ``either sign (the deal) or
resign.'' Daianu called the deal ``immoral'' in the light of
Romania's economic woes.
	   On a four-day official visit to Israel, Vasile toured Israel
Aircraft Industries, which specializes in upgrading American Cobra
attack helicopters.
	   Ministers fought among themselves over which helicopter deal was
better for the country, the daily Ziua reported. Daianu said if
Romania bought helicopters from Israel, it would save dlrs 1.2
billion.
	   Vasile and his wife posed for photographs in a a Cobra
helicopter and the prime minister told reporters the Bell Textron
deal was ``not final.''
	   American company Bell Textron has said Romania must purchase 96
attack helicopters called ``Dracula'' as part of the
government-guaranteed loan.
	   Supporting the deal, Babiuc said Romania has to show willing to
spend on defense if it wants to join NATO. ``If we want to be
serious about entering NATO, our defense budget has to be doubled
or even tripled.''
	   The deal would increase defense spending by 20 percent a year
about dlrs 200 million a year- for the next 14 years.
	   The final deci on the helicopter purchase will be taken by
Romania's Supreme Defense Council, Petre Roman, head of
parliament's upper chamber the Senate said. No session of the
council has been scheduled.
	   (am/ma)
</TEXT>
