<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo market's main index falls after four-day rise, dollar climbs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Wraps up with late dollar, closing bond price, other details &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos TOK101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index fell sharply
on profit-taking Monday after a four-day rise, while the U.S.
dollar climbed to a seven-week high against the yen.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 213.89 points, or 1.31
percent, closing at 16,165.08.
	   In the previous four trading days, the Nikkei index had gained a
total of 434.61 points, or 2.8 percent, including Friday's gain of
177.37 points, or 1.09 percent.
	   ``The steep fall in financial shares damped sentiment,'' said
Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo Securities Co.
	   Major bank issues and brokerage stocks were sold amid renewed
worries about the health of the nation's banking system, which is
saddled with huge bad debts left from a collapsed bubble of real
estate speculation in the early 1990s.
	   Trading was light as many investors held back to see what the
administration of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, inaugurated last
week, will do in efforts to rescue Japan's economy from recession.
	   Declines outnumbered advances 823 to 274, with 170 issues
unchanged. An estimated 300 million shares changed hands on the
first section, down from Friday's 379 million.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 16.80 points, or 1.33 percent, to 1,245.24. It
had climbed 13.85 points, or 1.11 percent, on Friday.
	   In late afternoon, the dollar bought 145.64 yen, up 1.86 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of
144.65 yen on Friday. During Monday's trading, it ranged between
144.60 yen and 145.71 yen, its highest intraday level in Tokyo
since June 16.
	   The dollar advanced despite some concern among traders that
pushing the U.S. currency higher too aggressively might invite
intervention by Japan's central bank.
	   The yen has come under selling pressure amid a perception that a
turnaround in Japan's economy could take time, despite plans
unveiled recently by Obuchi.
	   Obuchi has promised 6 trillion yen (dlrs 42 billion) in income
tax cuts and 10 trillion yen (dlrs 69 billion) in stimulus
spending.
	   On Friday, the government said Japan's unemployment rate in June
rose to 4.3 percent, its highest since the government began taking
such statistics in 1953.
	   Obuchi is expected to offer some details of his economic plans
in a speech before Parliament later this week.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.225 percent from Friday's finish of 1.250
percent, driving its price up to 111.62 yen from 111.45 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj)	   
</TEXT>
