<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong market dives before earnings and growth reports
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing figures; ADDS revised economic growth
figures for 1st quarter, and interim earning results for HSBC
Holdings &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos HK101-103 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Share prices tumbled Monday in Hong Kong, with
the key index losing 4.8 percent because of bad news both from
abroad and at home.
	   The Hang Seng index fell 383.43 points, closing at 7,552.77. The
loss followed drops of 3.89 percent last week and more than 4
percent the previous week.
	   Traders blamed a sharp fall Friday on Wall Street, the weakness
of the Japanese yen resulting from uncertainties about the new
government of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, and concerns about the
domestic economy.
	   After the market closed, the government reported that the
economy shrank by 2.8 percent in the first quarter, revising an
earlier estimate of a 2.0 percent contraction.
	   Giant HSBC Holdings, Hong Kong's leading bank, also announced
that its net profit fell 16 percent to U.S. dlrs 2.40 billion in
the first half of this year. HSBC accounts for a third of the
weight of Hong Kong's benchmark stock index.
	   HSBC shares fell 10 Hong Kong dollars to 179.00.
	   Hong Kong withstood much of Asia's financial turmoil in the
first months after it began last summer, but now has been dragged
down into recession as well. Unemployment is at a 15-year high. The
economy is being slowed further by cargo problems at the new Chek
Lap Kok airport.
	   ``Investors are selling on the yen's weakness, and the Dow's
fall,'' said Michael Ng, dealing director at Sassoon Securities.
	   The dollar hit a seven-week high of 145 yen Monday in Asia. The
Dow fell 143.66 points on Friday.
	   The Hang Seng index is nearing its low for the year, 7,462.5,
which it reached in mid-June.	   
</TEXT>
