<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,0579 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; GRENADA: Castro arrives amid cheers &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) _ Hundreds cheered to welcome Fidel
Castro when he arrived Sunday in Grenada, the Caribbean island that
is the only place where U.S. and Cuban forces battled it out
directly in a bloody Cold War confrontation.
	   Leaving his airplane, Castro clasped his hands over his heart as
the audience began singing a revolutionary hymn, ``Forward march,
forward march against imperialism!'' Some unfurled a gigantic
banner reading in Spanish, ``Long live the ideas of the Cuban
revolution,'' while others waved small Cuban and Grenadian flags.
	   The visit to Grenada _ a former French and British colony of
three islands tucked between Trinidad and St. Vincent _ signals
Castro's renewed acceptance among former foes in the Caribbean and
their frustration with Washington's economic policies.
	   At the airport, Prime Minister Keith Mitchell, once outspoken
against Castro, called the early 1980s when Cuba and the United
States competed for influence on the island a time of ``hatred and
divisiveness.''
	   Castro said it was time for the two countries to put the
invasion behind them.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Legislature to consider plebiscite bill
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Trying to revive a sputtering
effort to clarify Puerto Rico's relationship with the United
States, local lawmakers will begin hearings Monday over a proposed
plebiscite on the island's future.
	   Representatives from the island's justice department and its
three main political parties are to testify before the island's
legislature about a law asking Puerto Ricans to vote for
independence, statehood or continued commonwealth under the control
of the United States.
	   Pro-statehood Gov. Pedro Rossello has been pushing a similar
bill in the U.S. Congress for two years. The U.S. House of
Representatives passed the measure by one vote in March, but Senate
leaders have been reluctant to consider the bill.
	   In a letter made public by a pro-commonwealth group Sunday,
Senate President Trent Lott said he worried the definition of
commonwealth offered to Puerto Ricans weakens islanders' U.S.
citizenship and other rights.
	   In a 1993 plebiscite, Puerto Ricans chose continued commonwealth
over statehood by two percentage points. Independence came in a
distant third.
	   Rossello wants to hold the new vote in December.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Alex dissipates before reaching islands
	   MIAMI (AP) _ Tropical Storm Alex dropped below storm strength
Sunday, degenerating into a weak trough before reaching the Leeward
Islands, forecasters at the United States' National Weather Service
said Sunday.
	   Reports from an Air Force hurricane-chasing plane indicated Alex
no longer has a closed low-level circulation, producing little more
than a few showers and locally gusty winds.
	   Alex still was about 300 miles (480 kilometers) east-northeast
of the northern Leeward Islands when the storm began dissipating,
forecasters said.
	   Forecasters also were watching a large tropical wave about
midway between the Lesser Antilles and the Cape Verde islands
Sunday. The wave was moving west at about 15 mph (25 kph). Slow
development of the wave is possible in the next day or two,
forecasters said, although it has changed little since Saturday.
</TEXT>
