<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia. Some of these stories also moved earlier today as
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Japan, Thailand, South Korea, Myanmar and
separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Sluggish sales have forced Japan's top
semiconductor maker, NEC Corp., to cut capital spending on chip
production by 16.6 percent to 150 billion yen (dlrs 1.03 billion)
this year, the company said Monday.
	   The Tokyo-based NEC will also postpone its scheduled start of a
new domestic chip-manufacturing plant by one year to early 2000, a
company spokesman said.
	   The NEC spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
company will also shelve plans to rationalize its chip-production
lines at domestic plants for the fiscal year, which ends next March
31.
	   NEC originally planned a total of 180 billion yen (dlrs 1.24
billion) in capital spending on chip production.
	   The spokesman said NEC plans to raise output of 64-megabit chips
from the current monthly figure of nearly 8 million to about 10
million by December. NEC originally had planned to boost monthly
production to 15 million chips by mid-1999.
	   But the company said it will sharply slash production of
16-megabit memory chips from 6 million per month to 2 million in
December.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Nissan Motor Co. said Monday that its subsidiary
COMPASSLINK Corp. will start an information service for car
navigation in Japan on Sept. 10.
	   Drivers will use their car navigation systems or digital mobile
telephones to tell operators of the 24-hour service what
information they need. The data will then be transmitted through
mobile phone circuits. Information will include news and weather
forecasts, the company said.
	   The new service will charge a connection fee of 3,500 yen (dlrs
23.10) and a monthly fee of 2,500 yen (dlrs 17.20) per 10 uses,
with each additional 10 uses at 500 yen (dlrs 3.40).
	   COMPASSLINK was established last December with capital of 2
billion yen (dlrs 13.8 million) and is 52 percent owned by Nissan.
	   ___
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The Thai government will announce a
comprehensive package to fix the country's battered banking system
Aug. 15, a senior government official said Monday.
	   Kobsak Chutikul, director-general of the Department of
Information of the Foreign Ministry, said the Finance Ministry and
the Thai central bank would announce the plan to solve problems at
local banks and finance companies.
	   Aug. 15 also marks the first anniversary of Thailand's
acceptance of a dlrs 17.2 billion rescue package from the
International Monetary Fund.
	   Since Thailand's financial crisis erupted in July 1997, the
government has shut down 56 insolvent finance companies and has
taken over seven weak ones. It has also taken over four banks,
writing down their capital to almost zero before appropriating
them.
	   The Bank of Thailand said earlier this year that it might take
action against banks that fail to complete a first round of
mandated capital increases by Aug. 15.
	   Thai banks have been ordered to increase their capital funds
because their reserves dwindled when the country's currency, the
baht, was floated last July and subsequently lost more than 30
percent of its value.
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Battered by Asia's recession, South
Korean exports suffered their largest monthly contraction in 13 1/2
years in July, the government said Monday.
	   And with imports of raw materials for its factories falling, the
nation recorded a dlrs 3.08 billion trade surplus, compared to a
dlrs 837 million deficit in the same month last year.
	   Exports dropped by 13.7 percent from July last year to dlrs 10.2
billion, the third straight and the largest monthly contraction
since January 1985.
	   The Commerce, Industry and Energy Ministry attributed the
contraction to the recession in Asia, one of South Korea's main
export markets, and the appreciation of Korea's currency, which
made its products more expensive.
	   Continuing strikes at the nation's major auto and other
manufacturing plants also helped pull down the export figure, the
ministry said.
	   The nation's imports decreased by 43.7 percent to dlrs 7.12
billion, largely due to sharp drops in international oil prices and
in domestic consumption amid the worst financial crisis in years,
it said.
	   The cumulative trade surplus during the first seven months
reached dlrs 23.13 billion, compared to a deficit of dlrs 9.99
billion for the same period last year.
	   ___
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Myanmar has signed an agreement with an
Indonesian company for an exploration and feasibility study on
developing coal resources in central Myanmar, a government press
release said Monday.
	   Terms of the agreement between the government and PT Austindo
Nusantara Energiwere not disclosed.
	   Oil-rich Indonesia and energy-poor Myanmar are major trading
partners. Myanmar is in desperate need of new sources of energy.
Power outages have become a daily occurrence in the capital,
Yangon.
	   ___
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Two of Malaysia's biggest banks
are lowering their base lending rates following the central bank's
announcement last Friday that it was lowering its intervention rate
to 10.50 percent from around 11.00 percent, effective Monday.
	   Public Bank Bhd. announced over the weekend that beginning
Monday, its base lending rate, or the rate at which it lends to its
best customers, was revised to 12 percent from 12.10 percent.
	   And Bank Bumiputra Malaysia Bhd. is also lowering its BLR to
12.00 percent from 12.10 percent starting Tuesday.	   
</TEXT>
