<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Massacre,0403 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Militants massacre 23 in northern India
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Suspected Kashmiri separatists shot and
killed 23 sleeping construction workers on a remote mountain road
as part of their ongoing battle to free their predominately Muslim
territory from Indian rule, police said Monday.
	   The attack took place farther outside Kashmir than any previous
separatist attack.
	   Initial reports said the laborers from a road-widening project
were asleep Sunday when an unknown number of militants burst into
their shed after midnight and sprayed them with gunfire. Six people
were wounded.
	   The killings took place at Kalaban, 15 kilometers (10 miles)
from the nearest town, Chamba, said Mohinder Kumar, a police
officer reached in Chamba.
	   The mountainous area, 450 kilometers (270 miles) north of the
capital, New Delhi, is in the state of Himachal Pradesh a few miles
(kilometers) across the state border of Jammu-Kashmir, where
militants have become more active.
	   It was the fourth multiple killing attributed to Kashmiri
militants in just over a week. The previous attacks left 20 people
dead and five others wounded.
	   Those killings took place in mountain villages in the Udhampur
district of Kashmir, about 100 kilometers (60 miles) from where
Sunday's massacre took place.
	   Islamic militants are fighting for an independent homeland or
for a merger with India's Islamic neighbor Pakistan. Mainly Hindu
India accuses Pakistan of providing material and men to the
insurgency in Kashmir, India's only Muslim-majority state. Pakistan
says it only gives moral and political support to the movement.
	   The two nations have fought two of their three wars over Kashmir
since they became independent from British rulers in 1947.
	   The separatist insurgency that erupted in 1989 has been centered
in the Kashmir Valley, where most residents are Muslim. Under
pressure from the military, the separatists have been striking more
often in the Hindu-populated area of southern Jammu-Kashmir, said
Major General P.P.S Bindra, the army commander in Udhampur.
	   On Saturday, the military announced a new offensive against the
guerrillas. The army said it would deploy heavy reinforcements
along the disputed border with Pakistan, draft new battalions for
anti-insurgency operations and speed up plans to arm villagers
against insurgents in vulnerable areas, officials said. 	   
</TEXT>
