<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Earthquake </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine town reports widespread but minor damage in strong
</HEADLINE>
quake &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ A strong earthquake caused widespread
but minor damage to buildings and houses, and aftershocks continued
to frighten residents in a central Philippine town, officials said
Monday.
	   No casualties were reported in the magnitude 5.7 quake, which
struck the island province of Masbate at dawn Sunday, knocking
objects off shelves and cutting off power, officials said.
	   The quake was centered at sea about 13 kilometers (8 miles)
northeast of the fishing town of Masbate, and was caused by a
movement in the Philippine Fault, which runs along the country's
eastern coast, seismologists said.
	   A Masbate town official said an initial inspection showed some
buildings, including some schools and many houses, had developed
cracks, and a few may have to be declared unsafe. A slab of cement
fell from a building during the quake but no one was hurt, another
official said.
	   Officials said bridges and other public works would also be
inspected.
	   An official of the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and
Seismology in Masbate town said eight aftershocks followed the
earthquake Sunday and three more occurred Monday, causing a deluge
of calls to her office from alarmed town residents.
	   The Philippines is located in one of the most earthquake-prone
regions in the world.	   
</TEXT>
