w2280 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKorea-Rain 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Rain, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll from floods rises to 52; about 50 still missing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES death toll to 52, ADDS details &QL; 
 &UR; By SANG-HUN CHOE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Fresh rains turned mountain streams
into raging torrents Monday, hampering the search for 50 people
known missing in floods in South Korea. The death toll rose to 52
as more bodies were recovered.
	   As rescuers probed downstream river bottoms, they confronted
grim scenes from South Korea's worst natural disaster in years:
Three children trapped and killed in a submerged car; the bodies of
a grandmother and a 7-year-old boy tangled in flood debris.
	   President Kim Dae-jung urged 42,000 soldiers, police and
firefighters to step up their search and rescue efforts, and
praised them for heroism.
	   One firefighter was critically injured Monday when a helicopter
heading for the disaster scene was buffeted by a sudden rain shower
and crashed in a rice paddy. Another rescuer drowned Sunday after
jumping into a surging stream to save others.
	   Relief operations centered around scenic Mount Chiri National
Park, where all but eight of the dead and missing were lost or
stranded by floods triggered by heavy rains Saturday.
	   Rescuers, aided by helicopters, cranes and other heavy
machinery, cleared a path through landslides and reached deeper
into the park, where dozens of campers were still believed
stranded. They later used ropes and pulleys to bring 35 college
students across raging torrents to safety.
	   Officials expected the number of deaths to rise as more families
reported missing relatives.
	   ``Many people call to report missing people. But we don't count
all of them in our list because some families don't know where
their relatives went on vacation,'' said Lim Jae-woon, a Home
Ministry official.
	   A front moving east from China dumped up to 30 centimeters (12
inches) of rain in less than three hours early Saturday, engulfing
hundreds of sleeping campers in flash floods in the park 220
kilometers (135 miles) south of Seoul.
	   Police said whole families camping along normally placid streams
were swept away. Some bodies were found washed up on coastal
beaches 100 kilometers (62 miles) away, raising fears that many of
the missing will never be found.
	   ``We are expanding our search further downstream, but our
operations are slow because of occasional heavy rains. Upstream,
it's almost impossible to venture into those wild streams,'' said
Kwon Ki-hwan, an official at the government's Disaster Relief
Headquarters.
	   TV footage showed flood-swept camping sites littered with
crumpled tents, overturned cars and other debris. Family members
searched hospital morgues for missing relatives.
	   Local news media were filled with harrowing tales from
survivors. A father disappeared under floodwaters after helping his
7-year-old son cling for hours to a tree branch while friends
worked feverishly to build a makeshift bridge to the pair. The son
was saved.
	   Another man pulled two children from a flooded ravine, then was
swept away himself by the swirling waters.
	   As of Monday, 1,600 marooned people had been rescued from the
national park, police said.
	   Also Monday, President Kim ordered the Cabinet to revamp the
nation's disaster warning system. Saturday's rains had not been
forecast by the National Weather Service.
	   The downpours submerged homes and farmland, washed away roads
and triggered landslides. As communications with remote areas were
restored, property damage estimates climbed to dlrs 60 million
Monday.	   
</TEXT>
