<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Economic Plan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai government approves 25 measures to stimulate economy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The Thai government approved 25
measures Monday to stimulate the economy and stop its steady slide
into recession despite billions of dollars in bailout money from
the International Monetary Fund.
	   The unveiling of the package came on the first day of talks with
an IMF team visiting Bangkok for a quarterly review of its rescue
program.
	   Thailand is in the midst of its worst economic crisis in modern
times.
	   The measures approved Monday include pumping dlrs 600 million
into the agricultural sector, spending dlrs 122 million to
restructure the country's manufacturing base and allowing the
government to run a deficit equivalent to 3.5 percent of gross
domestic product.
	   The Finance Ministry will be responsible for obtaining funding
from bond issues or international agencies for many of the
projects.
	   More than 60 percent of Thais work in agriculture, and the
government is counting on the sector to soak up workers laid off in
construction and manufacturing. Unemployment is expected to climb
to 2.8 million from around 1 million last year.
	   It was burgeoning manufacturing relying on cheap labor that
fueled Thailand's 1985-95 economic boom. The manufacturing package
is designed to improve production efficiency and the skills of Thai
labor, develop small- and medium-scale industry, and relocate
industrial plants from Bangkok to the provinces to improve wealth
distribution.
	   Thailand's boom went bust when the central bank depleted foreign
reserves in a failed defense of the country's currency, the baht,
which lost more than 30 percent of its value after being floated in
July 1997.
	   The baht float also triggered attacks on other Asian currencies,
and economic problems roiled across the continent, deeply affecting
Indonesia and South Korea.
	   All three hardest-hit nations were forced to seek IMF bailouts.
	   Although the government of Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has
adhered to the austerity measures required by the IMF package,
Thailand's economy has yet to rebound.
	   Government Spokesman Akapol Sorasuchart said the government will
be allowed to run a budget deficit equivalent to 1.5 percent of
GDP, while the state enterprise investment budget will be in
deficit up to 2 percent.
	   Although the IMF had demanded that Thailand post a budget
surplus of 1 percent of GDP, the agency has relaxed its
requirements.
	   The IMF agreed that it was time to stimulate the economy after
the baht stabilized at around 40-42 to the dollar during the second
quarter of 1998, and the economy was sinking more deeply into
recession than anticipated.
	   An IMF projection for a 1998 contraction in GDP of 4 to 5.5
percent is expected to be revised toward 6-7 percent.
	   The Finance Ministry also said Monday it will make public a
rescue plan for the banking and finance sector on Aug. 15.
	   Four Thai banks have been taken over by the government and 56
insolvent finance companies shut down in the wake of the economic
crisis.	   
</TEXT>
