w2300 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serbs press attacks in Kosovo after vowing that offensive is over
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with Serbs reportedly overrunning another KLA
village; Albanians reporting continued fighting; TRIMS outdated
material; no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Government forces overran another
ethnic Albanian stronghold Monday and pressed their attacks
elsewhere in Kosovo despite Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
pledge that the offensive was over.
	   Serb military sources said police entered Smonica early Monday
after shelling the village near the Albanian border for days. The
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at least a dozen
Kovoso Liberation Army fighters were killed.
	   Serb sources also said troops continued Monday to lay siege to
another border village, Junik. Independent media in the Yugoslav
capital Belgrade said most KLA fighters had slipped out of the
village for sanctuaries in nearby Albania, leaving a few dozen
insurgents who have encircled their positions with land mines.
	   The reports could not be independently confirmed. But Albanian
sources said fighting was continuing Monday in at least three areas
of the rebellious province, scenes of heavy clashes during the
weekend.
	   During the weekend, government forces systematically targeted
homes of Albanian civilians, driving them away by gunfire and then
torching and looting the abandoned dwellings.
	   The campaign to drive Albanian civilians from their homes is
reminiscent of ``ethnic cleansing'' _ the forcible removal of rival
ethnic groups that marked conflicts in the former Yugoslav
republics of Bosnia and Croatia earlier this decade.
	   On Sunday, the KLA said Serb police shelled about 13 ethnic
Albanian villages in the Drenica region west of Pristina, forcing
civilians to flee for their lives and then setting their houses on
fire.
	   Eight Albanians were reported killed, the Albanian-run Kosovo
Information Center said Sunday. Serb sources said two policemen
were killed and two others wounded in fighting at Prilep near the
Albanian border.
	   Witnesses said police used 20-millimeter antiaircraft guns to
fire on Albanian houses in the Prilep fighting.
	   The clashes occurred just three days after Milosevic told a
European Union delegation that the offensive, which began July 24,
was over. He later assured U.S. envoy Christopher Hill that tens of
thousands of ethnic Albanians displaced by the fighting could
return to their homes and international relief organizations could
assist them.
	   But in Albania's capital, Tirana, a Kosovo Albanian party
courted by the United States accused the Serb-led Yugoslav
government of trying ``to make it impossible for thousands of
Albanians to return to their homes.''
	   The statement was issued by the Albanian Democratic Movement,
whose leader, Mehmet Hajrizi, has been mentioned as a key figure in
a planned Albanian team that U.S. diplomats hope can negotiate the
future of the majority Albanian province with Milosevic.
	   Milosevic has promised to restore Kosovo's autonomy, which he
canceled in 1989. But he and major world powers oppose independence
for Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs in the province
by 9-to-1.
	   Kosovo is located in southern Serbia, the dominant of two
republics that make up the remainder of Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and European nations fear independence could
lead to demands by Albanian-speaking communities in Macedonia and
Yugoslavia's other republic, Montenegro, to establish a ``Greater
Albania'' in the southern Balkans.
	   KLA leaders are expected to announce this week whether they will
accept a U.S. plan for Albanian politicians to enter peace talks
with Milosevic. The current Serb offensive appears designed to
deliver a strong blow against the rebels and force them to
negotiate from a position of weakness.
	   In a lengthy commentary Sunday, the government's Tanjug news
agency said the ``efficient action'' by Serb forces had ``almost
entirely broken down terrorist gangs of the so-called Liberation
Army of Kosovo.''
</TEXT>
