w2304 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Election 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodia's election committee to recount some results
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to qualify with `said' in 1st graf; UPDATES with
Ranariddh's remarks; substitutes `districts' for `constituencies'
thruout for clarity; substitutes `announced' for `estimated,' 13th
graf; ADDS specific attribution for comments on seat allocation;
edits thruout &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By GRANT PECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Responding to opposition complaints,
Cambodia's election commission said Monday it had agreed to recount
votes from certain areas in last week's general election.
	   But the procedure still had not begun 1 1/2 hours after it was
scheduled, with no explanation for the delay.
	   It was not even clear whether there would be an actual recount
of votes, or merely a reconciliation of locally compiled tallies
with provincial totals announced by the National Election
Committee.
	   A reconciliation would be unlikely to satisfy opposition demands
for votes to be recounted from areas where it had alleged fraud in
voting or ballot-counting.
	   As of Monday afternoon, preliminary totals for half of the
country's 23 electoral districts had yet to be released.
	   Results announced so far for 11 provinces show Co-Premier Hun
Sen's Cambodian People's Party leading in all but three of them.
	   One of the two districts captured by the opposition FUNCINPEC
party was the central province of Kampong Cham, the country's
biggest constituency, with 18 of the National Assembly's 122 seats.
	   FUNCINPEC leader Prince Norodom Ranariddh said Monday that an
offer by Hun Sen _ the apparent winner of the July 26 election _ to
form a coalition government would not be considered until after
ballots in disputed areas were recounted.
	   ``We have to wait for the final decision because counting and
recounting are delayed. It's better to wait a few more days,''
Ranariddh said after returning from a weekend trip to Bangkok,
Thailand.
	   Ranariddh, who was ousted by Hun Sen as the country's co-premier
in a coup last year, denied rumors that members of his party had
already met with Hun Sen's party to discuss the proposed
partnership.
	   Over the weekend, Hun Sen called for the speedy formation of a
new government so Cambodia would win back its seat at the United
Nations.
	   The seat has remained vacant since last year's coup.
	   The National Election Committee has not yet announced how votes
won by the parties would translate into parliamentary seats. But a
projection by the Committee for Free and Fair Elections in
Cambodia, an independent election monitoring group, gives the
Cambodian People's Party 64 seats, FUNCINPEC 43 and the Sam Rainsy
Party 15.
	   A spokesman for the committee said Monday he hoped preliminary
tallies would be completed for all districts Tuesday or Wednesday,
but that the committee had not yet received all documentation from
two provinces, Battambang and Rattanakiri.
	   The spokesman, Im Suordei, also defended the committee's
decision to change the formula for allocating parliamentary seats
based on the vote, saying that it was approved and circulated well
before the election.
	   The change in formula, which was not widely publicized until
late last week, favors the top vote-getting party in any particular
province.
	   In practice, this would work to the advantage of the ruling
party, and is significant because it could provide that party with
enough extra seats _ over the original formula _ to attain a
parliamentary majority.
	   Im Suordei did not explain why the change had been made, other
than to say the allocation was ``done in the highest mathematical
way, a very scientific one.''
	   There was no ``political intention, it is technical work,'' he
said.
	   The election was held one year after Hun Sen ousted Ranariddh as
his co-premier in a violent coup, shattering a tense dual
premiership formed after the U.N.-sponsored elections in 1993.
	   The opposition parties have asked for a recount in areas where
they suspect irregularities.
	   They also asked that new votes be taken in disputed precincts if
their charges of wrongdoing were found valid, and threatened to
boycott the National Assembly if their complaints were not heeded.
	   Without the opposition's attendance, the assembly is unlikely to
have present the two-thirds of its 122 members needed to conduct
any major business.
	   Hun Sen responded by inviting the opposition to join a coalition
government, but warning that if they carried out their threat not
to attend the assembly, he could lower the constitutional minimum
for the assembly to meet and confirm a government from two-thirds
to 50 percent plus one. He also said his current government could
simply remain in power.	   
</TEXT>
