<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Crime </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police report increase of crime in Singapore
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Crime increased in Singapore in the first half
of the year, continuing a worsening trend in the affluent, tightly
run island republic that has prided itself on low crime and safe
streets, television reported Monday.
	   The report, citing official statistics, said the biggest
increase came in violent crime, with 12 more murders in
January-June than in the same period last year, while rape jumped
by 30 percent.
	   The worsening trend in violent crime trend began last year. In
1997, the number of murders jumped by 23 percent, to 38 cases from
31 the previous year. The number of rape cases rose by 4 percent,
from 99 to 103.
	   Only 15 murders and 61 rapes committed in 1997 were solved.
	   Housebreaking, car theft and robbery have marginally increased
between January and June 1998.
	   Police are focusing on the crimes that have significantly
increased, officer Khoo Boon Hui was quoted as saying.	   
</TEXT>
