<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Butler meets Iraqi officials on weapons inspections
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Aziz criticism of Butler, PIKS UP As usual, 16th
graf. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing &QL; 
 &UR; By WAIEL FALEH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ An Iraqi official on Monday accused chief
U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler of ``serving the American
policy'' by trying to prolong punishing trade sanctions on Iraq.
	   Using unusually harsh language, Iraq's deputy prime minister,
Tariq Aziz, told reporters after a three-hour session with Butler
that the U.N. Special Commission was ``back to its old games, to
its old tricks.''
	   The commission, which Butler heads, is responsible for ensuring
that Iraq has eliminated its weapons of mass destruction, as
required by U.N. resolutions that ended the 1991 Gulf War.
	   The U.N. Security Council has said that trade sanctions _
including a ban on air travel and limits on the sale of oil _ will
not be lifted until the commission ensures the weaponry has been
destroyed.
	   Aziz accused Butler's team of ignoring the country's headway in
eliminating its weaponry and, instead, focusing on ``minor issues
which make no sense from the angle of disarmament.''
	   He concluded: ``Since this is the wish of the American
administration to perpetuate the situation, to prolong the current
situation, to keep the sanctions on the people of Iraq .... as long
as this is the American wish, you (Butler) are serving the American
policy.''
	   Butler did not hear Aziz's remarks and, when asked about them,
said only that ``work is in progress.''
	   On Sunday, Butler had told reporters: ``Our steadfast aim is to
get this done as soon as possible to get to the end of the
disarmament phase so the Security Council can consider the
sanctions issue.''
	   The two sides were to meet again later Monday for further talks.
	   Neither Aziz or Butler gave specifics on what was discussed at
the morning session, but the ``blueprint'' Butler presented the
Iraqis during his last visit in June calls for further disclosures
about the country's missile program as well as biological and
chemical weaponry.
	   Aziz repeated Iraq's earlier contention that Iraq ``does not
have any weapons of mass destruction.''
	   Aziz is under pressure to produce results during the current
talks, which are to conclude Wednesday.
	   Last month, Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein said in a nationally
televised speech that the sanctions must be lifted this year -- the
first time he had set a deadline. That statement later was endorsed
by the Revolutionary Command Council, which is Iraq's collective
leadership.
	   Iraq's Parliament was to meet Monday to discuss the weapons
inspections and sanctions but delayed the special session until
Thursday to discuss the results of Butler's visit, Parliament
officials said.
	   Iraq says the sanctions have caused widespread suffering among
its 22 million people.
	   As usual, Iraqi newspapers excoriated Butler in their editorials
on Monday.
	   Al-Thawra, the newspaper of Saddam's ruling Baath party, said
Butler was no longer the representative of an international
organization but ``a man who implements American policies against
Iraq.''
	   Iraq has long accused the United States and Britain of
needlessly prolonging the trade sanctions.
	   Al-Thawra accused the United States of ``igniting a series of
dangerous crises,'' including a standoff earlier this year over
Iraq's refusal to open presidential sites to U.N. inspectors.
	   The United States and Britain sent warplanes and ships to the
Gulf, threatening military action to force Iraq to cooperate. The
crisis was defused in a February agreement negotiated by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
	   The paper called Butler's commission ``not credible'' and
accused him of making statements in Iraq suggesting there was
progress in disarmament, then telling the U.N. Security Council
there were problems.
	   The state-run Al-Jumhuriya repeated allegations that depleted
uranium warheads used by U.S. forces in the Gulf War had poisoned
Iraq's environment. The government says the chemicals have
contributed to birth defects and higher rates of cancer.
	   In an unusual claim, it also accused the Americans of trying to
sabotage Iraq's grain output with rodents.
	   ``Iraqis noticed an unusual increase of mice and rats in Iraq,
which led them to think that this is (the result of) an organized
operation by a foreign side, represented by the American officers
and spies working at the Special Commission,'' Al-Jumhuriya said.
	   It termed the pest problem ``biological warfare'' against Iraq.
 &UR; wf-eap
</TEXT>
