<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gunfire rings though Kinshasa army barracks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS details of rumors of a Rwandan-led coup against Kabila;
quotes from former finance minister. ADDS byline. Edits throughout.
No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By KAMANGA MUTOND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Gunfire and rumors echoed through Congo's
capital of Kinshasa early Monday morning as rival soldiers clashed
in a military barracks and the government ordered the population
off the streets.
	   The sound of gunfire could be heard from Camp Kokolo military
base on Kinshasa's west side. It was not immediately clear who was
fighting, although tensions have been escalating in recent days
between troops loyal to President Laurent Kabila and his one-time
Rwandan allies.
	   Kabila last week ordered all Rwandan soldiers out of his
country, but did not elaborate on the reason. Rwandan troops played
an important role last year in helping Kabila oust longtime
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   The country's finance minister, who was arrested last week and
then released, said he was questioned about whether Rwandan
soldiers still in Kinshasa had been planning a coup against Kabila.
	   ``I was questioned about rumors of a putsch attempt,'' said
former Finance Minister Ferdinand Tala-Ngai.
	   Kabila has been growing anxious about the presence of Rwandan
forces in Kinshasa and weeks before ordering them to leave he
increased security around government buildings.
	   Tanks were deployed in front of the presidential residence and
office compound while troops were stationed at key ministry
buildings.
	   The sound of fighting Monday triggered an order by the
government to clear the streets.
	   ``The government asks the people of Congo and those foreigners
here in the country to stay calm and to stay at home until order is
restored,'' said an abrupt announcement Monday morning on
state-controlled People's Radio. ``Stay at home just until that
time when the armed forces of Congo reestablish civil order.''
	   Shops throughout the capital remained closed Monday morning and
people who had headed downtown for work early in the morning were
quickly returning home.
	   Speculation was rife over the stability of Kabila's government
after weeks of growing tension between the president, his top
advisers and what now appears to be a shaky military alliance with
neighboring Rwanda.
	   In eastern Congo, meanwhile, a spokesman for a breakaway ethnic
group urged the people to oust Kabila.
	   ``We've taken the decision to no longer recognize the government
of Laurent Kabila,'' said the spokesman, who identified himself
only as Andre. ``We don't want to separate from Congo, but Kabila
must be removed from power.''
	   In a statement delivered to The Associated Press and the Voice
of America, Andre said his group, representing Banyamulenge ethnic
Tutsis, was in control of most of Kivu province.
	   Kivu has been the scene of ongoing unrest for months.
 &UR; (km/ids)
</TEXT>
