<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kyrgyzstan-Anthrax </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nine cases of anthrax in Kyrgyzstan, village quarantined
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Nine villagers from southern Kyrgyzstan have been
hospitalized with anthrax, and their village has been quarantined,
the Interfax news agency reported Monday.
	   The Emergencies Ministry of the former Soviet republic said that
some 300 other residents of a village in the Jalal-Abad region of
the Central Asian country had eaten contaminated beef, Interfax
reported.
	   The bacteria that causes anthrax is common among domesticated
livestock and can be transferred to humans. When it infects, the
bacteria produces a toxin, or poison, that attacks cells.
	   Thorough cooking is believed to kill the bacteria.
	   (ji/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
