<HEADER>
w2343 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-SilkAirCras 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-SilkAir Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: SilkAir crash investigation to continue for 6 more
</HEADLINE>
months &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with investigation team's report, RECASTS throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The Indonesian-led team investigating the
SilkAir crash in Indonesia last December said Monday it has found
``no indication that air traffic control, weather or maintenance
was a factor in the accident.''
	   Other aspects of investigation, including the examination of
human factors, are continuing, the team said in a statement. It
added that the investigation is likely to continue for the next six
to eight months.
	   Last Dec. 19, a SilkAir Boeing 737-300 mysteriously dropped from
the sky into the Musi River in the Sumatran jungle, killing all 104
people aboard. SilkAir is a subsidiary of the flag carrier
Singapore Airlines.
	   Supporting a theory that the crash of flight MI 185 may have
been a case of pilot suicide, The Asian Wall Street Journal last
week cited the debt-ridden captain's last-minute life insurance
policy and his tampering with a cockpit tape to hide a previous
flying error.
	   The investigation team said its Human Factors Group still was
``acquiring factual information for the study of the background of
the flight crew members, their professional proficiencies, their
career, private lives, and their actions and interactions before
and during the accident flight. This will continue for the next two
to three months.''
	   It said that ``numerous rumors about the cause of the MI 185
accident ... are all speculation. The investigation team is still
trying to determine the cause or causes of the accident.''
	   Besides Indonesian officials, the team includes representatives
of Singapore Airlines and Boeing.
	   The investigation remains unaffected by the economic crisis in
Indonesia, the statement said.
	   Earlier Monday, Singapore Communications Minister Mah Bow Tan
also said the investigation would take at least six more months.
	   Mah was asked in Parliament to comment on the Asian Wall Street
Journal story last week listing pilot suicide as a likely cause of
the crash, but the question was ruled out of order before the
minister answered.	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Singapore-SilkAir Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
