</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Gay Games Firing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Managing director of Gay Games dismissed for overspending
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Just as the 1998 Gay Games got
under way, the managing director of the event was dismissed for
overspending.
	   The board of directors for the quadrennial Olympics-style
homosexual sports and cultural festival issued a terse statement
Monday, saying it had ``revoked the mandate'' of Dutchman Marc
Janssens on Sunday, the day after the opening ceremonies.
	   ``The reason is that Mr. Janssens made commitments outside the
approved budget, commitments that were also bigger than his
authority,'' the statement said. It did not elaborate.
	   ``We have no overview of the complete situation,'' said Games
spokesman Paul van Yperen, adding the directors are still
investigating the extend of the financial problem.
	   The Gay Games, which began on Saturday and runs through Aug. 8,
is expected to attract 15,000 participants and 200,000 visitors
from 66 countries.
	   The event is costing 14 million guilders (dlrs 7 million), but
organizers have received 3 million guilders (dlrs 1.5 million) in
government subsidies.
	   Another 3 millions guilders (dlrs 1.5 million) also came from
heavyweight corporate sponsors such as KLM Royal Dutch Airlines and
Kodak.
	   (jc/bk)
</TEXT>
