<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Obit-China-Luo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Luo Jingyi, Stanford student, clandestine Communist, dies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Luo Jingyi, a former Stanford University student
who worked as an underground agent for China's Communist Party and
rose to the top ranks of the nation's security agency, has died at
age 93, state media said Monday.
	   Luo, who was from Shanghai and studied at Stanford in 1925, died
of illness July 27 in Beijing and was cremated Friday at a cemetery
for venerated revolutionaries on the city's outskirts, the Xinhua
News Agency said.
	   Luo also studied in Moscow and, after returning to China, did
clandestine work for the Communist Party for 13 years until it
seized power in 1949, Xinhua said without providing details.
	   After the Communist takeover, Luo worked in foreign trade and
other fields and rose to vice ministerial rank in the Ministry of
State Security before retiring in 1983, Xinhua said.
	   It did not give details about Luo's work in the Security
Ministry, China's equivalent of the KGB in the former Soviet Union.	   
</TEXT>
