w2352 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-TimorBook     08-03 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Timor Book </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian troops in East Timor now carrying human rights booklets
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Indonesia-East Timor &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Long accused of abuses, Indonesian
soldiers in East Timor are carrying a new aid: booklets that tell
how to respect human rights.
	   The 12-page publication forbids rape and torture and requires
soldiers to protect civilians, said Lt. Col. Supadi, military chief
of staff in the former Portuguese colony.
	   The book, which is being distributed to the 11,000 Indonesian
soldiers in East Timor, is based on U.N. guidelines on human
rights.
	   International rights groups say the Indonesian military, which
invaded East Timor in 1975, has committed widespread abuses while
seeking to quell separatist rebels and their civilian sympathizers.
	   Tens of thousands of people died in fighting and of disease and
famine in the years following the invasion and 1976 annexation,
which has not been recognized by the United Nations.
	   New President B.J. Habibie has pledged democratic reform and has
offered autonomy for East Timor, ruling out the desire of many
activists there: a vote on independence.
	   Talks on East Timor are scheduled Tuesday and Wednesday at U.N.
headquarters in New York. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the
foreign ministers of Indonesia and Portugal are taking part.
	   It is not the first time that the Indonesian military has
distributed human rights booklets. Soldiers in the eastern province
of Irian Jaya, also home to a small band of separatist rebels, were
given the publications last year.	   
</TEXT>
