<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Rebel Attack </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Radio: rebels attack second mining town, 20 killed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HENRY WASSWA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ Rebels based in eastern Congo have
attacked a second mining town in western Uganda, killing 20 people,
an independent radio station said Monday.
	   Central Broadcasting Service (CBS) said Allied Democratic Forces
rebels struck an army post and a police station in Kilembe, 400
kilometers (248 miles) west of Kampala Sunday afternoon.
	   It was not immediately possible to contact the Ugandan army
spokesman for confirmation.
	   On Saturday, ADF rebels attacked Kasese, 20 kilometers (12
miles) east of Kilembe, setting fire to two hotels and 20 vehicles.
The army says eight died in the attack, but newspapers and radio
stations put the death toll at as many as 17.
	   The Alliance of Democratic Forces is made up of remnants of the
former Ugandan army which was defeated by President Yoweri
Museveni's guerrilla forces in 1986. Analysts say the rebels come
from several tribes but say the ADF is dominated by members of a
Muslim missionary movement known as Jamiat al-Tabliq.
	   But Tabliq movement leaders in Kampala on Sunday distanced
themselves from armed rebellion.
	   There have also been reports that some members of the army of
the former Zaire (now Congo) and the former Rwandan Hutu army have
joined the ADF, which has bases in the foothills of the Rwanzori
Mountains and also in Congo.
	   It is not known whether the ADF has a formal ideology, other
than wanting to destabilize Museveni's government. They are
believed to receive arms and supplies from the Islamic Front
government in neighboring Sudan.
	   Until the Kasese attack, the rebels hit isolated civilian
targets in rural areas. Two months ago they set fire to a technical
training school outside Fort Portal, 50 kilometers (30 miles) north
of Kasese, killing at least 80 students and carrying off about 100
others.
	   (hw/sl)	   
</TEXT>
