<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Myanmar-Gas Pipeline </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gas flowing from Myanmar to Thailand through pipeline
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Natural gas from Myanmar is already
flowing to Thailand through a controversial dlrs 1.2 billion
pipeline, the Petroleum Authority of Thailand said Monday.
	   Gas started entering the Thai section of the pipeline last
Thursday, a PTT spokesman said, but hasn't yet reached the power
station in Ratchaburi, 95 kilometers (59 miles) west of Bangkok,
where it will be converted into energy.
	   That will take about seven days if all goes well, he said. The
gas is being permitted to flow in more sections of the
240-kilometer (148-mile) Thai portion of the pipeline each day so
PTT officials can make sure there are no leaks or other problems.
	   The pipeline is owned by Total of France, Unocal of the United
States, Myanmar's military government and PTT.
	   Thai environmentalists have protested against the pipeline,
saying its construction has damaged rain forests and displaced
wildlife, including elephants, the national symbol of Thailand.
	   Democracy and human rights activists have charged that its
profits will fund Myanmar's military regime, which, although in
poor financial shape, spends more than half its budget on weapons
while suppressing the country's democracy movement and ethnic
minorities.
	   They have also charged that the Myanmar military used forced
labor to build infrastructure for the project.
	   Although all parties in the consortium deny the charge, Myanmar
citizens have testified in a U.S. court that they were used as
forced labor to build pipeline infrastructure.
	   The consortium has spent several million dollars on social
welfare projects along the Myanmar section of the pipeline route to
improve the lives of people in the area.	   
</TEXT>
