</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Jehovah's Witness </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore Jehovah's Witness sues to get job back
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ A Jehovah's Witness, dismissed from his tenured
teaching job for refusing to sing the national anthem and recite
the national pledge, went to court Monday to get his job back,
citing constitutional protection of individuals to practice their
faith.
	   During the first day of trial in his civil suit against the
vocational institute that employed him to teach English and
mathematics, Peter Nappalli, 37, hesitated several times to answer
questions that would identify acquaintances as Jehovah's Witnesses,
a denomination banned in 1972.
	   The Jehovah's Witness version of the Bible and other literature
is banned, proselytizing is prohibited, and police are permitted to
raid homes to break up Bible studies of three or more people.
	   It is legal for individuals to be Jehovah's Witnesses, under a
constitutional clause guaranteeing the right to profess and
practice religion.
	   But there are many restrictions under other laws in Singapore,
where the ruling party, fearful of any religious or racial
disharmony, propagates a nationalist ideology that leaves little
room for dissent.
	   Jehovah's Witness adherents such as Nappalli run into trouble
when they obey the tenets of their faith by refusing to do military
service, pledge allegiance to the national flag or sing the
national anthem.
	   Nappalli, who had served a three-year prison term for refusing
the national service required of all Singaporean males, lost his
teaching job after 10 years when the school began enforcing a
requirement for students and faculty to recite the pledge and sing
the anthem at daily assemblies.
	   Asked why he had ever applied for a teaching job, when he knew
this was a requirement, Nappalli said that in 1984 Jehovah's
Witnesses were not being dismissed for refusing to comply with
those rituals.
	   ``I was protected by a higher law: the constitution,'' Nappalli
answered. ``As a citizen of Singapore I believed the constitution
would balance out that situation.''
	   In fact, Nappalli testified that during the 1,600 assemblies he
attended, most of those around him did not sing out loud or recite
the pledge.
	   ``The taped music was louder than anything anyone was singing,''
he said. He said the students _ aged 14 to 20 _ only started
reciting the pledge en masse in 1988, when a new code required them
to place clenched fists over their hearts as they spoke.
	   Nappalli stood silently during the assemblies. But in 1991, he
was warned of disciplinary action if he did not begin singing and
reciting the pledge. Three years later he was fired.
	   The Institute of Technical Educations argued in court documents
that review boards were never told of Nappalli's refusal to recite
the pledge and sing the anthem, and therefore continued to promote
him. The institute said his failure to participate set a bad
example to students and breached discipline.
	   In a 2 1/2-hour opening cross-examination, the institute's
attorney, Tang Khin Wei, brought out Nappalli's admission that when
he applied for the teaching post he answered ``no'' when asked if
he had ever served time in prison.
	   Nappalli said he thought the question applied to a criminal
offense.
	   More than 30 members of the public, many of them Jehovah's
Witnesses, filled the courtroom. The audience gasped at one point
when Tang asked Nappalli directly if a woman who had recommended
him for the teaching job was a Jehovah's Witness.
	   Nappalli said the lawyer needed to ask her.
	   Later, he was asked how many working teachers he knew of were
Jehovah's Witnesses who did not recite the pledge or sing the
anthem. Nappalli gave an indirect answer, and his attorney objected
to the question, as well as another asking what Nappalli did as a
Jehovah's Witness. Some of the common practices, such as going
door-to-door to share their faith, are illegal in Singapore,
although Nappalli admitted he does that.
	   Nappalli, who supports his wife and children as a tutor, is
suing for reinstatement to his job, back pay and annual raises and
bonuses, and compensation for denial of his constitutional rights.
	   Testimony was expected to last until Friday.	   
</TEXT>
