<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Inflation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Inflation soars in crisis-ridden Indonesia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Dramatic rises in basic food prices
have pushed up the inflation rate in crisis-ridden Indonesia to
almost 60 percent in this year's first seven months, a government
official said Monday.
	   Dow Jones Newswires quoted the official as saying the consumer
price index rose 8.56 percent in July from June, compared with an
increase of 4.64 percent in June from May.
	   The inflation rate for the first seven months of the year
reached an estimated 59.1 percent, he said.
	   Speaking on condition of anonymity, the official said sharp
price increases for rice, cooking oil, wheat flour and spices were
to blame.
	   The Indonesian government forecasts inflation at 80 percent by
the end of the year.
	   Indonesia is enduring its worst economic crisis in 30 years.
	   The value of the rupiah has plunged, unemployment is growing
fast and the economy is in deep recession.
	   On Sunday, the newspaper Kompas quoted President B.J. Habibie as
saying the government would need three years to restore economic
growth.
	   Habibie took power after his autocratic predecessor Suharto quit
May 21 amid widespread student-led protests against his 32-year
authoritarian rule.
	   Habibie has pledged to carry out painful economic changes
required under a dlrs 43 billion International Monetary Fund rescue
plan.
	   He has also promised to make sweeping political reforms and to
hold elections in 1999.	   
</TEXT>
