r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-Corruption     08-03 0225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Corruption,0225 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indian prime minister introduces tough anti-corruption bill
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NEELESH MISRA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
introduced a tough anti-corruption bill Monday creating a watchdog
agency with sweeping powers to clean up India's scandal-ridden
politics.
	   The bill to set up the three-person office of the Lok Pal, or
Keeper of the People, provides for a chairperson and two other
judges with unprecedented authority to probe allegations of
corruption against government officials, members of Parliament and
Cabinet members, including the prime minister.
	   Sources in India's Supreme Court said former Chief Justice
Jagdish Sharan Verma, noted for his tough stand on corruption
issues, was likely to be made the first Lok Pal.
	   The three members would be appointed by India's president _ a
largely ceremonial position _ on the recommendation of a panel of
government and Parliament leaders. They can be removed by the
president only for proven misconduct after an independent inquiry
by the chief justice.
	   Several top political leaders, including former Prime Minister
P.V. Narasimha Rao, are currently under indictment on corruption
charges. Other powerful figures are implicated in some of the
biggest corruption scandals in the country's history. 	   
</TEXT>
