<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gunfire rings though Kinshasa army barracks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS fighting in second barracks; UPDATES with Rwandan troops
apparently in hiding near Kinshasa; army erects roadblocks into the
city. Pickup 4th graf pvs, `The country's ...' &QL; 
 &UR; By KAMANGA MUTOND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Gunfire and rumors echoed through Congo's
capital of Kinshasa early Monday morning as rival soldiers clashed
in a military barracks and a nearby base while the government
ordered the population off the streets.
	   The sound of gunfire could be heard from Camp Kokolo military
base and the Tshatshi barracks on Kinshasa's west side.
	   The clashes apparently involved troops loyal to President
Laurent Kabila and his one-time Rwandan allies. The fighting comes
amid growing suspicions within Kabila's government that the Rwandan
troops had been plotting against the regime.
	   Kabila last week ordered all Rwandan soldiers out of his
country, but did not elaborate on the reason.
	   Although Rwandan troops played an important role last year in
helping Kabila oust longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, relations
between the central African countries have soured in recent months.
	   According to a defense ministry official, more than 1,000
Rwandan Tutsi soldiers fled the Kokolo base and are hiding in a
forest just outside of Kinshasa.
	   Kabila's loyalist troops have erected roadblocks in Kinshasa and
are searching for the renegade Rwandans, said the defense ministry
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   The government forces have been given orders to kill the Rwandan
soldiers, the official said.
