<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 killed, 20 wounded in latest massacre
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Armed men in military fatigues stopped a
bus at a fake roadblock, then slit the throats of passengers and
the driver, hospital officials said Monday. Ten people were killed
and 20 wounded.
	   The attack Sunday afternoon took place near Saida, 400
kilometers (250 miles) southwest of the capital, Algiers.
	   When the armed group signaled the bus to stop, the suspicious
driver speeded up instead, but was forced off the road by a volley
of machine-gun fire. Once the bus was stopped, the attackers moved
in, slitting the throats of some passengers.
	   An official source in Saida, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the attackers were later caught.
	   They weren't identified, but such attacks are usually blamed on
Islamic militants waging a violent insurgency against the
military-backed government.
	   A U.N. panel, led by former Portuguese President Mario Soares,
is currently in Algeria to look into the massacres and bombings
that have killed an estimated 75,000 people since the insurgency
began.
	   The insurgency was sparked in 1992 after the government canceled
parliamentary elections an Islamic party was set to win.
	   (jn-parf) 	   
</TEXT>
