w2414 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Election-Abu     08-03 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election-Abuses </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian fearful of revenge not assured by strongman's appeal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBIN McDOWELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodian leader Hun Sen's weekend
appeal to his security forces not to terrorize members of the
opposition following last week's elections has done little to ease
fears among those who fled their homes to escape persecution.
	   Threats, intimidation and attacks on Hun Sen's political
opponents have continued, say the victims, who scoffed Monday at
Hun Sen's assurances of safety, broadcast on state-run television
and radio.
	   Human rights workers said complaints of harassment and even
attempted killings are still flooding into their offices, although
they applauded Hun Sen's appeal.
	   Chum Sarath, 20, a member of the opposition Sam Rainsy Party,
pointed to a three-inch (8-centimeter) gash on his skull. The day
after ballots were cast, he said, a group of about 15 thugs kicked
and beat him unconscious with a wooden club.
	   ``Hun Sen can say whatever he wants, but that does not mean the
people below him listen,'' said the political activist, who has
spent the past week in a safe house and has no intention to return
home any time soon.
	   The elections were held one year after Hun Sen ousted Prince
Norodom Ranariddh in a violent coup, shattering a tense dual
premiership formed after U.N.-sponsored elections in 1993. As many
as 100 of Ranariddh's supporters were killed by Hun Sen's forces in
the months after his takeover.
	   Election officials have not yet announced the winners of last
week's parliamentary election, blaming delays on difficulties in
verifying results from the country's remote provinces. According to
unofficial projections, Hun Sen appears likely to win at least half
of the seats in the National Assembly.
	   Following charges by opposition parties of election fraud, the
National Election Committee said Monday it had agreed to a recount
of ballots in areas where FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy Party
suspect irregularities.
	   Though election day proceeded peacefully, with only minor
complaints reported by party activists, those who voted against Hun
Sen's ruling party say they fear retaliation and retribution. They
began fleeing to provincial capitals and to Phnom Penh last week.
	   Scores of Hun Sen's political opponents say they are afraid
ruling party members will carry out death threats made before the
polls. Several politicians in Phnom Penh told human rights workers
that after election day, they had received anonymous phone calls,
sometimes playing funeral dirges and then hanging up.
	   Nieng Pha, an activist from Prey Veng province for Ranariddh's
FUNCINPEC party, fled to Phnom Penh after being shot in the leg by
unknown assailants last month. He said he is still being followed
and that family members have warned that it is too early to come
home.
	   A woman activist for the Sam Rainsy Party, who had to be sedated
when she arrived in the capital last Friday because she was so
upset, appealed to the international community for help at a news
conference Monday.
	   Two days after the election, she slipped away from home in the
central province of Kampong Cham after a friend warned her of
threats and police came to her home.
	   The woman, who asked that her name not be used, lost her husband
to political violence last year when unknown assailants threw hand
grenades into a demonstration led by Sam Rainsy. Sixteen people
were killed and more than 100 injured, but no one has yet been
brought to justice for the attack.
	   ``I request the international community to help find justice,''
she said. ``If the situation continues, everyone will die and the
nation will never see peace.''	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Cambodia-Election-Abuses; CT:i; 
