<TEXT>
	   REIMS, France (AP) _ A day after the Tour de France ended in
Paris, members of the Dutch team TVM were being questioned by
police Monday about banned drugs found in their possession.
	   TVM team members had pulled out of the race on Friday, two days
before the ending, saying they had neither the physical nor the
mental strength to continue.
	   Six cyclists, along with other team staff members, were being
questioned Monday morning in Reims, north of Paris. Already the
team director, Cees Priem, and its doctor, Andrei Mikhailov, and a
masseur have been placed under formal investigation _ a step short
of being formally charged _ on doping charges.
	   The TVM investigation actually began last March, when customs
agents found performance-enhancing drugs in a team car, seizing
about 100 doses of EPO, which increases oxygen to the red blood
cells.
	   But it wasn't until the scandal involving another team, Festina,
broke out that the TVM allegations came to light.
	   Priem and Mikhailov were arrested on July 23, and subsequent
searches of TVM hotel rooms resulted in the seizure of more drugs.
Team members were taken to a hospital in Albertville, where they
were subjected to extensive medical checks.
	   The 17th stage of the race had to be annulled when all the
cyclists, angered at the treatment of TVM members, refused to race
and merely coasted in a pack to the finish line.
	   Finally, the TVM riders quit the Tour July 30 in Switzerland,
meaning they wouldn't have to come back through France.
	   Tour de France organizer Jean-Claude Killy, the former ski star,
said Monday that cyclists who had taken drugs were not the only
guilty party.
	   ``They're certainly guilty because you can't dope somebody
without them knowing, but they're also victims because they're at
the bottom of the chain,'' he said, referring to the suppliers.
	   Sports Minister Marie-George Buffet warned that doping among
athletes was also frequent at the junior and regional levels, where
drugs are seen by some as a guarantee of getting to the top.
	   In an interview with French daily Le Monde, she said 221
athletes tested positive for drugs in France in 1997, of whom just
27 were ``at the top level.''
	   (parf-jn-ip)
</TEXT>
