<HEADLINE>
German software giant debuts on Wall Street
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ SAP AG, Germany's biggest software
company and one of the stars on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange, hoped
to repeat that success in its Monday debut on Wall Street.
	   SAP, based in Walldorf in southwest Germany, hoped to raise its
international profile by becoming the eighth German firm to be
listed in the United States.
	   At present, 21 percent of SAP's freely floated stock is in the
hands of U.S. investors, said chief executive Henning Kagermann in
a weekend interview with Germany's financial daily Boersen-Zeitung.
	   The stock has risen some 115 percent this year alone on the
Frankfurt exchange.
