<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Japan-Coaches Punished </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Giants, Tigers coaches fined, suspended for three games
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese professional baseball's Central League
fined two coaches 300,000 yen (dlrs 2,100) each Monday and
suspended them for three games for their parts in melees that broke
out after batters were hit by pitches.
	   The Yomiuri Giants and the Hanshin Tigers also issued a joint
apology to fans for the violence in Sunday night's game between the
two clubs, won by the Tigers 6-3.
	   The punishment was ordered for Shiro Takegami, a 57-year-old
batting coach of the Giants, and Tadayoshi Ookuma, a 55-year-old
outfielder and base running coach for the Tigers, said Masaaki
Nagino, an official of the Central League.
	   In a televised game before 54,000 spectators at Koshien Stadium,
Takegami pushed Tigers catcher Akihiro Yano in a melee after Giants
rookie Yoshinoru Takahashi was hit by a pitch on his right arm in
the top of the eighth inning.
	   Takegami was ejected immediately.
	   In the bottom of the eighth, Yano was hit in the back by a pitch
thrown by ace reliever Hiromi Makihara, and Ookuma kicked Makihara.
Ookuma also was ejected.
	   The melees erupted two days after the league had suspended
Giants pitcher Balvino Galvez for the remainder of the season for
violence against an umpire during the Giants 6-1 loss to the Tigers
Friday night.
	   Galvez (9-7), formerly with Texas Rangers, was knocked out in
the sixth after giving up six runs. On his way to the bench,
apparently angry over the plate umpire's calls, he suddenly hurled
a ball at the umpire.
	   No games were scheduled Monday in either of Japan's two
professional leagues.
 &UR; (sk)	   
