<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Singapore-Dispute, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dispute between Malaysia, Singapore turns bitter
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Malaysian deputy minister's advice to travelers,
last 3 grafs &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ A row between Malaysia and
Singapore over the shift of a joint customs and immigration post
got uglier Monday with more Malaysian officials joining in a tirade
against their neighbor to the south.
	   Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat accused Singapore's media of
launching a ``hate campaign,'' while Education Minister Najib Abdul
Razak described Singapore as ``arrogant,'' newspapers reported
Monday.
	   Singapore relocated its railroad immigration facility Saturday,
despite Malaysia's refusal to go along. Train services are running
smoothly between the two countries, but Malaysian officials
complain it takes longer because passengers now have to get off
twice for immigration checks.
	   ``Why did they find a time such as now, when the country is
facing an economic slowdown and other problems?'' Malaysian
Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik was quoted as asking in the Star.
	   Information Minister Mohamed held out the threat of Malaysia
turning off its water supply to Singapore. About half of the water
consumed daily by Singaporeans comes from its Southeast Asian
neighbor.
	   ``Malaysians are still able to control their emotions, but I
won't be surprised if they come to a point where they cannot take
it any more and want the government to stop supplying water to
Singapore,'' he said.
	   In a Parliament session in Singapore, Minister for Trade and
Industry Lee Yock Suan said Malaysia will only hurt itself if it
decides to stop selling water to Singapore.
	   ``If they don't sell it to us, they don't have anybody to sell
it to,'' Lee said. He added that the water deal and the dispute
over Malaysia's immigration checkpoint are two separate issues.
	   Malaysian Education Minister Najib said, ``Singapore must act as
a gentleman would in resolving this problem or the republic would
be held responsible for any deterioration in relations between the
two countries.''
	   Malaysia's main opposition leader Monday urged restraint.
	   ``Singapore and Malaysian ministers and leaders should observe a
moratorium and stop mutual bashing,'' said Lim Kit Siang, the
opposition leader in Parliament.
	   Relations between the two countries have swung from diplomatic
tolerance to hostility in recent weeks.
	   In 1963, Singapore was incorporated into Malaysia, an experiment
that failed two years later after wrangling between Singapore
senior minister Lee Kwan Yew and the late Malaysian Prime Minister
Tunku Abdul Rahman.
	   Singapore still remains Malaysia's third-largest trade partner
and an important gateway into Malaysia.
	   More than 200,000 Malaysians cross over to Singapore each day to
work. Twenty-seven trains run daily between the two countries for
passenger, freight and a golf shuttle service.
	   Train travelers from Singapore need not worry if their passports
are not stamped on entering Malaysia, Malaysian Deputy Home
Minister Ong Ka Ting said.
	   He said their particulars are recorded into computers by
Malaysian immigration officers when they board the train at Tanjong
Pagar station and their entry is perfectly legal.
	   ``What is important is to facilitate travel of the visitors.
That's the duty of immigration officers. We leave other matters to
the governments of both countries,'' he said.	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Malaysia-Singapore-Dispute, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
