w2441 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-RugbyU-English     08-03 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-English-European Tournament </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
English clubs and RFU agree on European tournament.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ After months of feuding with the Rugby Football
Union over its decision to quit the European competition, the
English First Division Rugby Union scored a breakthrough and could
form a new tournament by October.
	   The EFDR and the RFU released a joint statement Monday saying
the two bodies were prepared to work in partnership to set up a new
cross-border tournament to replace the existing European club
competition.
	   ``The clubs are keen to institute a new tournament this season
and, while concerned about the practicality and mindful of time
constraints, the RFU has no objection in principle to this,'' the
statement said.
	   The RFU plans to open urgent negotiations with the unions in
other European countries in a bid to get the tournament up and
running by October.
	   The move is the latest development in a battle between the first
division clubs and the RFU which has been ongoing since the top 14
English clubs withdrew from the Europan tournament due to
structural concerns about the event.
	   Leading English club Bath won the European title in January
before the English clubs shunned the tournament.
	   Last week the top nine clubs in France also decided to pull out
in favor of forming a new championship with the English clubs.
	   EFDR chief executive Doug Ash said there was no definite
structure for the proposed tournament, although it would be
organized by European Rugby Cup _ the organization which ran the
first three European competitions.
	   ``It was a key breakthrough when the RFU agreed that we should
try to organize European rugby this coming season, when until now
it looked as though that would not be possible,'' he said.
	   Ash said the competition could start in October and the EFDR
would be pushing for all 14 English first division clubs to be
involved in the top tier of the tournament.
	   Under previous guidelines, only the top four English clubs
contested the main European tournament while the remaining teams
competed in a second conference.
	   (jp)
</TEXT>
