</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Obit-Schirdewan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Memorial service set for old revisionist communist
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Karl Schirdewan, a communist imprisoned by the
Nazis for treason and later victimized by former East Germany's
hardline Stalinists, has died at age 91.
	   Schirdewan, who had been ill for some time, died July 15 in a
hospital in Potsdam, just outside Berlin, said Baerbel Ritter, a
spokeswoman for the party of former east German communists.
	   A memorial service is scheduled for Wednesday at the Old City
Hall in Potsdam, she said Monday.
	   Born on May 14, 1907, in Koenigsberg _ now Kaliningrad in Russia
_ Schirdewan was an early communist youth group functionary and in
the 1920s was a close colleague of Ernst Thaelmann, then leader of
Germany's communist party.
	   Later as a resistance fighter against the Nazis, Schirdewan was
sentenced to three years in prison in 1935 for high treason,
serving the time in Sachsenhausen, Mauthausen and Flossenbuerg
concentration camps.
	   After the war, when East Germany formed a government in 1949,
Schirdewan rose to become a Central Committee secretary and a
member of the Politburo starting in 1953.
	   In 1958 he fell from favor with hardline Communist leader Walter
Ulbricht for comments ``contradictory to official party policy''
and was demoted to manage the party's state archives in Potsdam.
	   He remained a member of the communist party and was
rehabilitated and appointed to its Council of Elders when it was
renamed the Party of Democratic Socialism in 1990.
	   Shortly before his death, Schirdewan completed his memoirs,
which are to be published later this month, the spokeswoman said.
	   He is survived by his widow Giesela.
 &UR; (gb-pfg)
</TEXT>
