<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian govt. to sell 5 percent of country's largest company
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian government plans to sell off another 5
percent of the country's largest company, Gazprom, in order to
raise much-needed cash, officials said Monday.
	   The sale would reduce the government's share in the company from
40 percent to 35 percent, and could bring protests from Communist
lawmakers who oppose the sale of many state assets.
	   With nearly 400,000 employees, Gazprom controls production and
distribution of Russia's vast natural gas supplies and is one of
Western Europe's largest suppliers.
	   The gas monopoly is revered as a symbol of national strength,
but the government has targeted Gazprom recently as part of a drive
to get companies to pay overdue taxes.
	   The results of the tender, which will be open to foreigners,
will be announced in September, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   In other economic developments Monday:
	   _ Two oil companies that are behind in their tax payments will
have reduced access to the country's oil export pipeline. The
Sidanko and Onako oil companies will have their monthly exports
reduced by one-third until they pay their taxes, the Interfax news
agency said. The government's chronic inability to collect taxes is
one of its most serious problems.
	   _ The Finance Ministry said it may issue dlrs 2 billion in
Eurobonds later this year, but emphasized it would wait until
``market conditions allow the lowest costs.'' Russia is under less
pressure to sell the bonds now because of recent infusions of cash
from the International Monetary Fund.
	   _ President Boris Yeltsin promised to pay all back wages to the
military by early September, ITAR-Tass reported. Soldiers, like
many people are paid by the state, often receive their salaries
months late. The president has frequently pledged to pay wage
arrears, but the government often lacks the money to deliver.
	   (nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
