<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Panda Procreation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Artificially inseminated panda gives birth to cub
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ An 8-year-old panda has given birth to a cub in
captivity after becoming pregnant through artificial insemination,
China's official Xinhua News Agency reported Monday.
	   The mother, named Number 28, gave birth to her second baby after
a four-month pregnancy at a panda research center at Wolong Nature
Preserve in southwestern Sichuan province, the agency said.
	   The cub was the 21st baby panda born at the research center, the
report said, and so far 15 have survived to adulthood.
	   Poaching and loss of habitat have reduced the number of pandas
in the wild to fewer than 1,000, and any confirmed birth is
considered significant. Pandas are notoriously difficult to breed
in captivity, forcing many zoos to rely on methods like artificial
insemination. Chinese scientists announced last month they were
experimenting with techniques to clone pandas.
	   The animal also suffers from a low reproductive rate. Scientists
believe only a quarter of female pandas are able to conceive,
Xinhua said.
	   The panda is native only to China, where it is a national
symbol.
	   Xinhua also reported three Siberian tiger cubs were born at a
zoo in the northeastern city of Changchun July 3. It was the ninth
litter born to a 13-year-old tigress named Yanchun, Xinhua said.
	   Because of poaching for pelts and body parts used in Chinese
medicine, fewer than 500 Siberian tigers are believed to survive in
the wild.	   
</TEXT>
