</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Athlete's Brother </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brother of British javelin champion jailed for murder
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WOLVERHAMPTON, England (AP) _ A judge on Monday jailed the
brother of British Olympic javelin gold medallist Tessa Sanderson
for 18 months for manslaughter.
	   Eric Sanderson was working as a nighclub bouncer when he punched
Martin Leaver, 36, in the face, causing him to fall and hit his
head on a sidewalk. Leaver sustained serious brain damage and died
later in hospital.
	   Sanderson, 35, who admitted manslaughter, gave himself up to
police the day after the attack.
	   Tessa Sanderson, the 1984 Olympic javelin champion, was at
Wolverhampton Crown Court to hear judge Francis Allen say he
accepted her brother was ``gravely upset'' at the result of his
actions. She later refused comment.
	   Prosecutor Melbourne Inman told the court that Leaver, of
Wolverhampton, central England, died in the town's New Cross
Hospital on April 20 after being struck a single blow outside the
Chicago Rock Cafe, a pub which also functions as a club.
	   Inman said Leaver, a local council worker, and his brother
became abusive after failing to gain entry to the venue.
	   Managers asked Sanderson, also of Wolverhampton, to go outside
to clear the area, but he ''lost his temper'' after being pushed,
Inman said.
	   Sanderson admitted later that he punched the victim in the face
''hard enough to shut him up.''
	   Patrick Harrington, Sanderson's lawyer, said Leaver and his
brother had abused and taunted bouncers and witnesses saw Leaver
push Sanderson in an aggressive manner.
	   The judge agreed that Leaver's ``own behaviour undoubtedly gave
rise to this incident.''
	   ''That is very relevant in mitigating what you did but the fact
remains that you lost your temper and that was a direct cause of
his death,'' he said.
	   (scl)
</TEXT>
