r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-NATO     08-03 0212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO General Secretary comes to Poland on vacation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ NATO's secretary general said Monday he
decided to vacation in Poland, the biggest of the three former
Warsaw Pact countries to be invited to join the alliance, as a way
of promoting friendly ties.
	   After a breakfast meeting with the Polish foreign minister,
Secretary General Javier Solana said he hoped his visit would help
make ``relations between the countries of Europe not just a
formality,'' but rather a deeper ``human relationship.''
	   Solana reiterated that Poland will become a full NATO member in
April 1999, but that it will take part in NATO discussions before
that to ``land softly'' in the Alliance.
	   Poland, along with Hungary and the Czech Republic, are expected
to become NATO members at its 50th anniversary meetings on April
24-25, 1999.
	   Solana arrived in Warsaw on Saturday with his wife, Conchita
Gimenez, and their 23-year old daughter Vega and 21-year-old son
Diego for a nine-day vacation.
	   He will visit the historical city of Krakow in southern Poland
and northern Gdansk, the birthplace of Solidarity trade union. He
also will meet with Polish president Aleksander Kwasniewski on the
Baltic coast.
 &UR; (bp-pfg)
</TEXT>
