</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serbs press attacks in Kosovo after vowing that offensive is over
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with US envoy saying Serb offensive setback to
peace, warns of humanitarian catastrophe &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Government forces overran another
ethnic Albanian stronghold Monday, pressing attacks which have
forced tens of thousands from their homes since Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic declared the offensive over.
	   Senior U.S. envoy Christopher Hill called the offensive a
setback to American and European peace efforts and declared ``we
are on the verge of a humanitarian catastrophe.''
	   Serb and Albanian sources reported continued fighting Monday in
central and southern parts of the rebellious province. The
Albanian-run Kosovo Information Center said four people were killed
and several others, including an 80-year-old man, were wounded in
shelling Monday.
	   Six villages had been ``nearly leveled to the ground,'' the
Albanian center said.
	   Meanwhile, the government's Tanjug news agency said police
entered Smonica early Monday. Serb military sources said troops
shelled the village near the Albanian border for days and killed at
least a dozen Kovoso Liberation Army fighters.
	   Serb sources also said troops continued Monday to lay siege to
another border village, Junik. Independent media in the Yugoslav
capital Belgrade said most KLA fighters had slipped out of the
village for sanctuaries in nearby Albania, leaving a few dozen
insurgents who have encircled their positions with land mines.
	   The latest fighting broke out only days after Milosevic promised
a European Union delegation last week that the latest offensive
against the KLA was over.
	   On Friday, Milosevic assured Hill that he would take ``personal
responsibility'' for assuring that international aid organizations
could deliver relief supplies to the refugees and that diplomatic
observers could escort them back to their homes.
	   Speaking to reporters in Pristina, Hill said he was waiting for
signs those promises would be fulfilled.
	   ``I'm not interested in anyone's assurances,'' he said. ``We
don't have facts on the grounds as far as I can see.''
	   An official of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, Mons
Nyberg, said access had been ``on and off,'' with police sometimes
holding his teams at checkpoints for hours before allowing them to
proceed.
	   It was uncertain, he added, whether this was due to a ``lack of
communication or a systematic plan to stop of slow access.'' Nyberg
estimated at least 35,000 people had fled the weekend fighting,
swelling the total number of refugees to about 180,000 since the
government launched its crackdown on Albanian militants in
February.
	   In Geneva, a spokeswoman for the International Committee of the
Red Cross, Amanda Williamson, said an ICRC team found between
60,000 and 80,000 refugees hiding on the slopes of Mount Berisa
south of Pristina.
	   She said the ICRC in Belgrade was trying to organize an aid
convoy.
	   The campaign against Albanian civilians was reminiscent of
``ethnic cleansing'' _ the forcible removal of rival ethnic groups
that marked conflicts in the former Yugoslav republics of Bosnia
and Croatia earlier this decade.
	   On Thursday, Milosevic told a European Union delegation that a
government offensive launched July 24 was over. He later assured
U.S. envoy Christopher Hill that refugees could return to their
homes and international relief organizations could assist them.
	   In Albania's capital, Tirana, a Kosovo Albanian party courted by
the United States accused the Serb-led Yugoslav government of
trying ``to make it impossible for thousands of Albanians to return
to their homes.''
	   The statement was issued by the Albanian Democratic Movement,
whose leader, Mehmet Hajrizi, has been mentioned as a key figure in
a planned Albanian team that U.S. diplomats hope can negotiate the
future of the majority Albanian province with Milosevic.
	   Milosevic has promised to restore Kosovo's autonomy, which he
canceled in 1989. But he and major world powers oppose independence
for Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs in the province
by 9-to-1.
	   Kosovo is located in southern Serbia, the dominant of two
republics that make up the remainder of Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and European nations fear independence could
lead to demands by Albanian-speaking communities in Macedonia and
Yugoslavia's other republic, Montenegro, to establish a ``Greater
Albania'' in the southern Balkans.
	   KLA leaders are expected to announce this week whether they will
accept a U.S. plan for Albanian politicians to enter peace talks
with Milosevic. The current Serb offensive appears designed to
deliver a strong blow against the rebels and force them to
negotiate from a position of weakness.
	   reid/ds/av
</TEXT>
