<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Fat Farm </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Obese Chinese youngsters being shipped off to fat farms
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Children in Shanghai are six times more likely to
be obese than their counterparts a decade ago, and many are being
shipped off to slimming camps for the summer, the official Xinhua
News Agency reported Monday.
	   The typical 10-14-year-old in China's largest city eats too much
junk food and watches too much television, while rarely exercising,
Xinhua said.
	   New statistics show one out of 100 children in Shanghai is
obese, 6.24 times the rate of a decade ago, Xinhua said.
	   During the weeklong slimming camps, children are roused at 6
a.m. for strenuous exercise in the stifling summer heat of China's
largest city, the agency said. Children are served special diets
planned by professional nutritionists, and junk food is banned at
the camps, it said.
	   Doctors lecture kids on the dangers of obesity and children are
required to wash their own clothes and make their own beds, chores
few are required to perform at home, it said.
	   China's policy of permitting most families just one child has
created a generation of overindulged only children, frequently
referred to as ``little emperors'' because of their tyrannical hold
on the affections of parents and grandparents. 	   
</TEXT>
