<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-New Government </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After months of political wrangling, Dutch get new Cabinet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Netherlands-Cabinet-Glance &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ Ending months of political
wrangling and speculation, ministers of the Netherlands' new
coalition government were sworn in Monday and introduced to the
nation.
	   Signaling the beginning of their administration, giddy new
Cabinet ministers posed for photos with Dutch Queen Beatrix outside
her Noordeinde Palace in The Hague.
	   Prime Minister Wim Kok returns for a second term to lead the
so-called Purple Coalition, referring to the spectrum of political
colors that make up the alliance.
	   The new team has two female deputy prime ministers, marking the
the first time in Dutch political history that women have held that
position. They are former Transport Minister Annemarie Jorritsma,
who will serve as economic affairs minister, and Els Borst, a
veteran politician who will serve a second term as health minister.
	   The coalition, which includes Kok's left-leaning Labor Party,
the right-leaning Liberal Party and the centrist Democrats 66
party, has governed for the last four years.
	   Coalition governments have ruled for the past 80 years in the
Netherlands, where there are a dozen sizable parties, none of which
has been able to garner enough votes to take control outright.
	   Since general elections in May, leaders of the three top parties
had huddled in talks to formulate a new blueprint for the
government and reshuffle the 15-member Cabinet to bring in new
leaders.
	   Missing from the new team are some of the most visible ministers
from the last government, including former Foreign Minister Hans
van Mierlo and Justice Minister Winnie Sorgdrager.
	   But the Cabinet has some familiar faces. In addition to Borst
and Jorritsma, Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm _ credited by many for
helping the Netherlands' cut its budget deficit and qualify to join
Europe's single currency _ returns to his old job.
	   Former Agriculture Minister Jozias van Aartsen, who oversaw the
country's efforts to contain an economically devastating outbreak
of swine fever, was promoted as the new foreign minister.
	   The trouble-ridden Justice Ministry portfolio was handed to
newcomer Benk Korthals, who faces a slew of leftover controversies
from the last administration, including a Dutch child pornography
ring operating on the Internet.
	   ``I see it as a challenge,'' said Korthals, a lawyer.
	   (jc/bk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Netherlands-New Government; CT:i; 
