<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Kashmir,0269 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indian shelling kills three more people in Pakistani Kashmir
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Shelling by Indian troops killed
three more people, including two children, in the
Pakistan-controlled area of Kashmir on Monday, raising the number
of Pakistanis killed in the shelling during the last five days to
54, army officials said.
	   Two children were killed when Indian forces launched shells at
Atmaqam in Neelam Valley, 50 kilometers (30 miles) from
Muzaffarabad, the capitol of Pakistan-held Kashmir. Another man was
killed in shelling in Bhimber sector near the border, they said.
	   The number of deaths were low because most people had fled from
the border villages and the intensity of India's shelling has
eased, the officials said on customary condition of anonymity.
	   Indian army officials say 34 Indians, most of them civilians,
were killed by Pakistani forces. Pakistan says most of its
casualties were civilian.
	   Witnesses say dozens of people have also been wounded and
thousands displaced on both sides of Kashmir. India and Pakistan
each accuse the other of starting the bombardment.
	   Pakistan and India have fought two wars over Kashmir, the
Himalayan territory divided between them, since the countries
gained independence in 1947 from British rule.
	   Pakistan demands a right of self determination for Kashmiri
people, which is the only Muslim majority area in Hindu dominated
India.
	   India accuses Pakistan of arming Muslim militants fighting for
Kashmir's independence. Pakistan denies the charge and say it
offers only moral and political help. 	   
</TEXT>
