<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Saddam's Son </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
News agency says Odai's attackers captured
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraqi security forces have captured the men
who shot and seriously wounded President Saddam Hussein's eldest
son Odai in 1996, the official Iraqi News Agency reported Monday.
	   The agency said the General Directorate of Security would issue
a statement later in the day with ``the details of this criminal
operation ... as it was revealed by the criminals themselves.''
	   INA said the statement will show how the assailants pursued Odai
and then shot him in his car.
	   The agency did not say how many assailants were taken into
custody or when and where they were apprehended. Nor did it give
any details of their identities.
	   Odai, 34. was shot about 10 times on Dec. 12, 1996, while he
waited alone in his car in the upscale Al-Mansoura neighborhood in
the capital Baghdad.
	   In April last year, surgeons operated on his shattered left leg.
He has since been shown on state-run television walking with the
aid of a cane.
	   Iraq blamed Iran for the attack. Iran denied involvement.
	   Two opposition groups claimed responsibility for the attack: the
Iranian-backed Al-Dawa Party, a Shiite opposition group, and the
Mohammed Madhlum al-Dulaimi Group, named after an Iraqi air force
general executed for plotting against Saddam.
 &UR; lb-eap
</TEXT>
