w2496 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-DeathPena     08-03 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Death Penalty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine judge fixes execution date despite court prohibition
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Despite Supreme Court orders, a judge
has set a date this week for the first execution under a 1994 law
that restored the death penalty in the Philippines, the justice
secretary said Monday.
	   The judge set Friday for a lethal injection for Leo Echegaray,
who was convicted of twice raping his 10-year-old stepdaughter in
1994, said Justice Secretary Serafin Cuevas.
	   Cuevas said, however, the government could not carry out the
execution until the Supreme Court lifts an indefinite prohibition
it imposed while considering a petition questioning the
constitutionality of the death penalty law.
	   No reason was mentioned for setting the Friday execution date.
	   The current Philippine constitution, adopted in 1987, abolished
the death penalty, but a law that took effect in January 1994
restored it for 13 ``heinous crimes'' including rape, murder and
drug trafficking.
	   Echegaray's lawyers have petitioned the Supreme Court to declare
the law unconstitutional, arguing that lethal injection, the chosen
mode of execution, is inhuman.
	   Death sentences are automatically reviewed by the Supreme Court,
which so far has affirmed only a few of the more than 600 handed
down by lower courts.
	   Last year, the Supreme Court approved Echegaray's execution
between February and August this year. In February, however, it
stopped a lower court from fixing a specific date until it has
ruled on the petition.
	   Cuevas said the Supreme Court could issue a ruling on the
petition before the end of the month to satisfy the deadline it set
for Echegaray's execution.
	   Several groups, including the Roman Catholic Church, have
opposed the death penalty, saying the crime rate has not declined
despite the restoration of capital punishment. The groups say the
death penalty also discriminates against the poor, and that many
death-row inmates may have been convicted because they could not
afford good lawyers.
	   Proponents, however, say the penalty has not yet sent its
message to would-be criminals because no one has been executed
under the 1994 law. They also say the law has enough legal
safeguards to prevent the execution of innocent people.	   
</TEXT>
