<SLUG> BC-Spain-Honduras-Asylum </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spain rejects asylum petition from Honduran fugitive
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Spain has turned down a petition for
political asylum from an ex-Honduran military officer wanted at
home for his alleged links to a death squad blamed for
assassinating hundreds of suspected rebel sympathizers in the
1980s, the Foreign Ministry said Monday.
	   Former army captain Billy Joya arrived in Spain last week and
sought asylum to avoid being deported to Honduras, a ministry
spokesman, customarily not identified, said. He added that Joya
would not be deported immediately as his lawyers had appealed the
decision.
	   Joya has evaded capture since a Honduran judge ordered his
arrest in 1995 on charges of kidnapping and torturing six
university students in 1982. Other police officers suspected in the
same kidnap-torture case are also on the run.
	   The case is a landmark in civilian efforts to assert control
over the military, which ruled Honduras from 1963 to 1981 and
retained great autonomy afterwards.
	   The Foreign ministry spokesman said Honduras had not yet asked
for Joya's extradition.
	   (mr/cg) 	   
</TEXT>
