w2521 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-WaterScare 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Water Scare, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS sufferers, others with immune problems well aware of unsafe
</HEADLINE>
water &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout with AIDS and other immune disease
sufferers accustomed to boiling water; increases safe water zone &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ More than 3 million Sydney residents
have learned what it's like to have to boil water to make it safe
to drink _ but people with immune systems weakened by AIDS and
other diseases have been doing it for years.
	   An outbreak of the potentially deadly microscopic parasites
giardia and cryptosporidium detected last week panicked
Sydneysiders, who are boiling drinking water or buying bottled
water.
	   It was a severe embarrassment for the city that will be host to
the 200 Summer Olympics in just two years.
	   Fear and anger among city residents has continued since the
dangerous parasites were found.
	   ``Opening the tap and drinking water is something we take for
granted, and what has happened with the water makes me understand
what people in Third World countries go through,'' said Sydney
resident Rick Turansky.
	   The Health Department said so far there had been no reported
cases of illness from water contamination, but the parasites have
an incubation period of a week or more.
	   The water treatment plant that had spread the parasites has been
cleaned up and the city's water system is being flushed with clean
water.
	   By Monday night, 104 suburbs in the west and south of the city,
housing more than 600,000 of the city's 3.7 million people, had
been given the all-clear to resume drinking tap water.
	   But Urban Affairs Minister Craig Knowles could not say when the
rest of Sydney would be able to stop boiling drinking water or
relying on bottled water.
	   Giardia and cryptosporidium are most dangerous to people who
already have weakened immune systems.
	   Cryptosporidium got into the water supply of Milwaukee in 1993,
contributing to the deaths of about 100 people. More than 400,000
others became ill.
	   Those who died were mostly the elderly, infants, people
recovering from surgery and those with immune systems weakened by
AIDS, the HIV virus, lymphoma, cancer chemotherapy or hepatitis.
	   Many people in Sydney with those problems had already been
taking precautions against water contamination even before the
parasite crisis struck.
	   ``There are obviously special problems for people with any
compromised immune system, but we have taken precautions for a long
time before this. The threat of cryptosporidium has been around for
a long time,'' said Jo Watson, a research officer with the group
People Living with HIV/AIDS.
	   ``As far as we're aware, there hasn't been any increase in
reports of people with HIV/AIDS being affected by giardia or
crypto.
	   ``There's no need to go into a panic about this. Giardia is
easily treated with antibiotic tablets, and our community has been
aware of crypto for a long time,'' she said.
	   Cryptosporidium does not respond to antibiotics.
	   There are some 6,000 to 7,000 AIDS/HIV positive people in the
state of New South Wales, and the great majority live in Sydney,
the heart of Australia's gay community, Watson said.
	   Authorities found a number of dead dogs and foxes in canals near
the water plant, but Knowles said it was not clear if they caused
the problem.
	   ``It may be the case that we never find the source of
contamination,'' he said.
	   The runoff of polluted water from farms in the water catchment
area has also been proposed as a possible source of the
contamination.
	   Giardia can cause diarrhea and other gastrointestinal problems.
Cryptosporidium causes flu-like symptoms. Both are naturally
occurring parasites in the intestinal tracts of mammals, and are
normally spread through fecal matter.	   
</TEXT>
