<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Mad Cow </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New case of mad cow disease in France; 127 cattle destroyed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French authorities slaughtered a herd of 127 cattle
over the weekend, after detecting a new case of mad cow disease,
the Agriculture Ministry said Monday.
	   The infected animal was a milk cow on a farm in the Manche
region, on France's northern coast. It was born in July 1989.
	   The ministry said in a statement that it was the 38th case of
mad cow disease discovered in France since 1990, and the seventh
this year.
	   The disease, bovine spongiform encephalopathy, was first
detected in 1985. The ailment eats holes in the brain, causing
cattle to stagger and drool. There is no cure.
	   Scientists believe the mad cow disease may be linked to an
equally fatal human brain ailment, Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease.
	   (parf-jk-ip)
</TEXT>
