<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German opposition calls for abandoning atomic energy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with government reaction &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Warning of dire economic consequences,
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government and Germany's atomic energy
industry Monday attacked plans by the Social Democrats to start
closing nuclear power plants if they win national elections this
fall.
	   Government spokesman Otto Hauser said SPD demands for pulling
out of atomic energy as quickly as possible were ``not thought
through and besides that, damaging to Germany's business climate.''
	   Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt warned such a move would mean
``a withdrawal of German business from the technological
world-league and endanger a massive number of jobs.''
	   According to this week's Der Spiegel newsmagazine, if the Social
Democrats win the Sept. 27 parliamentary elections, they plan to
order the six oldest of Germany's 19 atomic power plants closed by
2002 and the last by 2028.
	   Michael Donnermeyer, a spokesman for the Social Democrats,
refused to comment on the timetable, noting only that the party's
campaign platform calls for ending the use of atomic power ``as
quickly as possible.''
	   PreussenElektra chief Hans-Dieter Harig told the Bild newspaper
that he would seek ``not insignificant'' damages from the federal
government if the Social Democrats start ordering the early closure
of atomic power plants.
	   ``More than a third of the power is produced in German atomic
power plants,'' he said. ``We can't just suddenly do without that.
It would be economic recklessness to shut down atomic power plants
before the end of their technical and economic lifespan.''
	   Hauser noted that the Social Democrats' chancellor candidate,
Gerhard Schroeder, sits on the board of PreussenElektra as governor
of Lower Saxony state, which gets 60 percent of its electricity
from nuclear power.
	   Technology Minister Juergen Ruettgers added Germany needs atomic
power to meet clean-air goals.
	   But the Social Democrats' environmental policy spokesman in
parliament, Michael Mueller, said recent reports of radiation leaks
during atomic waste transports demonstrated that a basic condition
is lacking for atomic energy _ the safe disposal of the waste.
	   ``The atomic power plants are like a jumbo jet that's in the air
without a landing strip having been built,'' he told German radio.
 &UR; (pfg-gb)
</TEXT>
