<SLUG> BC-Japan-Politics-Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll finds low support for new Japanese Cabinet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comments &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The newly formed Cabinet of Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi was supported by less than one-third of voters questioned in
a weekend poll, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   The poll, by the newspaper Asahi, found 32 percent support for
Obuchi's Cabinet, with 47 percent of those polled saying they do
not support the new administration. That figure was the worst
disapproval rating for a new Cabinet since the paper began taking
polls on the subject in 1955, excluding the brief, scandal-tainted
government of Prime Minister Sousuke Uno in 1989.
	   ``I am taking (the results) seriously,'' Obuchi was quoted as
saying by Kyodo News service.
	   Obuchi said, however, it is more important to study what the
government can do for the public than seeking ways to raise
popularity ratings, Kyodo added.
	   Obuchi, president of the long-ruling Liberal Democratic Party,
unveiled his Cabinet last Thursday after winning an election in
Parliament to become Japan's next leader.
	   He faces immediate pressure to quickly pull Japan's struggling
economy out of recession.
	   Separately, Chief Cabinet Spokesman Hiromu Nonaka was quoted as
saying that a popularity rating of around 30 percent gives the
Cabinet more incentive to ``do our best.''
	   ``The government, with Prime Minister Obuchi at the head, will
try to meet public expectations and get through the current
difficulties to raise public support,'' Nonaka was quoted as saying
by Kyodo.
	   The paper surveyed 1,130 registered voters Saturday and Sunday.
It provided no margin of error.
	   The Asahi survey follows one published Sunday by the Yomiuri,
Japan's largest newspaper, which put the Cabinet's approval rating
at a slightly higher 33.1 percent.
 &UR; (kgo-may)	   
