<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Racism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Right-wing paper loses second printer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHUR, Switzerland (AP) _ A newspaper owned by the leader of a
far-right Swiss Italian party on Monday lost its second printer in
a week over allegations of anti-Semitism.
	   Gasser Print AG of Chur, which was due to start printing Il
Mattino della Domenica, said it decided over the weekend to cancel
its contract to print the paper.
	   Giuliano Bignasca, leader of the Lega dei Ticinesi, is currently
under investigation for alleged anti-Semitic articles in the
free-distribution Sunday paper, which he claims has a circulation
of 40,000 in the southern canton (state) of Ticino.
	   The contract was entered into before the charges emerged, Gasser
Print said in a statement.
	   Last week, the previous printer, Vogt Schild of Solothurn, said
it had pulled out its contract. The firm cited the charges against
Bignasca as the reason.
	   Bignasca has railed in recent weeks against threats of sanctions
by U.S. states and cities against Switzerland over its handling of
Holocaust victims' assets.
	   The paper has said the U.S. policy is being directed by Jews who
hold key positions in the Clinton administration. The July 5
edition listed 60 U.S. officials whom it identified as being
Jewish.
	   The regional anti-immigrant party has one seat in the 200-member
lower house of parliament. It received some 12 percent of the vote
in the most recent regional vote in Ticino, Switzerland's only
Italian-speaking state.
	   Over the years Bignasca has been sentenced a number of times for
slander and drug-related offenses.
	   Last month, a Swiss court ordered fines and prison terms under
Switzerland's 1995 anti-racism law for an author and his publisher
for producing books denying the existence of the Nazi gas chambers.
 &UR; (gm)
