<SLUG> BC-Algeria, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At least 24 killed in attack, search operation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with officials saying 12 killed, plus 12 more in chase
operation; UN mission head meeting Algerian president. ADDS
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By RACHID KHIARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Armed men in military fatigues stopped a
bus at a fake roadblock, then slit the throats of passengers and
the driver, killing 12 people, authorities announced Monday.
	   After the attack Sunday afternoon, at least 12 suspected Islamic
militants were killed by the army as it searched for the attackers,
authorities said in a statement. Although some attackers were
caught, they said, a search operation was continuing Monday.
	   The attack came as a U.N. panel continued its mission in
Algeria, looking into the massacres and bombings that have killed
an estimated 75,000 people since the Islamic insurgency began in
1992.
	   The mission, led by former Portuguese President Mario Soares,
met Monday with President Liamine Zeroual. No details of the
meeting were immediately available.
	   Six people were wounded in Sunday's massacre near Saida, 400
kilometers (250 miles) southwest of the capital, Algiers.
	   It began when the armed group signaled the bus to stop. The
suspicious driver speeded up instead, but was forced off the road
by a volley of machine-gun fire, according to witnesses and
hospital sources speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   Once the bus was stopped, the attackers moved in, slitting the
throats of some passengers, according to the sources.
	   (rk-parf-jn) 	   
