<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Trapped Workers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rescue workers fight against time to save trapped workers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) _ Rescue efforts were underway Monday to
save more than 20 workers trapped underneath a collapsed building
near the Nigerian capital Abuja.
	   At least one dead body had already been removed from the site of
the accident which occurred Sunday when the first floor of a
building under construction suddenly collapsed and trapped workers
on the ground floor, witnesses told reporters.
	   The collapsed building was part of a huge housing complex
sponsored by the state-owned Federal Housing Estate, about 20
kilometers (12 miles) from Abuja.
	   At the time of the incident, independent sub-contractors were
overseeing construction work going on simultaneously on both the
ground and first floors.
	   One survivor, James Okolo, who was in the bathroom when the
accident occurred, told reporters he went along to the site to
``earn a little bit of money instead of sitting at home.''
	   ``Suddenly the top platform collapsed. It happened with such
speed that those on the ground floor did not have a chance at
all,'' Okolo said.
	   Despite the involvement of leading construction companies in
Abuja, rescue efforts Monday morning were being hampered by a lack
of heavy duty cranes to lift the huge concrete slabs under which
the men were buried.
	   Officials for the firm who allegedly bolted from the site
immediately after the incident, were unavailable for comment.
	   Construction accidents are fairly common in Nigeria, where
corruption and incompetence have led to a lack of accountability
within the sector.
