<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Saddam's Son,0219 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq says attackers of son of Saddam Hussein captured
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraqi security forces have captured the men
who shot and seriously wounded President Saddam Hussein's eldest
son Odai in 1996, the official Iraqi News Agency reported Monday.
	   The agency said the General Directorate of Security would issue
a statement later with ``the details of this criminal operation ...
as it was revealed by the criminals themselves.''
	   The Iraqi agency said the statement will show how the assailants
pursued Odai and then shot him in his car. The agency did not say
how many assailants were taken into custody or when and where they
were apprehended. Nor did it give any details of their identities.
	   Odai, 34, was shot about 10 times on Dec. 12, 1996, while he
waited alone in his car in the Iraqi capital, Baghdad.
	   In April 1997, surgeons operated on his shattered left leg. He
has since been shown on state-run television walking with the aid
of a cane.
	   Iraq blamed Iran for the attack. Iran denied involvement.
	   Two opposition groups claimed responsibility for the attack: the
Iranian-backed Al-Dawa Party, a Shiite opposition group, and the
Mohammed Madhlum al-Dulaimi Group, named after an Iraqi air force
general executed for plotting against Saddam. 	   
</TEXT>
