<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Angola </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa prepared for Angola peacekeeping if asked
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DANIEL J. WAKIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Defense Minister Joe Modise on
Monday accused Angola's UNITA movement of resuming hostilities and
said South Africa was willing to participate in a U.N. peacekeeping
operation in Angola.
	   Tensions between UNITA and the Angolan government have surged in
recent weeks, culminating in the massacre of more than 100
civilians in a remote northern village.
	   ``The information we are getting is to the effect that both
sides are preparing for conflict,'' Modise said. ``I think it's no
secret that UNITA has been on the offensive in some towns.''
	   Regional leaders last week demanded that Angola's UNITA movement
complete demobilizing their forces and take all their elected
positions in government, as set out in a 1994 peace accord.
	   Modise said that if the United Nations asked South Africa to
send troops, the government would consult with fellow Southern
African Development Community member countries and, if the SADC
agreed, would send its forces.
	   Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie Kasrils faulted the Organization
for African Unity and SADC states for their weak response todate to
the Angola crisis.
	   ``One doesn't see that energetic a role in terms of these
countries, with all due respect,'' Kasrils told reporters.
	   U.N. special envoy to Angola Lakhdar Brahimi was due to leave
the southwest African country Wednesday for a tour of neighboring
states and talks with leaders close to President Jose Eduardo dos
Santos and UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi.
	   Soon after it won independence from Portugal in 1975, Angola
plunged into civil war. It became a Cold War battlefield, pitting
UNITA _ backed by the United States and former apartheid South
Africa _ against the then-Marxist government, supported by Cuba and
other left-wing governments.
	   Recalling those times, a Johannesburg daily reported Monday that
300 South African mercenaries are supporting UNITA, a Portuguese
acronym for the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola.
	   The Star quoted unnamed intelligence sources in South Africa and
abroad as saying that the mercenaries were working for a new,
unnamed security group in South Africa.
	   ``We don't have any facts on this, '' Kasrils told The
Associated Press, adding that the government would move against
anyone breaking the law.
	   South Africans are banned from acting as mercenaries and must
obtain approval of the National Conventional Arms Control Committee
to offer military-related services abroad.
	   A Portuguese weekly newspaper, Independente, on Saturday
reported that South Africa's best-known private military company,
Executive Outcomes, has provided the Angolan government with pilots
to fly new planes bought from Russia.
	   (var-pr-aos
</TEXT>
