<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Latest statistics indicate economy getting worse
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with financial secretary's remarks in grafs 8-9 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARCOS CALO MEDINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Already mired in recession, Hong Kong received
a battering of bad economic news Monday _ new figures indicating a
sharp economic contraction, bad earnings reports and a steep drop
on the stock market.
	   Officials predicted more trouble was ahead.
	   The gross domestic product fell 2.8 percent in this year's first
quarter due to ``a significant downturn'' in domestic demand and
fewer tourists, the Census and Statistics Department said in a
statement.
	   The fall in GDP was sharper than the 2 percent the government
had estimated previously, and a result of more specific numbers,
officials said. Unemployment is at a 15-year high, and tourism is
off more than 20 percent this year.
	   No figures are available yet for the second quarter, which ended
in June, but senior officials already have indicated that it is
likely to show further contraction. The government economist, K.Y.
Tang, said Monday that when the numbers do come out, the second
quarter probably will be worse than the first.
	   He declined to predict what might happen in the second half of
the year, but said the economy, which is driven by exports and
services, is unlikely to improve until the rest of Asia does.
	   The latest figures also indicated that total exports decreased
by 1 percent from the same period last year.
	   Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said he expected Hong Kong's
economy to recover at a faster pace than other economies in the
region.
	   He said Hong Kong's economic fundamentals remain strong and many
of the territory's largest companies remain profitable.
	   Hong Kong initially withstood much of Asia's financial turmoil,
but now has been dragged down into recession as well.
	   In a survey conducted by the Home Affairs Bureau of more than
1,500 respondents last month, 66 percent said the state of the
economy was their biggest worry.
	   Meanwhile, HSBC Holdings, which has the largest capitalized
stock on the Hong Kong stock exchange, announced late Monday that
its net profit for 1998's first six months amounted to U.S. dlrs
2.40 billion, down 16 percent from dlrs 2.87 billion a year
earlier.
	   Group Chairman John Bond said the fall reflected ``the impact of
a deteriorating economy environment in Asia.''
	   The group's principal unit, Hong Kong Bank, posted a 41 percent
profit decline to U.S. dlrs 787 million from dlrs 1.3 billion a
year earlier.
	   It also announced a bad debt provision of more than dlrs 1
billion because of Asia's economic problems.
	   ``There is considerable uncertainty about the duration of the
downturn,'' Bond said in a statement. ``We do not know when the
recovery will start.''
	   Dragged down by lackluster performance of HSBC shares, the Hang
Seng index, the market's key indicator of blue chips, lost 383.43
points, or nearly 5 percent, closing at 7,552.77.	   
</TEXT>
