w2560 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  EU-ArmsExports     08-03 0238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> EU-Arms Exports </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Candidate countries, Iceland, Norway, commit to EU rule on arms
</HEADLINE>
sales

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium - The European Union welcomed a pledge Monday
by 13 countries to commit to an EU code of conduct to curb arms
sales to countries with poor human rights records or aggressive
designs on their neighbors.
	   ``The European Union takes note of this commitment and welcomes
it,'' the EU said in a joint statement with the 13 countries.
	   These are 11 countries that have applied for EU membership -
Bulgaria, Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia,
Lithuania, Poland, Romania, Slovakia and Slovenia - as well as
Iceland and Norway.
	   They declared that they ``share the objectives of the EU code of
conduct on arms exports.'' The 15 EU countries formally approved
the code, which is not legally binding, on June 8.
	   The code sets out criteria that should govern arms sales and
rules out exports to nations that might use weapons for attacking
other states, internal repression or support of terrorism.
	   But it is not legally binding in that it gives individual
governments leeway to determine when a prospective arms-buying
nation meets the criteria.
	   Six candidate countries to the EU - Cyprus, the Czech Republic,
Estonia, Hungary, Poland and Slovenia opened membership talks with
the EU this year. The EU says the other five need more time to
prepare for such talks.
	    &UR; (as) 	   
