<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine president describes economy as toothless paper tiger
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President Joseph Estrada said Monday
the Philippines, described by his predecessor as an emerging
economic tiger, was actually a toothless paper tiger, and that the
ugly truth about Manila's economy should not be concealed.
	   Estrada has been criticized, mostly by business leaders, for
portraying the Philippines as a country on the edge of bankruptcy.
They said this could scare off investors and alarm international
creditors.
	   Estrada said Filipinos have a right to know the true state of
the country's finances and economy to forestall surprises.
	   ``We should not always hide and window-dress a serious condition
because in the end people get shocked when they find out the
truth,'' Estrada said in a radio interview.
	   ``They said we're the new tiger of Asia but it turned out we're
a paper tiger without a tooth,'' Estrada said, alluding to the
country's economy.
	   In his first state-of-the-nation address last week, Estrada said
Asia's year-old financial crisis has slowed the Philippine economy
and lowered labor productivity, causing inflation, unemployment and
crime to rise.
	   While the budget deficit is forecast to climb as high as 70
billion pesos (dlrs 1.7 billion), corruption and foreign debt
payments continue to drain the government's coffers, he said.
	   Businessmen said Estrada's description of the economy as nearing
bankruptcy could jeopardize Manila's chances of tapping the
international capital market at a time when it is preparing to
launch an international bond of at least dlrs 500 million to ease
its budget deficit.
	   Estrada said that while he pointed out the economy's weaknesses,
he stressed that the Philippines was better off than Indonesia,
Malaysia and Thailand, which are projecting recessions because of
continued financial difficulties from the regional crisis.
	   Despite financial constraints, Estrada said he would give
priority to food security and ensure that basic services to
Filipinos continue.
	   Estrada won the May 11 presidential elections by a wide margin
on a pro-poor platform.	   
</TEXT>
