r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  Cambodia-Election-Loser     08-03 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Cambodia-Election-Loser </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hand-picked Cambodian premier accepts crushing election defeat
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ The man who replaced Prince Norodom
Ranariddh as Cambodia's co-premier after last year's bloody coup
gracefully conceded his election defeat Monday, saying he had no
regrets.
	   Despite an aggressive election campaign and predictions by Ung
Huot that his Reastr Niyum party would win up to 50 of the 122
seats in parliament, it failed to capture a single one.
	   ``I am willing to transfer my power to the new government, the
next government,'' Ung Huot, who is also foreign minister, said in
an address to be aired on state-run television. ``I appeal to all
Cambodians, whatever their political aspiration, to accept the
result.''
	   Cambodian leader Hun Sen deposed Ranariddh as his co-prime
minister in last year's violent coup, shattering a tense dual
premiership formed after the U.N.-sponsored elections in 1993. At
least 100 supporters of Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC party were killed by
Hun Sen's forces in the months that followed.
	   The prince and his loyalists spent months in exile before
returning with international backing to participate in elections.
	   Ung Huot and a handful of other FUNCINPEC members, several of
them ministers in Ranariddh's government, stayed behind to give
their support to Hun Sen, lending his administration a stamp of
legitimacy. Ung Huot was appointed Hun Sen's new co-premier.
	   Though he was sharply criticized by loyal FUNCINPEC members and
by ordinary Cambodians who saw his actions as a betrayal, Ung Huot
defended the move at the time as necessary to bring a return to
political stability.
	   ``I think what I did was right for the moment,'' he said Monday.
``I never thought it was a mistake.''
	   When elections were called earlier this year, Ung Huot formed
his own party. Despite what he thought was a sure fire campaign
pledge _ to shoot violent criminals on sight _ he failed to capture
the public's loyalty.
	   Ung Huot has now joined FUNCINPEC in complaining about
irregularities in the counting of ballots, but he said Monday that
if the National Election Committee determines that the polls were
free, fair and credible, he will step aside gracefully.
	   ``I feel sad, but that is the verdict of the people,'' he said,
adding that he intends to remain politically active. ``We will have
to look at our shortfalls, strengths and weaknesses, and after a
period of political stability will rethink our strategy.''	   
</TEXT>
