<HEADLINE>
King Fahd undergoing tests, reported in stable condition
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ King Fahd was to undergo tests in a
Riyadh hospital on Monday, a day after he was admitted for
observation, a medical official said.
	   ``The king is in a stable condition and there is nothing to
worry about,'' said the official, who spoke only on condition his
name not be used.
	   He did not reveal the nature of the king's medical problems. He
added that Fahd was not expected to remain in the hospital for
long.
	   Diplomats in Saudi Arabia had said Sunday that the king was
taken to the King Faisal Specialist Hospital for treatment of an
illness. But the medical official said the king merely was
undergoing routine medical tests.
	   Fahd's health has been the source of much speculation since he
suffered a stroke in November 1995 and, two months later,
temporarily handed over power to Crown Prince Abdullah, his
half-brother. The crown prince has essentially remained in command
since then.
	   The king was admitted to the same hospital in March for
treatment of a gall bladder infection.
	   Fahd, who is in his mid-70s, has suffered for years from
diabetes and arthritis. 	   
