<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Budget </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukrainian Cabinet prepares to slash government spending
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's Cabinet has prepared a draft
presidential decree on slashing government spending and sent it to
President Leonid Kuchma for signing, the finance minister said
Monday.
	   The measure is part of Cabinet efforts to adopt a new 1998
budget that will meet the demands of international financial
organizations.
	   Ukraine's parliament last month failed to discuss the budget,
leaving it to the government to adopt the required changes.
Officials have said the new budget would be implemented by a
presidential decree in early August.
	   The International Monetary Fund, which is considering a new loan
to Ukraine, has made adoption of a more frugal budget a key
requirement.
	   An IMF mission which visited Kiev last week said it would
recommend the disbursement of a dlrs 2.2 billion loan for the
cash-strapped former Soviet republic.
	   Finance Minister Ihor Mityukov said the decree would only
address spending, leaving revenues for parliament to discuss, the
Interfax news agency reported. Mityukov did not provide concrete
figures.
	   An earlier draft provided for revenues of 17.9 billion hryvna
(dlrs 8.95 billion), spending of 20.24 billion hryvna (dlrs 10.12
billion) and a deficit of 2.34 billion hryvna (dlrs 1.17 billion),
or 2.3 percent of GDP.
	   (sms/mr)
</TEXT>
