</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Nadir Pilot </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pilot faces jail for helping businessman Nadir escape Britain
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ A man who helped indicted businessman Asil Nadir
escape Britain in a sensational flight to northern Cyprus was
convicted Monday of obstructing justice and now faces a likely jail
sentence.
	   Judge Michael Hyam told Peter Dimond he will probably go to
prison for enabling Nadir, the former chairman of collapsed food
and electronics conglomerate Polly Peck, to flee Britain in 1993.
	   ``The real question is how long and I will need a social inquiry
report to help me,'' Hyam told Dimond, who showed no emotion in
court.
	   Dimond, 56, is free on bail while the judge has time to obtain
and study a report on his background. It was not immediately clear
when he will be sentenced.
	   After deliberating for five hours, a jury of eight women and
three men at the Old Bailey convicted Dimond of charges that he
perverted the course of justice between January and May 1993, when
Nadir began planning his flight and then took off.
	   Nadir's escape was a wild climax to one of Britain's more
dramatic boom-and-bust stories.
	   Polly Peck grew dramatically in the early 1980s, but eventually
collapsed in 1991 with debts of dlrs 2.1 billion after
investigators began probing irregularities in Nadir's finances.
	   Nadir claimed he could not get a fair trial in Britain and in
May 1993 he jumped dlrs 5.2 million bail to flee to northern
Cyprus, a self-proclaimed nation recognized only by Turkey.
	   He still faces 13 charges of theft in Britain involving 30
million pounds, or about dlrs 48 million, from his companies. But
Britain has little chance of bringing Nadir to trial _ it has no
extradition treaty with northern Cyprus and Turkey has refused to
send him.
	   The prosecution said Dimond arranged the light aircraft that
spirited Nadir to northern France, where he boarded an executive
jet bound for Cyprus via Vienna and Istanbul.
	   Dimond is a pilot but did no flying on the journey. He
accompanied Nadir and remained with him in Cyprus until January
1998, when he returned to Britain on business and was arrested.
	   Dimond testified he believed Nadir had been unfairly treated by
British authorities and needed a chance to prepare his case before
returning to Britain to face trial.
	   ``I always thought it would be sorted. I never doubted his
integrity,'' Dimond testified.
	   A spokesman for Nadir refused comment on the verdict.
	   (scl-db)
</TEXT>
