<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwanese protest atrocities in Indonesia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ About 200 Taiwanese, shouting
``murderers,'' protested outside the Indonesian mission Monday to
denounce atrocities against ethnic Chinese.
	   They burned incense sticks and set up an altar to mourn the
ethnic Chinese killed during the May uprising that brought down
Indonesian President Suharto.
	   Lawmaker Lee Ching-hua, who led the protesters, demanded that
the Indonesian government apologize, compensate the victims and
reassure the world that similar incidents will never happen again.
	   More than 1,000 people died in Jakarta alone in rioting over
price increases. Women's groups say at least 168 women were raped
by rioters.
	   Many of the victims were members of the ethnic Chinese minority,
which controls much of the economy and often is made a scapegoat in
difficult times. Indonesia is undergoing its worst economic crisis
in decades.
	   Human rights activists have widely accused the military, and a
government inquiry is under way.
	   Protesters later moved to the Foreign Ministry to demand that
the Taiwan government suspend planned economic aid and order a
pullout of Taiwanese investment from Indonesia.
	   In response, Foreign Minister Jason Hu said Indonesian President
B.J. Habibie has assured Taiwanese officials that authorities will
severely punish those responsible.
	   Meanwhile, organizers of a world conference of Chinese writers
said five ethnic Chinese writers were barred from leaving for
Taiwan. The writers were to report on the atrocities in Indonesia
at the meeting that opened Monday, they said.
	   Taiwan does not have diplomatic relations with Indonesia. But
Taiwanese have invested U.S. dlrs 13.2 billion in Indonesia, and
several Taiwanese factories were ransacked during the May uprising.	   
</TEXT>
