<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Georgia-Russian Peacekeepers, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Georgian president wants Russian peacekeepers to stay in Abkhazia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT spelling to ``forces'' sted
``forcers.'' &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ Georgia's president said Monday he
favored keeping Russian peacekeepers in the country's breakaway
Abkhazia region.
	   The peacekeeping force's mandate to monitor the region expired
July 31. It can be extended by a vote of leaders of all the
countries in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), but
Georgia has ultimate control over whether the troops stay or leave.
	   If Russian peacekeepers leave Abkhazia, ``certain forces might
attempt to again drag Georgia into a full-scale war,'' Georgian
president Eduard Shevardnadze said in a Monday radio address.
	   ``I think it is unreasonable to withdraw Russian peacekeepers
unless the question of their replacement is cleared up,'' he said.
	   The Russian peacekeepers were sent to stabilize the Black Sea
province of Abkhazia in 1994 following a war in which Abkhazian
separatists drove out Georgian government troops. Sporadic violence
keeps tensions in the region high.
	   Shevardnadze has often criticized the Russian troops for not
doing enough to help ethnic Georgian refugees move back into
Abkhazia. But he said the Russian troops were needed to maintain
safety for thousands of refugees beginning to return home.
	   More than 40,000 ethnic Georgians fled Abkhazia's Ghali region
during fighting in May between separatists and pro-government
militants.
	   The United Nations agreed last week to keep unarmed military
observers in Georgia for another six months and urged both sides in
the conflict to continue negotiating for a long-term peace.
	   (nw/gm)
</TEXT>
