<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Interior Ministry </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iranian interior minister handed security forces
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran's newly appointed interior minister, an
ally of moderate President Mohammad Khatami, was given control of
the powerful police forces by the country's top religious leader,
Iran newspaper reported Monday.
	   The move signals a small victory for Iran's moderate faction,
locked in a power struggle with hard-liners in the ruling clergy.
	   Although Khatami is the elected leader, the constitution gives
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the supreme leader, control of such key
instruments of power as the police, army and judiciary.
	   In a letter to Khamenei, Interior Minister Abdolvahed Mousavi
Lari asked that ``control of the security forces be placed with the
Interior Ministry, which is charged with maintaining security,''
the newspaper said. It did not say when the letter was written.
	   Control of Iran's police forces is traditionally in the hands of
the interior minister. But that responsibility was withheld from
Lari's predecessor, who was impeached last month by the hard-line
parliament for attempting to ease the strict Islamic social code
and promote public freedoms.
	   The police are in charge of security in the streets, enforcing
the strict Islamic dress code on women and ensuring that unmarried
couples do not mingle.
	   The handover followed the attack on the editor of the liberal
newspaper Toos and two Associated Press reporters Saturday. In
another victory for the moderate faction, the newspaper, which was
banned from publishing by the hard-line clergy on Saturday, was
being distributed again Monday.
	   The judiciary, which has the power to close down newspapers,
yielded to the urging of officials from the Ministry of Culture and
Islamic Guidance for the paper to continue publishing, Iran News
reported Monday. The Culture Ministry, run by a Khatami loyalist,
issues permits for newspapers.
 &UR; fsa-as
</TEXT>
