r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-ConvictedLeg     08-03 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Convicted Legislator </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Businessman gets three years in jail, may lose seat in legislature
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ An eight-year veteran of Hong Kong's
legislature famous for his outspoken and high-spending ways was
sentenced Monday to three years in prison for plotting forgery in a
land deal.
	   Chim Pui-chung could have received up to 14 years in prison on
the charge stemming from a 350 million Hong Kong dollar (dlrs 44.8
million) land deal in 1992. He said he would appeal.
	   Under the basic law, Hong Kong's constitution after it was
returned to China last year, members may be removed from the
legislature by a two-thirds vote of its 60 members if they are
found guilty of crimes and sentenced to more than a month in jail.
	   Some legislators have said that the body risks its reputation if
it allows Chim to stay.
	   Chim, who rides around Hong Kong in a gold Rolls Royce, was
found guilty by a nine-member jury Saturday. He was found innocent
of five other charges stemming from the same land deal.
	   In the legislature, he represents the financial services
industry, and was re-elected in May in balloting by only about 300
people _ members of the financial services industry.
	   Chim's case could tarnish the reputation of the majority of the
legislature that is not chosen by direct, popular vote at a time
when there are increasing calls for broadening democracy in Hong
Kong.
	   Legislative officials called a meeting for Wednesday to discuss
his case.
	   If Chim is removed, a new election would be held to fill his
post.
	   The South China Morning Post on Sunday quoted Martin Lee, leader
of the largest party, the Democrats, and Emily Lau of the Frontier
movement as saying there was no need for the legislature to wait
for the result of Chim's appeal before it acted.
	   Lee was quoted as saying that it would ``discredit the
legislature if a convicted ... member is not disqualified.''
	   Only 20 members of the legislature were chosen by direct,
popular vote in May 24 elections. The number is to increase slowly
in the next 10 years.
	   Thirty members, including Chim, were chosen by elections within
specified professions, and the final 10 by an 800-member election
committee. Those 40 seats are dominated by pro-Beijing elites.	   
</TEXT>
