<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Fighting, 1st Ld-Writethru,0676 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede ISLAMABAD
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Opposition says Taliban will get fight in Mazar-e-Sharif &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with comment from northern alliance,
Taliban official saying no decision on Mazar-e-Sharif attack,
Mazar-e-Sharif airport closed, civilians fleeing, other details.
ADDS byline and photo number &QL; 
 &UR; By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) _ Though the Taliban army met little
resistance when it took a key town nearby, the religious militia
will not have such an easy time in the opposition stronghold of
Mazar-e-Sharif, a northern alliance spokesman said Monday.
	   ``Our forces are ready to defend Mazar-e-Sharif. If the Taliban
try to capture Mazar-e-Sharif, they will face heavy resistance,''
said Zabet Saliy, spokesman for anti-Taliban military leader Ahmed
Shah Masood. ``They will repeat the mistake they committed last
year.''
	   Taliban fighters briefly held Mazar-e-Sharif last May,
retreating after street battles that left several hundred Taliban
soldiers dead. It is believed that as many as 2,000 Taliban
prisoners of war were later massacred.
	   Taliban fighters have been bolstered by a series of recent
victories and appear poised to capture all of Afghanistan. They
claim to be closing in on Mazar-e-Sharif from two directions, and
also claim to have gained ground in eastern Afghanistan on Monday.
	   Taliban leaders have imposed a strict version of Islamic law in
territory they control. Since capturing Kabul in 1996, Taliban
officials have barred girls from school, confined most women to
their homes, and declared that time once spent watching now-banned
television should be devoted to prayer.
	   The fractious anti-Taliban coalition is made of mostly of
Afghanistan's minority ethnic and religious groups.
	   Wekil Ahmad Muttawkil, a Taliban spokesman at the militia's
headquarters in the southern city of Kandahar, said leaders had not
yet decided whether to attack Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Last year's tough battle for Mazar-e-Sharif contrasts with
sketchy descriptions of Sunday's fall of Shebergan, the stronghold
of warlord Rashid Dostum that is located 100 kilometers (60 miles)
west of Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Dostum has joined Masood and the Hezb-e-Wahadat militia that
controls Mazar-e-Sharif against the Taliban, but his fighters also
clashed with Hezb-e-Wahadat in Mazar-e-Sharif last year.
	   Taliban officials said casualties were low and a large number of
prisoners of war were captured. Dostum's forces reportedly set fire
to Shebergan airport as they left, destroying several fighter jets.
	   Saliy, speaking by satellite telephone from northern
Afghanistan, said Dostum's men put up little resistance after some
of their commanders were paid off by the Taliban. Such mercenary
switching of loyalties has long been a hallmark of the Afghan civil
war.
	   After fleeing Shebergan on Sunday, Dostum retreated to Hayratan,
about 60 kilometers (40 miles) east of Mazar-e-Sharif on
Afghanistan's border with Uzbekistan and was trying to reorganize
his forces, Saliy said. Other members of the northern-based
anti-Taliban alliance met in Mazar-e-Sharif on Monday to assess the
military situation, Saliy said.
	   In neighboring Pakistan on Monday, Red Cross spokesman Michel
Schaffner said about 10 international aid workers in Mazar-e-Sharif
had asked the Red Cross to evacuate them, but no plane was able to
travel there because the airport was closed. Schaffner said it was
not clear why the airport was closed, and called the security
situation unpredictable.
	   Seven expatriate Red Cross workers flew out of Mazar-e-Sharif to
the Afghan capital of Kabul on Sunday, leaving behind a handful of
Afghan staff, Schaffner said. Their departure was routine, he said.
The Red Cross has been overseeing projects in Mazar-e-Sharif from
Kabul for safety reasons.
	   Independent sources speaking on condition of anonymity said
civilians were fleeing Mazar-e-Sharif in anticipation of fighting,
but the city was fairly calm Monday. 	   
</TEXT>
