<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Appeals court upholds death sentences; police crack heroin ring
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ A Vietnam appeals court has upheld the
death penalty for three men, including a Taiwanese, for involvement
in drug trafficking, a court official said Monday.
	   Last November, a preliminary court sentenced Chen Chi-tien of
Taiwan and associates Tram Huy and Phung Phu to death on charges of
illegal manufacture, trade and possession of drugs. A fourth man
was sentenced to life in prison for possession.
	   Police raided Tai's house in Ho Chi Minh City in May 1995 and
found 170.5 kilograms (376 pounds) of high-quality methamphetamine.
The defendants reportedly confessed they had produced the same drug
three other times over the previous year.
	   Meanwhile, the newspaper Youth reported that police in Ho Chi
Minh City last week arrested 13 heroin dealers who were supplying
about 2,000 addicts.
	   Drug use is a rising problem for Vietnam, where more than 30
traffickers have been condemned to death since early this year.	   
</TEXT>
