</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Minister: China has promised not to devalue currency
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ China has promised not to devalue
its currency so as not to exacerbate the Asian economic crisis,
Malaysia's foreign minister said Monday after talks with Chinese
officials.
	   The commitment to maintain the yuan at its current levels was
conveyed to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad by visiting Chinese
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, said Abdullah Ahmad Badawi.
	   The move by China is important to countries in the region,
Abdullah told reporters.
	   Tang met Mahathir a few hours before he ended his four-day stay
in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Asian nations have repeatedly sought assurances from Beijing on
its currency. A devalued currency would make Chinese exports
cheaper, hurting neighboring economies that are already reeling
from last year's currency battering.
	   China has been losing money in trade because its non-convertible
currency has not been devalued.
	   Tang also confirmed President Jiang Zemin's participation in the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit scheduled in Kuala Lumpur
in November, Abdullah said.	   
</TEXT>
