w2629 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-FarmerProtest     08-03 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Farmer Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polish farmers block border crossing to demand ban on grain
</HEADLINE>
imports &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Dozens of farmers spilled about 1,200 tons
of imported grain at the Polish-Czech border Monday in a protest
demanding a ban on grain imports.
	   The 60 farmers from the Solidarity trade union unlatched rail
freight cars at Muszyna, 370 kilometers (230 miles) south of
Warsaw, spilling the grain imported from Hungary and Slovakia
across the rail line to block traffic, PAP news agency reported.
	   The farmers want a total ban on imported grain and for the
government to prosecute anyone responsible for permitting imports.
It was the latest in a series of farmers' protests this summer to
demand more government protection of the agriculture industry.
	   In response, the government has promised to triple state
purchases of Polish grain and increase custom fees on grain imports
beginning Thursday.
	   ``That should discourage importers or at least reduce imports,''
said Krzysztof Trawinski of the Agriculture Ministry. He said a
total ban demanded by the farmers would violate international trade
agreements signed by Poland.
	   But farmers' leader Marian Zagorny said protests against grain
imports would spread across the country if the government fails to
meet farmers' demands immediately.
	   The farmers' Solidarity trade union has some 400,000 members in
the 4-million strong farmer lobby.
	   Polish agriculture remains hobbled by small, poorly equipped
farms unable to compete with larger, more modern farms in Western
Europe. Calls for reforms to consolidate farms and make them more
efficient in preparation for Poland's bid to join the European
Union have been resisted by farmers, who fear losing control of
their land and having to work for others.
	   (bp-tsc)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
