<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Kashmir, 1st Ld,0260 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indian shelling kills three more people in Pakistani Kashmir
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with report Indian brigade headquarters hit in new
graf 2, reported Indian casualties to 30 in graf 5 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Shelling by Indian troops killed
three more people, including two children, in the
Pakistan-controlled area of Kashmir on Monday, raising the number
of Pakistanis killed in the shelling during the last five days to
54, army officials said.
	   Associated Press of Pakistan added that Pakistani shells hit an
Indian brigade headquarters in the Kargil district of Indian-held
Kashmir. The news agency, quoting unnamed sources, said that
casualties were believed to be high. But India's defense ministry
reported no firing in Kargil on Monday, saying Pakistani attacks
had subsided.
	   The two children were killed when Indian forces launched shells
at Atmaqam in Neelam Valley, 50 kilometers (30 miles) from
Muzaffarabad, the capitol of Pakistan-held Kashmir. Another man was
killed in shelling in Bhimber sector near the border, they said.
	   The number of deaths were low because most people had fled from
the border villages and the intensity of India's shelling has
eased, the officials said on customary condition of anonymity.
	   In a statement Monday, the India Ministry of Defense said eight
soldiers and 22 civilians were killed by Pakistani forces, a
slightly lower toll than army sources had reported previously.
Pakistan says most of its casualties were also civilian.
	    &UR; Witnesses say, 5th graf 	   
</TEXT>
