r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-Ho     08-03 0179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Ho </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Taiwan to honor former general
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Taiwan's ruling Nationalist Party will
honor former Gen. Ho Sai-lai for his contributions to the country,
the official news agency reported Monday.
	   It will present national and party flags to the relatives of Ho,
who died in Hong Kong July 26, for use at his funeral scheduled
Wednesday, the Central News Agency said. Ho was 92.
	   Ho was the son of Robert Hotung, the comprador for Jardine's,
one of the first and largest of the foreign trading houses in Hong
Kong. Compradors were Chinese who served as middlemen between the
traders and the Chinese bureaucracy.
	   He attended military academies in Britain and France, and served
in the Nationalist army, which was defeated by the Communists and
fled the Chinese mainland for Taiwan in 1949.
	   Ho headed the Nationalist military delegations in Japan and
later in the United Nations between 1950 and 1962 before he retired
and settled in Hong Kong, the report said. He later was appointed a
Taiwanese presidential adviser.	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
