 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  APTV 1300 GMT OUTLOOK FOR MONDAY 3 AUGUST 1998  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 

 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the
next 12 hours  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
EXPECTED:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
P'PINES: COHEN - U-S Defense Secretary William Cohen is in Manila
for talks on greater U-S military access to the islands. APTV plans
coverage of Cohen's meeting with President Joseph Estrada and
Defence Secretary Orlando Mercado and protests against the American
visit. (First Run Expected After 1300)
----
IRAQ: BUTLER 2 - U-N chief weapons inspector Richard Butler is in
Baghdad for more talks with Iraqi Deputy Tariq Aziz, who accuses the
weapons chief of dragging out the inspections.  The start of the
talks (Europe Late 1500) will be added to earlier piece featuring
soundbites from Baghdad citizens on the UNSCOM program in Iraq and
comment from Butler on the eve of his talks.  (First Run 0900 The
Americas)
----
RUSSIA: NUCLEAR - Russia is embarking on a plan to build new, safer
power stations and close down aged ones using funds provided by
European countries. APTV covers a news conference about the future
of Russia's nuclear power program under the proposal, which will
oversee the construction of four new plants. (Europe Late 1500)
----
AUSTRIA: ART -  A bizarre artistic event is set to take place in
Austria, where a native artist - whose sponsors include David Bowie
and Yoko Ono - will slaughter a series of animals before 2000 people
in what he is calling the culmination of his life's work. Three
bulls, and six pigs will be killed, crucified and disembowelled
during Hermann Nitsch's 'Six Day Orgy Mystery Theatre' at his castle
near Mistelbach. Item includes arrivals and protests outside the
castle.  (APTV Eurovision 1440)
----
TURKEY: PALACE - APTV has visited an archaeological site in Turkey
where diggers have uncovered the remnants of a 6th century Byzantine
palace.   In addition to pictures from the site, we talk to the head
of the archeological team and an independent American archaeologist
about the discovery.  (Europe Late 1500)
----
US: COURT MARTIAL -  APTV covers the start of court martial
proceedings in Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, for the four U-S
Marines involved in the February in-flight accident which sent an
Italian ski gondola crashing to the ground, killing 20 people.
(Europe Late 1500)
----
RUNNING:
 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
UK: REES-JONES -  Trevor Rees-Jones - the only survivor of the car
crash which killed Diana, Princess of Wales, Dodi Fayed, and their
driver - has talked on television for the first time. He spoke
exclusively to APTV in advance of the first anniversary of the fatal
crash on August 31. (Available to all broadcasters but not other
video agencies. Non-APTV clients must super caption: Pictures
courtesy APTV)  (First Run 0900 The Americas)
----
REES-JONES: BACKGROUNDER - APTV has a backgrounder piece on Trevor
Rees-Jones and the car crash he survived which killed Diana,
Princess of Wales.  It accompanies the exclusive APTV interview with
Jones. (First Run 0900 the Americas)
----
UK: SAUDI - As King Fahd of Saudi Arabia remains in the hospital
amid rising fears over his health, his youngest son, Prince
Abdulaziz bin Fahd, insists in an APTV interview that his father is
fit and well.  The King, whose condition is stable, has raised
concerns in the MidEast over his health after being hospitalised on
Sunday for what was being called routine 'medical testing.'  The
prince spoke to APTV during a visit to Edinburgh, Scotland.  (First
Run 1130 Europe Update)
---
KOSOVO: BODIES - Serbian government forces press on in their attacks
against ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo, despite Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's pledge that the latest offensive was
over.  APTV has pictures from the Drenica region and comment from a
Kosovo Liberation Army soldier.  (First Run 0900 The Americas)
----
POLAND: GERMANY - Disputes over property dating back to World War
II are beginning to resurface in Poland between native Poles and
Germans who used to live there before the war. APTV's feature
includes coverage from Gdansk and Frankfurt, soundbites from Poles
fearing they risk losing their homes and comments from the German
Union of Expellees in the dispute, which could hamper Poland's
attempts to gain entry to the European Union. (FIRST RUN 0800 EUROPE
MORNING)
----
MIDEAST: PEACE - Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his
cabinet met on Monday, hours before another session of
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations on Middle East peace.  Includes
soundbite from Ahmed Tibi, an adviser to Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, who says it is up to Israel to make the next move to salvage
talks.
Also includes a demonstration by Palestinian families in the Gaza
Strip protesting Palestinian prisoners held in Israeli jails. (First
Run 1130 Europe Update)
----
ETIMOR: REBELS - As the United Nations prepares to debate the
situation in East Timor, the territory's key rebel leader is calling
for direct international involvement in the island's future. In an
exclusive interview with APTV - his first since becoming commander -
Taur Matan Ruak branded recent Indonesian troop withdrawals a
``publicity stunt'' and vowed to fight on for independence. Features
pictures of  Falintil Army troops on manoeuvre.  (FIRST RUN 0715
ASIA PACIFIC LATE)
----
INDONESIA: CHILDREN - APTV looks at the impact of the economic
crisis in Indonesia on the country's children. With their parents
out of work and desperate, more and more children are being put to
work to help their families make ends meet. The feature contains
interviews with some children labourers who have been forced to
rummage through rubbish dumps for items to sell to recycling
companies, as well as comments from children's rights activists.
(FIRST RUN 0715 ASIA PACIFIC LATE)
----
Editor of the Night:  44 171 427 4100
Master Control Room :  44 171 427 4131
