<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-North Korea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese top brass visit North Korea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Senior Chinese military officials traveled to
Pyongyang Monday for exchanges with their North Korean
counterparts, China's official Xinhua News Agency reported.
	   Lt. Gen. Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of staff of the People's
Liberation Army, led a delegation of officers on a goodwill visit
at the invitation of North Korea's military, Xinhua said.
	   High-level exchanges between the former comrades in arms
continue despite Beijing's growing closeness to South Korea.
	   China opened formal diplomatic relations with Seoul in 1992 and
trade between the two has since flourished.
	   At the same time, China has been a source of urgently needed
food and fuel for isolated North Korea and has encouraged its
communist ally to adopt reforms similar to Beijing's own
market-oriented policies to revive its failing economy.
	   China fought on the North's side in the 1950-53 Korean War and
Chinese leaders still profess to a ``profound friendship'' between
Beijing and Pyongyang.	   
</TEXT>
