w2637 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MiddleEastBusinessBri     08-03 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan, Israel, Egypt, Kuwait.

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Italian oil giant ENPPI and Egypt's Petrojet
are building a new pipeline that will transport natural gas from
northern Egypt to the Sinai peninsula, the daily Al-Ahram said
Monday.
	   The pipeline, which will extend from the Bahariya gas fields
north of Port Said to the Sheikh Zweid region in northern Sinai, is
part of a government plan to increase natural gas production from
112 million cubic meters per day to 463 million, Oil Minister Hamdy
el-Banbi was quoted as saying by the paper.
	   The dlrs 164 million pipeline, which will cross under the Suez
Canal, will be linked to the national gas grid.
 &UR; __
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ In a bid to end a shortage of cement, a
Cabinet ministerial committee ordered the doubling of production to
3 million tons this month, the daily Al-Ahram reported Monday.
	   The decision by the Ministerial Committee on Cement, headed by
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzoury, also allows the public and
private sectors to purchase cement directly from the factory
instead of going through licensed traders, said the paper, quoting
Minister of Cabinet Affairs Talaat Hammad.
	   The decision comes at a time when the government has accused a
group of traders of monopolizing the market by purchasing cement,
holding on to their stock and thereby inflating the price to nearly
300 pounds per ton (dlrs 85).
	   The decree also orders the tax authority to investigate traders
and collect outstanding taxes on profits. It said traders who
withheld the sale of cement would be fined. It did not give a
figure.
	   Egypt produced about 20.772 million tons of cement in 1997-98
and imported 2.9 million tons to meet local demands, the paper
said.
	   Cement shortages are common during the months of July and August
when construction projects increase.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Some 80 South African companies will exhibit their
products and services in Kuwait for the first time later this year,
the organizer of the trade show said Monday.
	   ``The whole idea is to increase export from South Africa to
Kuwait,'' said Emiranda Coetzer of South Africa's Challenge
Exhibition Group. She said Kuwait imports fruits and vegetables
from the African nation and is South Africa's second largest oil
supplier, providing 16 percent of its oil imports.
	   Coetzer said the three-day show will open Nov. 3 and will
include seminars on investment opportunities in South Africa. The
companies will show clothes, jewelry, military equipment and
furniture. Tourist and construction companies will also be
represented.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) - Parliament approved Monday a government request to
reschedule the payment of hundreds of millions of dollars in bad
debts owed by private investors to the Central Bank.
	   Twenty-six of the 39 legislators and ministers who attended the
session voted for the amendment to the bad debts law. Thirteen
voted against.
	   The 6.7 billion dinars (dlrs 21.89 billion) in debts soured
after a 1982 crash of an unofficial stock market and were
aggravated by Iraq's 1990 invasion of this oil-rich state. After
the 1991 liberation, the government took over debts owed by 10,400
individuals from private banks in a debts-for-bonds deal.
	   The amendment will allow defaulters to rejoin the program and
pay their dues by the end of June 1999. Debtors who had to make two
more major payments, the first of which was due Sept. 6, can now
pay in three installments instead of two _ the first on Sept. 6,
1999 and the last on Sept. 6, 2000.
	   The government believes the rescheduling will increase chances
of payment, but many lawmakers accused it of favoring wealthy
merchant debtors at the expense of public money.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan and Iraq have agreed to upgrade
commercial and economic ties, an official said Monday.
	   A joint Jordanian-Iraqi higher committee held several meetings
here in the past two days and was expected to complete trade talks
on Tuesday, said Haidar Murad, Chairman of Jordanian Chamber of
Commerce Federation.
	   He said the volume of trade exchange between Jordan and Iraq
exceeded dlrs 250 million last year.
	   Zuhair Abdul Ghafour Yunis, head of the Iraqi delegation to the
talks said efforts were underway to increase trade to dlrs 400
million.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordanian and foreign investors based at an
industrial free trade zone in the northern city of Irbid have
complained that Israel's 11.7 percent input that makes it benefit
from U.S. concessions is too high and should be lowered to 8
percent, the chairman of the Century Investment Group said Monday.
	   Omar Salah said heavy weight industrialists are not willing to
apply for a duty free status in U.S. markets before Israel lowers
its input.
	   Salah said the U.S. Trade Department is surprised that since the
creation of the zone in March no one had applied for a duty free
entry to U.S. markets.
	   Under the zone agreement signed between Jordan and Israel last
November, Jordanian and Israeli manufacturers should each
contribute an input of at least 11.7 percent from the minimum 35
percent.
	   Both manufacturers could also contribute 20 percent of the total
cost of production, Salah said.
	   ``The Israelis are showing some flexibility and are expected to
cooperate because they do not want to hinder the growth of
Jordan,'' Salah said.
 &UR; buros-sf 	   
</TEXT>
