<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-British Tourists </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spanish judge probes highway accident that left five British
</HEADLINE>
tourists dead &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   OLIVA, Spain (AP) _ A Spanish judge opened an investigation
Monday into the cause of a collision in which five young British
tourists were killed a day earlier.
	   The tourists, two women and three men aged between 18 and 25,
were returning to the holiday resort town of Benidorm from Valencia
city Sunday when their hired car collided with a truck close to the
town of Oliva. The five were killed instantly.
	   They were identified as Samuel Otaimaga, 23, of Kent, and Vivian
Obleajula, 21, Ian Boatswain, 21, Kara Jaimimi, 21 and Falelat
Oluremelekun, 24, all from London, a British Foreign Office
spokeswoman said.
	   The truck driver was unhurt in the accident.
	   Traffic was diverted around the accident for two hours while
firemen pried open the wreckage to remove the bodies. Fifty people
were killed in road accidents across the country in what was
Spain's busiest holiday weekend.
	   The remains of the five Britons were being kept at a morgue in
the coastal town of Gandia, just north of Oliva, before being
repatriated.
	   (mr/cg) 	   
</TEXT>
