<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Auto Sales </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Auto sales slump in Japan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's sluggish economy and rising unemployment
took its toll on auto sales in July, pushing them down for the 16th
straight month, producers announced Monday.
	   The Japan Automobile Dealers Association said sales of new cars,
trucks and buses, as measured by registrations, fell 8.4 percent in
July from the year-earlier month to 432,221.
	   Passenger car sales slipped 0.5 percent to 323,881, truck sales
dropped 26 percent to 107,210 and bus sales dipped 15 percent to
1,130. The figures don't include sales of mini-cars and
mini-trucks.
	   A spokesman for the association said the payment of summer
bonuses by Japanese companies to their employees failed to boost
sales much. He said a weak labor market with a record level of
unemployment of 4.3 percent for June may have been a reason for
that.
	   The association didn't make a forecast for the full year, but
the spokesman said that with sales down 18 percent in the
January-June period, it couldn't be expected that full-year sales
would surpass those of the previous year.
	   Analysts forecast that sales for the full fiscal year ending
March 31 will decline.
	   The spokesman for the association said he hoped the new
government of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi would move quickly to
implement new economic stimulus measures, including tax cuts.
	   By maker, sales of three companies rose in July: Honda's
increased 3.7 percent to 44,191 vehicles, Mazda's grew 4.5 percent
to 26,983 and Daihatsu's expanded 14 percent to 4,113.
	   Among other makers, Toyota's July sales fell 6.3 percent to
173,486 vehicles, Nissan's dropped 9.1 percent to 94,907,
Mitsubishi Motors' declined 22 percent to 31,603 and Isuzu's fell
31 percent to 6,724.
	   Sales of imported vehicles in Japan fell 20 percent in July to
25,145.
 &UR; (jc-apdj)	   
