</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Czech-Havel Surgery, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Havel undergoes tracheotomy, doctors fear pneumonia developing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes, additional information
 &UR; By ONDREJ HEJMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Czech President Vaclav Havel
underwent a tracheotomy Monday amid fears he might be developing
pneumonia eight days after serious abdominal surgery.
	   ``We're looking at a lung inflammation here. You could call it a
potential pneumonia,'' Boris Stastny, a member of Havel's medical
team, said after Monday's operation at Prague's military hospital.
	   Doctors performed a tracheotomy, a routine surgery during which
a small artificial hole is made in the throat to facilitate
breathing.
	   Following the operation, Havel was in the hospital's
intensive-care unit.
	   Doctors said Havel's temperature was back to normal but he will
be kept sedated till Tuesday.
	   ``The only problem ... is that we have already carried out a
tracheotomy for the fourth time in the same place, which is very
scarred by now,'' said Professor Ernst Bodner of the Innsbruck
University Clinic, who performed the 90-minute surgery.
	   Havel has had tracheotomies three times previously.
	   Bodner operated on Havel in April when the president's colon
ruptured while he was vacationing in Austria.
	   Bodner was part of a Czech-Austrian team of doctors who operated
on Havel in Prague to restore his digestive tract July 26.
	   The surgery had been declared successful, but Havel's overall
recovery was hindered by breathing problems.
	   The 61-year-old president, formerly a chain smoker, has been
hospitalized five times since December 1996, when he had a third of
his lung and a tumor removed.
	   Last week, Havel's lungs collapsed briefly, forcing the use of
respirator, common after all of his surgeries.
	   Feeling optimistic, doctors took Havel off the respirator
Saturday night and waited to see if the president could breathe
without help.
	   Late Sunday, Havel's temperature shot up to 39 degrees Celsius
(102 degrees Fahrenheit), his heartbeat went up and laboratory
findings indicated a lung inflammation, doctors said.
	   According to experts, Havel will need a minimum of six weeks to
fully recover. He is scheduled for an official visit to the United
States in September.
	   (oh/scl)
</TEXT>
