w2650 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Vietnam-CurrencyPress     08-03 0255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Currency Pressure </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top banker warns of weak yen, possible yuan devaluation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ The government is worried that the weak
Japanese yen could force devaluation of the Chinese yuan, with
unpredictable dangers for Vietnam's economy, the newspaper
Investment reported Monday.
	   ``If the Japanese yen continues to be unstable, the Chinese yuan
will be devalued, and we just cannot foresee what happens next,''
state bank Governor Nguyen Tan Dung, who also is a deputy prime
minister, was quoted as saying.
	   The paper also quoted Nguyen Dong Tien, of the state bank's
Economic Research Department, as saying Japanese economic policies,
especially those related to currency, have a huge impact on
Vietnam's economy and financial system. Japan is Vietnam's major
donor, investor and importer.
	   ``The weaker yen putting pressure on the Chinese yuan creates
some danger to Vietnam's monetary system and economy,'' Tien said.
	   An unidentified state bank official was quoted as saying
devaluation of the yuan is only a matter of time.
	   Even as other currencies plunged during the Asian economic
crisis, Vietnam has kept tight reins on the dong, permitting only
three 5 percent drops over the last year.
	   As a result, Vietnam's exports have become relatively more
expensive than those of its regional competitors. But the
government worries that a major cut in the currency's value will
make much-needed imports more expensive and its dollar-denominated
debts more difficult to repay.	   
</TEXT>
