w2651 &Cx1f; wstm-
b i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sudan-Truce 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Truce, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudan declared unilateral truce in southern Sudan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series, UPDATES with rebel comment, ADDS
byline. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By MOHAMED OSMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Sudan announced Monday a unilateral
cease-fire throughout southern Sudan, where war has caused a
worsening famine. The government urged rebels to follow suit.
	   ``The announcement comes as a further measure in the continuing
effort by the government to contain the humanitarian situation in
southern Sudan,'' a government statement said.
	   Aid workers estimate that about 1.5 million people are facing
starvation in southern Sudan, mainly in Bahr al-Ghazal province, as
a result of drought and the fighting.
	   The U.N. World Food Program is air-dropping 9,500 tons of food a
month _ at a cost of dlrs 30 million _ into the south in the
world's largest aid operation.
	   The cease-fire declaration expands the scope of a limited
three-month truce reached in July between the government and the
rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army. It comes on the eve of peace
talks between the warring parties in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
	   The government did not say how long the truce would last.
	   ``The cease-fire ... is to demonstrate the keenness of the
Sudanese government to prepare the ground for the success of the
peace talks,'' government spokesman Ghazi Salah Eddin Atabani said.
	   ``We hope the rebel movement will listen to the voice of reason
and declare on its part a comprehensive cease fire as well,''
Atabani was quoted as saying by the official Sudan News Agency.
	   A rebel official in Cairo, Egypt, dismissed the announcement.
	   ``This cease-fire is just a maneuver for the talks tomorrow,''
said Daniel Kodi Angelo, an SPLA representative in Cairo, Egypt.
	   But he said he could not comment on the leadership's response.
	   The talks in Addis Ababa will be the first negotiations between
the government and the SPLA since May when the two sides met in
Nairobi, Kenya. They are expected to deal with the issue of
self-determination for the people of southern Sudan and the
relationship between religion and the state.
	   The SPLA has fought since 1983 for autonomy for the south's
Christian and animist peoples from the Islamic north. An estimated
1.5 million have died in the fighting and war-induced famines.
