<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Long Distance Education </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai education officials to delay buying pricey signal receivers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The Thai Education Ministry has delayed
plans to buy 6,775 signal receivers for its satellite classroom
program after the price became unusually high, a senior ministry
official said Monday.
	   The delay came after the government's Budget Bureau suspected
that the private company controlling the educational broadcasting
and the equipment, headed by telecommunications magnate Thaksin
Shinawatra, was pushing up the prices of the receivers.
	   The bureau wants to pay 16,000 baht (dlrs 400) per receiver
while the distributor is offering them at 25,000 to 26,500 baht
(dlrs 625 to dlrs 662) each, the official said.
	   The bureau commented that the price is still extremely high for
the imported receivers, made by the France-based Thomson Co., even
considering the falling value of the baht over the past year, which
has made imports more expensive.
	   The ministry may have to scrap the deal unless it can be
concluded before the end of the fiscal year in two months.
	   The receivers are imported into Thailand solely by Shinawatra
Satellite, which also controls distribution. Shinawatra owns the
Thaicom satellite, which has allowed the ministry to broadcast
educational programs to isolated areas free for four years.
	   The original deal on the project was made when Thaksin, who
entered politics a few years ago, was a Cabinet minister. Officials
from his company refused to comment. Thaksin was not available.	   
</TEXT>
