<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Economy,0377 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With Iran-Khatami's First Year
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Iranian president outlines economic plan &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ President Mohammad Khatami has called for
reducing government monopolies on goods and services, eliminating
the red tape holding back foreign investment and cutting the
country's reliance on oil revenues.
	   The moderate cleric, who took office one year ago, said Iran's
``sick'' economy has suffered from several decades of mismanagement
and needs fundamental changes, such as reducing government
intervention.
	   He outlined his long-awaited economic proposals in a speech
broadcast on state radio late Sunday. The remarks were reported
Monday in the Iran News.
	   Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei approved Khatami's
economic plan and wished the president success in implementing the
reforms, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
	   In his speech, Khatami also called for full implementation of
Islamic banking principles, which forbid interest payments, and
scheduled repayment of Iran's foreign debt, estimated at around
dlrs 15 billion.
	   The paper quoted him as saying that high unemployment and
inflation had cut into the public's purchasing power. Meanwhile, he
said, dependence on oil revenues, a shortage of capital, cumbersome
laws hindering investment and lack of competitiveness were hurting
development.
	   Iran and other Gulf oil producers have been grappling with
rising budget deficits because of low world prices for oil, a main
source of government revenues.
	   Khatami said that despite the economic problems, the government
would maintain subsidies on basic commodities such as rice, cooking
oil and meat.
	   The president also reiterated a commitment to reducing the gap
between rich and poor, a cherished tenet of the 1979 Islamic
revolution, the paper said.
	   Khatami said social justice would prevail over development if a
choice had to be made between the two.
	   He acknowledged that he was unable to give full attention to
economic policy during his first year in office because of
political distractions. Khatami, a reformist, has been involved in
a power struggle with Iran's powerful hard-line clerics since his
elections last year.
</TEXT>
