<SLUG> BC-Spain-Australian Fugitive </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spanish court gives Australian fugitive week to leave
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Madrid, Spain (AP) _ A court has given fugitive Australian
businessman Christopher Skase a week to leave Spain after it
overturned a stay he had won on a deportation order, an official at
the Australian Embassy in Madrid said Monday.
	   Christopher Skase fled to the Spanish Mediterranean island of
Mallorca in 1991 to avoid charges relating to the collapse of his
Qintex business which left him bankrupt in 1991 with debts
amounting to over U.S. dlrs. 1 billion. His extradition was turned
down by Spain in 1994.
	   The latest ruling came after Spanish authorities ordered Skase's
deportation last month when his residency papers expired. Skase's
lawyers then temporarily won a stay on the order.
	   An embassy official, who asked not to be named, said the ruling
was delivered to Skase on Friday and gave him seven days to leave
the country or appeal.
	   With most Spanish courts on vacation in August, the case is not
expected to be resolved until next month.
	   Lawyers for Skase could not be contacted for comment Monday.
	   Australian Justice Minister Amanda Vanstone welcomed the ruling
this weekend but acknowledged that Skase would almost certainly
continue to use all legal means available to him to avoid
deportation.
	   In an interview with a Mallorca newspaper this weekend, Skase
was cited as saying he was confident of staying in Mallorca.
	   (le/cg)
</TEXT>
