w2680 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-AbortionPill     08-03 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Abortion Pill </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition seeks introduction of abortion pill in Germany
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By UTA WINKHAUS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ The opposition Social Democrats are
working toward introduction of the French abortion pill RU-486 in
Germany if they are victorious in September's national elections.
	   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservative government so far has
declined to back the drug, which has been resisted in Germany by
abortion opponents.
	   Social Democratic lawmaker Marliese Dobberthien said Monday that
she has contacted the pill's French patent holder to urge him to
seek European Union approval for marketing the pill in Germany.
	   Edouard Sakiz, the patent holder, said in a telephone interview
from Paris that he would seek approval from EU regulators only if
Germany's federal government backs the plan.
	   The Social Democrats and their chancellor candidate Gerhard
Schroeder, who is leading Kohl in opinion polls, have not taken a
formal position on the abortion pill during the election campaign.
	   But Social Democrats in parliament traditionally have supported
RU-486's introduction, party spokesman Michael Donnermeyer said in
Bonn.
	   The abortion pill, known chemically as mifepristone and
introduced on the market in France in 1988, is available in Europe
only in France, Sweden and Britain.
	   It is 95.5 percent effective in causing abortion when taken
within the first 49 days of pregnancy.
	   The German chemicals and pharmaceuticals company Hoechst
originally owned the RU-486 patent through its French subsidiary
Roussel Uclaf and considered marketing the drug in Germany.
	   But the company said at the time it would do so only with the
backing of Kohl's government, which withheld support. Under
pressure from anti-abortion groups, the company transferred the
patent in April 1997 to Sakiz, one of the developers of the drug.
	   Sakiz produces the drug under a small company in France whose
name he keeps secret, fearing reprisals from abortion opponents.
	   Sakiz said he planned to apply in September to market RU-486 in
further European countries as of Jan. 1. He said Germany was not
yet on the list, but that if Schroeder wins the Sept. 27 election
and announces his government's support for RU-486, he would add
Germany.
 &UR; (im-pfg)
</TEXT>
