w2682 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OAU-Ethiopia-Eritrea     08-03 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Ethiopia-Eritrea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eritrean foreign ministers.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous. CORRECTS identification of Ethiopia and
 &UR; By BRAHIMA OUEDRAOGO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ Feuding neighbors Eritrea and
Ethiopia failed to reach a formula to end their tense border
standoff after two days of separate weekend talks with mediators in
Burkina Faso.
	   The rival Horn of Africa nations pledged not to resume
hostilities until they have held another round of peace
negotiations that have yet to be scheduled.
	   Fighting which flared in early May subsided in mid-June,
following a U.S.-brokered deal to stop deadly air raids. Several
hundred people _ perhaps more _ perished before the stalemate.
	   Breaking from the country's past stance, Eritrea's foreign
minister proposed to withdraw his country's forces from the region
if Ethiopia did the same to create a demilitarized zone.
	   ``We don't need a war to solve a border problem,'' Eritrean
Foreign Minister Haile Woldetensae said.
	   Eritrea had previously refused to consider moving its troops
from land it considers its own. Ethiopia, however, insists on a
pullout before face-to-face talks could proceed.
	   Ethiopia's Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin, however, said later
he was ``not optimistic'' despite the withdrawal offer.
	   The developments came after the opposing ministers met
separately with Burkina Faso's President Blaise Campaore who was
hosting the mediation efforts led by OAU secretary-general Salim
Ahmed Salim.
	   The Eritrean and Ethiopian ministers later held separate talks
with the OAU secretary-general and the foreign ministers of
Zimbabwe and Djibouti.
	   Both parties in the conflict have refused meet face-to-face.
	   Burkina Faso's Foreign Minister Ablasse Ouedraogo said Campaore
would meet soon with the heads of state of Djibouti and Zimbabwe to
discuss the latest developments.
	   The antagonists would subsequently attend another round of
meetings, although no date or venue had been decided on, Ouedraogo
added.
	   Eritrea, which claims rights to the disputed areas under
colonial-era agreements, gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993.
	   (bro-gam/ids) 	   
</TEXT>
