<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro,0255 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Montenegro stops all contacts with Milosevic's government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Montenegro's reformist government
stopped all contacts Monday with the government of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and a minister said a referendum on
secession could be held.
	   The Montenegrin government said they would not communicate with
the Yugoslav government until the federal premier, Momir Bulatovic,
steps down, and another successor from Montenegro is named.
	   Bulatovic, a former Montenegrin president, is a staunch ally of
Milosevic.
	   Montenegro and the much larger Serbia are the only two republics
that remained part of Yugoslavia as the country crumbled in the
early 1990s.
	   Bulatovic's party lost out in May voting to a coalition led by
pro-Western Milo Djukanovic, a reformist who now is president of
Montenegro. Milosevic and Djukanovic have clashed over economic and
other issues.
	   Milosevic, who became Yugoslav president last year, wants to
dominate Montenegro. He named Bulatovic as federal premier despite
his party's loss at home.
	   Predrag Drecun, labor minister in Montenegro's government, said
his party will propose a resolution next month giving Milosevic an
ultimatum to name a new federal premier from among Montenegro's
reformers.
	   ``If Milosevic rejects this, a referendum should be held in
Montenegro to decide whether it wants to stay in a country where
the will of the majority is not respected,'' Drecun said. 	   
</TEXT>
