<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-US Filter </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. Filter says low ringgit makes this good time to invest
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ U.S. Filter, a water and
wastewater treatment company, feels the weak Malaysian currency is
providing American investors with a good opportunity, its president
said Monday.
	   The national news agency Bernama quoted the president, Richard
J. Heckmann, as saying he would call on chief executive officers of
other U.S. companies to invest in Malaysia.
	   The ringgit has lost about 40 percent of its value against the
U.S. dollar in the last year.
	   Bernama said Heckmann added that U.S. media had given a negative
impression of the situation in Southeast Asia, including Malaysia.
	   U.S. Filter's fourth plant in Malaysia was opened last Friday by
International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz. The company
employs 50,000 employees in 94 countries.
	   Heckmann said U.S. Filter opened the plant based on Malaysia's
potential to become an international center for industrial
development despite the economic downturn, Bernama reported.
	   ``We know where we want to be. ... Not all countries are
suitable for manufacturing,'' said Heckmann.
	   ``We are here to stay, and we definitely want to be here to meet
the requirements of a fast-developing industrial manufacturing
community when its economy recovers,'' he said.	   
