<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Roller Coaster Record </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
American rattles over roller coaster rails for more than 1,000
</HEADLINE>
hours &QL; 
 &UR; By JENNY E. HELLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Richard Rodriguez greeted fans on shaky ``sea
legs'' Monday after riding for 47 days _ not the turbulent waves of
the ocean, but a wooden roller coaster.
	   The 39-year-old New York City native spent just more than 1,013
hours on the Big Dipper roller coaster in the English resort town
of Blackpool, beating his 1994 record of 549 hours.
	   Rodriguez outlasted Canadian rival Normand St. Pierre, who
stopped riding a Montreal roller coaster after 670 hours last
month.
	   ``I wanted to put the record out of reach,'' Rodriguez said
Monday, after surpassing his goal of 1,000 hours.
	   The Miami University lecturer and graduate student followed the
strict guidelines imposed by the Guinness Book of Records before it
stopped tracking the roller coaster competition several years ago.
He eat, slept and drank in his favorite carriage in the middle of
the roller coaster, taking off two hours each day to shower and eat
a hot meal.
	   Although Rodriguez said he is ``very attached to the ride,'' he
admitted ``missing interaction with people'' while he was going
around and around.
	   ``During the World Cup, I wanted to get out and have a lager
with people,'' he said. Alas, stopping for a few beers wasn't on
the schedule.
	   From the time he first experienced the ups and downs of the
Coney Island Cyclone as a child, Rodriguez has enjoyed ``the
adventure of riding a roller coaster and the cultural experience of
meeting new people everyday.''
	   The Cyclone remains one of his two favorites _ along with the
75-year old Big Dipper at Blackpool's amusement park.
	   ``They are very different,'' Rodriguez said. ``The Big Dipper is
a smooth-riding wooden coaster you can sleep on. The Cyclone has
steep inclines and rattles around.''
	   Rodriguez, a diabetic who survived the summer on a diet of fish
and chips, pasta and hot dogs, is donating the money he collected
from sponsors to diabetes research.
	   Before returning to school, he plans to tour England _ on his
two shaky feet.
	   (jeh-kg)
</TEXT>
