w2711 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Congo 4thLd-Writethru   08-03 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gunfire rings though Kinshasa army barracks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS that senior cabinet minister failed to return to country
after trip of South Africa. Edits to conform. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Rwanda-Congo-Rebellion &QL; 
 &UR; By KAMANGA MUTOND &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Gunfire and rumors of a coup d'etat
echoed through Congo's capital of Kinshasa early Monday morning as
rival soldiers clashed in a military barracks and at a second base
while the government ordered people off the streets.
	   In eastern Congo, military leaders reportedly revolted against
President Laurent Kabila and called for his ouster, while a senior
cabinet minister from the eastern ethnic Banyamulenge group failed
to return to Congo after a trip to South Africa.
	   A dawn-to-dusk curfew has been imposed on Kinshasa and troops
loyal to Kabila began a massive search for Rwandan Tutsi soldiers,
who were the president's one-time allies.
	   A defense ministry official said loyalist troops had been
ordered to kill any Rwandan soldiers found hiding in and around the
city.
	   The sound of gunfire was heard coming from Camp Kokolo military
base and the Tshatshi barracks on Kinshasa's west side.
	   The clashes apparently pitted Kabila's troops against Rwandan
mercenaries, who last year helped the president oust longtime
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   The fighting comes amid growing suspicions within Kabila's
government that the Rwandan troops had been plotting against the
regime.
	   In the Rwandan capital, Kigali, a private news agency reported
an open rebellion against Kabila had been launched in North Kivu
province in eastern Congo.
	   ``We, the army of the Democratic Republic of the Congo have
taken the decision to remove President Laurent Desire Kabila from
power,'' said a statement read Sunday in French and Swahili over
Radio Goma, according to the private Rwandan News Agency.
	   The statement was signed by Sylvain Mbuchi, commander of the
10th battalion of the Congolese army based in Goma, the provincial
capital, RNA said.
	   The statement called on the local population to remain calm and
go about their daily business and assured residents that the goal
of the rebels was to ``preserve the unity and security of the whole
nation.''
	   A spokesman for a breakaway ethnic group in North Kivu urged the
people to rise up against Kabila.
	   ``We've taken the decision to no longer recognize the government
of Laurent Kabila,'' said the spokesman, who identified himself
only as Andre. ``We don't want to separate from Congo, but Kabila
must be removed from power.''
	   In a statement delivered to The Associated Press and the Voice
of America, Andre said his group, representing Banyamulenge ethnic
Tutsis, was in control of most of North Kivu province.
	   Congo's Foreign Minister Bizima Karaha, a Tutsi from the
Banyamulenge group, failed to returned to Congo on Saturday from a
trip to South Africa. His absence has triggered speculation that he
may be linked to the uprising.
	   The crisis comes one week after Kabila ordered all Rwandan
soldiers out of his country without explanation. Earlier, Kabila
sacked James Kabari, a Rwandan Tutsi who had been the president's
top military commander.
	   Although Rwandan troops played an important role last year in
Kabila victory over Mobutu, relations between the central African
countries have soured in recent months.
	   According to a defense ministry official, more than 1,000
Rwandan Tutsi soldiers fled the Kokolo base and are hiding in a
forest just outside of Kinshasa.
	   Kabila has been growing anxious about the presence of Rwandan
forces in Kinshasa, and weeks before ordering them to leave he
increased security around government buildings.
	   Tanks were deployed in front of the presidential residence and
office compound while troops were stationed at key ministry
buildings.
	   The sound of fighting Monday triggered an order by the
government to clear the streets.
	   ``The government asks the people of Congo and those foreigners
here in the country to stay calm and to stay at home until order is
restored,'' said an abrupt announcement Monday morning on
state-controlled People's Radio. ``Stay at home just until that
time when the armed forces of Congo re-establish civil order.''
	   Shops throughout the capital remained closed Monday morning, and
people who had headed downtown for work early in the morning
quickly returned home.
	   Speculation was rife over the stability of Kabila's government
after weeks of growing tension between the president, his top
advisers and what now appears to be a shaky military alliance with
neighboring Rwanda.
 &UR; (var/ids)
</TEXT>
