<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey keeps Chechen president at a distance during visit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey kept Chechen President Aslan
Maskhadov at a distance Monday, insisting that his four-day visit
was a private one that did not include official meetings with
Turkish leaders.
	   Maskhadov, who has been seeking support for Chechnya's
recognition as an independent state, arrived in Istanbul Sunday.
	   Although many here sympathize with largely Muslim Chechnya's
demands for independence, Turkey, which is fighting
autonomy-seeking Kurdish insurgents itself, does not recognize
Chechnya's independence.
	   Turkey is also said to be weary of damaging its ties with
Moscow, which insists that Chechnya is part of Russia.
	   Chechnya claimed independence at the end of the 1994-1996
Chechen war. But its political status remains unresolved.
	   The Turkish foreign ministry said Monday that the leader of the
breakaway state was not going to visit Ankara or meet with Turkey's
government leaders.
	   Still, Maskhadov, accompanied by his family, held talks Monday
with junior coalition party leader Husamettin Cindoruk.
	   ``The Chechen people have received the greatest support for
their rightful struggle from Turkey,'' Maskhadov was quoted as
saying during the meeting.
	   Mashkadov was due to meet with a delegation of Turkish
businessmen.
	   Turkey and Chechnya are competing for the transport of Azeri oil
to Europe. Turkey plans to build a new oil pipeline linking Baku to
the Mediterranean Turkish port city of Ceyhan to replace the
existing line that passes through troubled Chechnya.
	   (ht-fd)
</TEXT>
