<HEADLINE>
International authorities turn back Albanian refugees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ Italian and Albanian patrol boats turned
back more than 600 Albanians trying to flee across the Adriatic Sea
early Monday, the interior ministry said.
	   Italian border authorities stopped 17 dinghies a few miles off
of the Albanian coast, then assisted them back to the Albanian port
of Vlora, 80 kilometers (50 miles) southwest of Tirana.
	   According to police sources, around 52 dinghies carrying 1,500
people, most of them women and children, have been returned to
Albania in the past 20 days.
	   Some of the people who wanted to leave Albania were refugees
who'd fled Yugoslavia's troubled Kosovo province, where ethnic
Albanians are fighting government forces for independence.
