<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Czech-Havel Surgery, 1st Ld-Writethru,0344 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Breathing problems force tracheotomy for Czech president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with details, fears Havel may be
developing pneumonia. CHANGES overline. ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By ONDREJ HEJMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Czech President Vaclav Havel
underwent a tracheotomy Monday amid fears he might be developing
pneumonia eight days after serious abdominal surgery.
	   Doctors performed the procedure, in which a small hole is cut
into the throat to facilitate breathing, because of a lung
inflammation, said Boris Stastny, of member of the medical team
treating Havel at Prague's military hospital. ``You could call it a
potential pneumonia,'' he said.
	   After the operation, Havel was in the hospital's intensive care
unit. Doctors said Havel's temperature was back to normal but he
would be kept sedated until Tuesday.
	   Dr. Ernst Bodner, who performed the 90-minute surgery, said it
was complicated by scarring from Havel's three previous
tracheotomies.
	   Bodner, of the Innsbruck University Clinic, operated on Havel in
April when the president's colon ruptured while he was vacationing
in Austria.
	   Bodner was also part of the Czech-Austrian team who operated on
Havel on July 26 in Prague to restore his digestive tract.
	   The surgery had been declared successful, but Havel's overall
recovery was hindered by breathing problems.
	   The 61-year-old president, formerly a chain smoker, has been
hospitalized five times since December 1996, when he had a third of
his lung and a tumor removed.
	   Last week, Havel's lungs collapsed briefly, forcing the use of a
respirator. Doctors took Havel off the respirator Saturday, but
late Sunday, his temperature shot up to 39 degrees Celsius (102
degrees Fahrenheit), his heartbeat went up and laboratory findings
indicated a lung inflammation, doctors said.
	   According to experts, Havel will need at least six weeks to
fully recover. He is scheduled for an official visit to the United
States in September. 	   
</TEXT>
