<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Chernobyl, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chernobyl's only working reactor shut down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details, comment from Chernobyl director in new
grafs 3-4. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ The only working reactor at the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant shut down automatically because of an electric
transformer malfunction, officials said Monday.
	   No radiation leaks have occurred at the reactor No. 3 since the
shutdown on Sunday afternoon, said the state company Energoatom,
which runs Ukraine's nuclear plants. The reactor will undergo
repairs until Friday, Energoatom said.
	   Chernobyl officials later said the shutdown was caused by short
circuit in the external electric cables leading to the transformer.
	   Chernobyl director Vitaly Tolstonohov said Monday that
malfunctions at reactor No. 3 this year were due to bad repairs,
but added that the reactor's equipment generally was in good
condition, according to the Interfax news agency.
	   Sunday's accident at the Chernobyl plant, albeit minor,
underscored recent warnings by Ukraine's top nuclear safety
official, who recently noted the growing number of malfunctions at
the country's five atomic power plants.
	   Oleksandr Smyshlyayev, who heads the Environmental Protection
Ministry's nuclear division, blamed the breakdowns on outdated
equipment and the failure to observe safety rules.
	   The Chernobyl plant originally had four working nuclear
reactors. Reactor No. 4 was destroyed in a 1986 explosion, the
world's worst nuclear accident. Another reactor was shut down after
being badly damaged by a 1991 fire, and a third is not operational.
	   Ukraine relies on nuclear plants to produce more than half of
its electricity, and says it does not have enough money to convert
to other forms of energy or make safety improvements.
	   (vl/sms/mr)
</TEXT>
