<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Worlds-Notebook </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Oliver aiming for another NBA shot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Jimmy Oliver is after the gold, certainly,
but some green would be nice, too.
	   The joint leading scorer for the U.S. team at the World
Basketball Championship is keenly aware that good shooting here
could translate into another shot at an NBA contract.
	   ``I know there's a lot of NBA people over here looking at games
so I go out and try to do what coach (Rudy) Tomjanovich asks me to
do,'' said Oliver, the Purdue product whose 12.3-point average
through four games tied him with Wendell Alexis. ``He's
constructing things where it makes all players on his team look
good. It benefits all the players.''
	   Tomjanovich, for his part, acknowledges that he is using the
players' individual aims as motivation.
	   ``We talked a little about us representing the United States and
also what this can do for these players personally,'' the Houston
Rockets coach said.
	   Oliver has played a total of 76 NBA games with Boston, Cleveland
and Toronto, but spent last season with Ciudad de Huelva in the
Spanish League.
	   The 6-foot-7 (1.99-meter) guard insists, though, that he'll be
all right if he does not get back to the NBA.
	   ``I'm not going to be sad,'' he said, ``if I don't get the
opportunity to return. Unfortunately, a lot of people get a couple
of years in the league and then don't get back in.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LUCKY 13: &LR;  Nigeria overcame a drug suspension, a slew of
injuries and an 0-3 start to win two straight consolation games and
finish 13th out of 16 teams at the tournament.
	   ``From the point of view of what we had to work with, the
players reached 110 percent. It's not been a happy tournament for
us,'' coach Ayo Bakare said after Nigeria beat Japan 70-60 Monday.
``I'm relieved we don't have to play any more games, or the coaches
would have had to dress up to play.''
	   Center Julius Nwosu was handed a two-month ban by FIBA after
testing positive for the banned stimulant ephedrine last week, and
with former New Jersey Net Yinka Dare (shoulder), Emeke Okenwa
(broken foot) and others injured, only seven players were available
for Monday's game.
	   Guard Kingsley Ogwudire led Nigeria with 19 points.
	   Bakare said African basketball can only improve if more
countries from the continent are invited to the Olympics.
	   ``FIBA needs to help out. Africa has just one spot in the
Olympics,'' the coach said. ``There's a lot of talent, a lot of
interest in basketball in Africa, but we need to let in more teams
at the top level. That's the only way for the game to improve back
home.''
	   The other African team at the worlds, Senegal, beat South Korea
75-72 Monday in the 15th-place game.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   ANTSY ANSTEY &LR; : The lone NBA player in Athens, Chris Anstey of
the Dallas Mavericks, has not exactly been a star.
	   Coming off the bench for Australia, he's averaging 9.5 points
and 5.5 rebounds in 20 minutes per game.
	   ``Going to Dallas I had a point to prove to myself. It's the
best league in the world, and was where I wanted to be, and my
challenge was to prove I belonged there,'' the 7-foot (2.13-meter)
center said. ``Now I've also got to prove I belong here, and prove
that I can play at this level, and in this type of game.''
	   (hjf)
</TEXT>
