<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arafat expected to present new Cabinet this week
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Ed: UPDATES with more details on new Cabinet, quotes from PLO
official &QL; 
 &UR; By IMAD MUSA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ After months of foot-dragging, Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat is expected to present his new Cabinet to the
legislature for approval on Wednesday.
	   ``There will be a special session of the legislative council
this Wednesday to listen to the names of the new Cabinet members
and to give them a vote of confidence,'' council speaker Ahmed
Qureia told The Associated Press.
	   The council has demanded reforms since issuing a report on
widespread corruption in the Palestinian Authority more than a year
ago, and has repeatedly threatened to hold a vote of no-confidence
in Arafat's government.
	   Assad Abdel Rahman, a member of the PLO Executive Committee,
said Arafat's list includes 10 new names _ most of them members of
the Palestinian Legislative Council.
	   At least two of the proposed new ministers _ Saad Kurunz and
Yusif Abu Safiya _ are independents sympathetic to the ideology of
the militant Islamic group Hamas.
	   A new ministerial position will be created to serve as a liaison
between the legislature and the executive branch.
	   In August, all but two of the 24 Cabinet ministers offered their
resignations, but Arafat did not accept them until a few weeks ago.
However the Cabinet has continued functioning despite the
resignations.
	   Abdel Rahman said Arafat plans to swap the portfolios of some
ministers, while others will leave the Cabinet entirely.
	   Some ministers named in the council's report on corruption
report, such as Planning Minister Nabil Shaath, will retain their
positions, he said.
	   A Palestinian official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
others named in the report, such as Civil Affairs Minister Jamil
Tarifi and Transport Minister Ali Qawasmeh, will remain
ministers-at-large, but will lose their portfolios.
	   Five Cabinet slots are vacant because two ministers have died
this year, one resigned, one is terminally ill, and the appointment
of another was never approved by the legislature.
 &UR; im-hla
</TEXT>
