u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-MissileTest     08-03 0222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Missile Test,0221 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India tests surface-to-air missile
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India on Monday tested a surface-to-air
missile that can deliver conventional explosives up to a range of
25 kilometers (15 miles), Press Trust of India news agency said.
	   The indigenous 650 kilograms (1,444 pounds) missile was fired
from a mobile launcher at a test site in India's eastern Orissa
state, PTI said. The missile has been named ``Akash,'' which means
sky.
	   India already has tested ``Trishul'' missiles that can be used
as a surface-to-air missile against aircraft and as a counter to
sea-skimming missiles.
	   Trishul, or Trident, uses solid fuel and has a range of up to
nine kilometers (5.5 miles) and can carry a warhead of 15 kilograms
(33 pounds).
	   India tested five underground nuclear devices May 11-13 and is
perfecting a delivery system.
	   The Indian government also has approved increasing the range of
the intermediate-range Agni missile, which it had previously
tested, but halted two years ago following pressure from the United
States.
	   India says it needs a nuclear defense against China and its
other neighbor Pakistan, both nuclear powers. India has fought
Pakistan in three wars since 1948 and still engages in frequent
border skirmishes. India and China fought a war in 1962.
</TEXT>
