w2773 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-MysteryCrash     08-03 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Mystery Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutors admit truth behind Ustica crash may never emerge
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP photos &QL; 
 &UR; By VANIA GRANDI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Prosecutors admitted Monday the truth may never
emerge about the 1980 crash into the Mediterranean of an Italian
airliner which killed all 81 people aboard.
	   Theories on what caused the Itavia DC-9 to blow apart on a
domestic flight near the tiny island of Ustica have ranged from a
bomb placed in a airline lavatory to a missile from aerial dog
fights possibly involving Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi's
plane.
	   But after an 18-year inquiry, Rome prosecutor Giovanni Salvi
said there was still ``deep uncertainty'' on the cause of the
accident.
	   Salvi said he and two other prosecutors working on the case had
found evidence to support both the bomb and missile theory, but had
also found evidence knocking down each.
	   For example, he said, traces of explosives found on two shards
from the plane's rear, where the bathroom is located, pointed to a
bomb. But the parts proved to consist of a slightly different medal
alloy than the rest of the plane, raising the possibility that they
did not come from the DC-9.
	   ``The truth is that this accident had characteristics never
encountered before,'' making it extremely difficult to resolve,
Salvi said. The wreckage, 90 percent of which was recovered and
reconstructed, is in one of the Mediterranean's deepest points and
the area was not completely covered by radar.
	   Investigators also said a gas tank and witness accounts suggest
U.S. jets were flying in the area when the DC-9 crashed June 27,
1980. Salvi, however, said they found no evidence to link the crash
to American presence.
	   Although the crash cause remains unknown, the prosecutors have
asked for the indictment of four retired Italian air force generals
and six other officers for an alleged cover-up. The investigators
suspect the generals failed to provide military information vital
to the probe.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
