w2780 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Rwanda-Congo-Rebellio 3rdLd-Writethru   08-03 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Congo-Rebellion, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eastern Kivu region in open rebellion against Kabila
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comment from Rwandan official; details; ADDS
byline &QL; 
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) _ The Kivu region of eastern Congo is in
open rebellion against the government of President Laurent Kabila,
a Rwandan official said Monday.
	   The official, who spoke on condition that he not be further
identified, said the 700-kilometer (435-mile) stretch between
Kalemie and Beni in South and North Kivu provinces was up in arms.
	   The private Rwandan News Agency said earlier that the radio
station in Goma, capital of North Kivu province, had broadcast a
communique from mutineers signed by Sylvain Mbuchi, the commander
of the 10the batallion of the Congolese army.
	   ``We, the army of the Democratic Republic of the Congo have
taken the decision to remove President Laurent Desire Kabila from
power,'' said the communique read Sunday in French and Swahili.
	   Officers and troops from the Rwandan Patriotic Army were
instrumental in launching and carrying out the eight-month
rebellion that brought Kabilia to power in the former Zaire in May
1997 and ousted dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   The rebellion began in October 1996 around Uvira, 200 kilometers
(125 miles) south of Goma, at the head of Lake Tanganyika.
	   In Kigali, Rwandan government spokesman Maj. Wilson Rutaisire
told The Associated Press no Rwandan troops were involved in the
current rebellion because they had all left the Congo last week at
Kabila's request.
	   However, he acknowledged that the departure of the unspecified
number of Rwandan troops may have played a role in the current
unrest.
	   ``The departure of our troops from Congo may have removed the
control that they had so that the conflict and the difference
(among ethnic groups in eastern Congo) could surface,'' Rutasire
said. ``This might have really contributed to the escalation of
conflicts they had there.''
	   Analysts have been predicting major problems in North and South
Kivu for some time because of the competition for land and power
among the Banyamulenge and other ethnic Tutsis who have lived in
the region for generations with ethnic Hutus _ also originally from
Rwanda _ and the so-called indigenous tribes like the Bahunde, the
Banyanga and the Babembe.
	   Writing in the July issue of Le Monde Diplomatique, French
researcher Gerard Prunier said Kivu was on the verge of explosion,
``and no one is looking for scissors to cut the fuse.''
	   The rebel communique called on the local population to remain
calm and go about their daily business and assured residents that
the goal of the rebels was to ``preserve the unity and security of
the whole nation.''
	   The communique called on politicians in the Congolese capital,
Kinshasa, to meet urgently and find a way of organizing good
leadership.
	   RNA said the airport in Goma was closed Monday and that a call
went out to residents and aid workers in the town just across from
the Rwandan city of Gisenyi to hand over all radio communications
equipment to security posts.
	   The agency said there were unconfirmed reports of similar
rebellions in Bukavu, 100 kilometers (60 miles) south of Goma and
the capital of South Kivu province, and in Kindu, the capital of
Maniema province, 130 kilometers (80 miles) west of Bukavu.
	   Another unconfirmed report said mutineers had opened Bukavu
prison and set free Banymulenge officers and troops from the
Congolese army who had been convicted of mutiny several months ago.
	   (var/sl)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Rwanda-Congo-Rebellion, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
