<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-New Government,0278 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After months of political wrangling, Dutch get new Cabinet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos DHG101-2 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ Ending months of political
wrangling and speculation, ministers of the Netherlands' new
coalition government were introduced to the nation Monday.
	   Slots in the 15-member Cabinet and the goals of the new
government had been under negotiation among the three top parties
in the coalition since general elections in May.
	   Monday, the giddy new Cabinet ministers were sworn in and
unveiled in a photo shoot with Dutch Queen Beatrix outside her
palace in The Hague.
	   The coalition, which is of such mixed political colors they call
it the Purple Coalition, includes Prime Minister Wim Kok's
left-leaning Labor Party, the right-leaning Liberal Party and the
centrist Democrats 66 party.
	   Kok again leads the coalition.
	   The new Cabinet has two female deputy prime ministers _ the
first time women have held the positions. Annemarie Jorritsma, will
also serve as economic affairs minister, and Els Borst, will serve
a second term as health minister.
	   Missing from the new team are some of the most visible ministers
from the last government, including former Foreign Minister Hans
van Mierlo.
	   Jozias van Aartsen, the former agriculture minister, is the new
foreign minister.
	   A newcomer, Benk Korthals, takes over the Justice Ministry,
which is embroiled in a scandal over child pornography.
	   Coalition governments have ruled for the past 80 years in the
Netherlands, where there are a dozen sizable parties, none of which
has been able to garner enough votes to take control outright. 	   
</TEXT>
