<SLUG> BC-Malta-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prime minister announces early election in September
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs, adds background &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VALLETTA, Malta (AP) _ With his party's thin hold on power
threatened, Prime Minister Alfred Sant on Monday announced
elections Sept. 5, three years ahead of schedule.
	   The Labor Party was returned to power on this Mediterranean
island nation in October 1996, but the government has recently been
rocked by resignations and embarrassing defeats in parliament.
	   Sant is seeking to strengthen the Labor Party's one-vote
majority, which has been undermined by former Labor Prime Minister
Dom Mintoff. He defied the party, although claiming he did not want
to bring down the government.
	   Mintoff twice voted with the opposition Nationalists over a
development plan in his district.
	   Labor won the last election after nine years in the opposition.
	   The upcoming elections will again pit Sant against Eddie Fenech
Adami, who survived calls for his resignation as Nationalist leader
after the 1996 vote.
	   (str/vls)
