<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Civil War,0215 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More than 50 killed in fighting in northern Sri Lanka
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Government soldiers and Tamil Tiger
rebels clashed in northern Sri Lanka on Monday, leaving more than
50 combatants dead, a military statement said.
	   The rebels attacked government soldiers near Mankulam, a
northern town close to a vital road link the military has been
trying to capture since last year. The area is 245 kilometers (150
miles) north of Colombo, the Sri Lankan capital.
	   The military repulsed the attack, which killed 15 soldiers and
37 rebel fighters, the statement said. At least 16 soldiers were
seriously wounded.
	   The military has been trying to capture the 70 kilometer
(45-mile) highway that passes through rebel-held territory that
could provide a land link to Jaffna Peninsula. It has gained
control of nearly two-thirds of the road link.
	   The peninsula is at present accessible only by air and sea, an
expensive means of transporting food and supplies.
	   The rebels are fighting for a separate homeland for minority
Tamils in the nation's north and east, claiming that they are
discriminated against by the majority Sinhalese. The government
denies the charge.
	   At least 54,000 people have been killed in the fighting since
1983. 	   
</TEXT>
