<HEADER>
w2823 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Nuclear     08-03 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's state nuclear power company announces construction
</HEADLINE>
program &QL; 
 &UR; By JUDITH INGRAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Expressing hope that nuclear energy will
experience a ``second wind'' in Russia, a top nuclear power
official outlined plans Monday to construct 15 nuclear reactors,
including two offshore floating stations, by 2010.
	   Yevgeny Ignatenko, managing director of the state-run
Rosenergoatom company that runs Russia's nuclear power plants,
called the plans modest.
	   Despite his optimism, critics say they could be scuttled by the
country's dire economic situation and continuing doubts about
nuclear safety after the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear disaster.
	   ``It's not just controversial. It's absurd,'' said Igor
Forofontov, an anti-nuclear campaigner for the Greenpeace
environmental organization. He said that Russia's nuclear industry
had left too many vital questions open, including plant safety and
nuclear waste disposal.
	   The clearest argument against the nuclear construction is
economic, he said.
	   ``In most countries, they know that nuclear power can't compete
with other energy sources,'' Forofontov said. ``For us, it's
catastrophically unprofitable.''
	   Russia currently has 29 nuclear reactors in operation at nine
stations, and last year they provided 13 percent of the nation's
electricity. Ignatenko said that nine reactors will have reached
the end of their service life by 2010 and should be closed.
	   Rosenergoatom plans to build three nuclear reactors by 2000,
another six by 2005 and six more by 2010. All are to be constructed
on or near the sites of existing reactors, Ignatenko said.
	   However, two of the new reactors are to be built on floating
platforms off Russia's Pacific coast. Ignatenko said that offshore
reactors are particularly suited to hard-to-reach areas, where
construction and fuel delivery are especially expensive.
	   Ignatenko said Russia was hoping for credits from the European
Union to meet construction costs. International nuclear experts
have approved the plans for construction of a new,
water-pressurized VVER-1000 reactor at Voronezh, about 475
kilometers (300 miles) south of Moscow, he said.
	   ``It's very important that in the future no one have doubts''
that Russia's nuclear reactors are up to the world standard,
Ignatenko said.
	   He claimed international experts who examined Russia's new
generation of reactors have rated them the third safest in the
world _ behind Japan and Germany but ahead of the United States.
	   The Chernobyl disaster in then-Soviet Ukraine created widespread
public distrust of nuclear energy and gave impetus to the
development of Russia's huge natural gas deposits as the key fuel
for power generation.
	   But energy experts argue that new nuclear plants are necessary
to guarantee the country's energy self-sufficiency.
	   (ji/mr) 	   
</TEXT>
