<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 4th Ld,0339 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aziz criticizes U.N. weapons inspectors after talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 9th graf to UPDATE with second round of talks beginning. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BAG101-105 &QL; 
 &UR; By WAIEL FALEH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Dimming prospects for progress in talks
with the United Nations, a top Iraqi official accused the chief
U.N. weapons inspector Monday of serving American interests by
trying to prolong punishing trade sanctions on Baghdad.
	   Using harsh language, Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said
after a three-hour session with chief inspector Richard Butler that
the U.N. Special Commission was ``back to its old games, to its old
tricks.''
	   The commission is responsible for ensuring that Iraq has
eliminated its weapons of mass destruction, as required by U.N.
resolutions that ended the 1991 Gulf War. The comments followed
some optimism that the two sides were on track to ending the
inspections, which began after the war.
	   The Security Council has said that the sanctions _ including a
ban on air travel and limits on the sale of oil _ will not be
lifted until the commission ensures the weapons have been
destroyed.
	   Aziz accused Butler's team of ignoring the country's progress in
meeting the goal and, instead, focusing on ``minor issues which
make no sense from the angle of disarmament.''
	   ``Since this is the wish of the American administration to
perpetuate the situation, to prolong the current situation, to keep
the sanctions on the people of Iraq .... as long as this is the
American wish, you (Butler) are serving the American policy,'' he
said.
	   When asked about Aziz's remarks, Butler said only that ``work is
in progress.''
	   On Sunday, Butler told reporters: ``Our steadfast aim is to get
this done as soon as possible to get to the end of the disarmament
phase so the Security Council can consider the sanctions issue.''
	   The two sides met again Monday night for further talks. Butler
will remain in Baghdad until Wednesday.
	    &UR; Neither Aziz, 10th graf 	   
</TEXT>
