<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Drugged Military,0195 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Every fifth draftee uses drugs, report states
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Twenty percent of Hungary's military
draftees regularly consume some sort of illegal drug, according to
a study released Monday.
	   Interviews and random drug tests conducted by the Hungarian
Armed Forces Health Institute showed one-fifth of the country's
27,000 draftees used drugs regularly.
	   For draftees returning from leave, nearly half tested positive
for drug use, Col. Andras Gacsalyi said at a conference unveiling
the results, the state news agency MTI reported.
	   Gacsalyi said new legislation will be adopted to allow mandatory
drug testing, but MTI did not specify under what circumstances the
testing would be conducted.
	   Once Hungary becomes a NATO member, a move expected by next
year, drug use will have to be more vigorously combated, Gacsalyi
said.
	   According to the survey, fewer soldiers in the eastern half of
the country use drugs. But those who use drugs often chose opiates,
which can rapidly lead to dependency.
	   In the western half of the country, the drug of choice is
amphetamines and similar ``disco drugs.'' 	   
</TEXT>
