w2836 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Austria-BloodyArt     08-03 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Bloody Art </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blood-spattered actors rub entrails in artistic happening
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Note nature
 &UR; By ROLAND PRINZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRINZENDORF, Austria (AP) _ After a bull was slaughtered at
sunrise to a cacophony of bells and brass, naked people strapped
onto crosses were fed and spattered with blood.
	   The bloody scenes marked the bizarre start Monday of a six-day
artistic happening conceived and directed by Austrian Hermann
Nitsch, a self-described action painter whose works are on display
in art galleries around the world.
	   Nitsch's extravaganza aroused widespread outrage before it
began. His chief critics are right-wing politicians, a Vienna
tabloid, animal rights activists and Catholic bishops.
	   But the 1,000 paying guests watching at dawn apparently did not
mind. They included friends, art students, artists and
intellectuals from several European countries and the United
States.
	   A total of 100 actors, all dressed in white before some of them
were blood-stained _ hair, face and body _ and 180 musicians,
including two Czech brass bands, are lined up to perform according
to a 1,595-page script of the ``Orgy Mystery Theater'' festival.
	   The script also provides for body and other painting, the
display of thousands of flowers and chamber music played under
lines of chestnut trees in a park. It also features Gregorian
chants as well as bucolic scenes with lots of wine _ 13,000 liters
(3,500 U.S. gallons) in all.
	   Some may question whether this is art, but not fans of
actionism, which has a small but devoted following in Austria and
elsewhere in Europe.
	   A summary of Nitsch's artistic intentions said the various
``stages of (human) existence are to be shown in their polarity
between the greatest happiness ... and the lowest chasm, the
revulsion, the bestial destructiveness of the darkest desires.''
	   In terse comments to The Associated Press, Nitsch defended his
artistic concept he said has a great many historic roots and is
designed to show the ``highest intensity'' of feeling, ``down to
cruelty.''
	   The site of the artistic happening Nitsch says represents his
life's work were his castle grounds outside this small village,
some 65 kilometers (40 miles) north of Vienna.
	   Preceded by an earsplitting cacophony of rattles, coach
whistles, bass drums and other noise-making instruments, three
professional butchers slaughtered and skinned a bull at daybreak.
	   After being hoisted on a wall in the large castle courtyard, the
bull was disemboweled with the help of the actors.
	   What followed was an orgy of blood. About ten white-clad
participants frantically rubbed animal bowels and other organs
against the dead bull, while some of them poured blood onto it all
until everyone was soaked.
	   In between, several blindfolded, naked men and women, strapped
onto wooden crosses, were carried to the scene and fed blood, most
of which was streaming down their body.
	   More bowel-rubbing _ this time involving a slaughtered pig _
took place some two hours later.
	   A handful of protesters who blocked some of the cars from
reaching Nitsch's castle held up a streamer saying: ``The animals'
dignity is untouchable.''
	   But Nitsch dismissed criticism. Referring to opposition by the
bishops, he said: ``The Catholics must realize that they are no
longer a stat relgion, that they cannot manipulate any more.''
	   (rp/dc) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
