<HEADER>
w2849 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Africa-Briefs     08-03 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Includes items on Kenya, Zimbabwe, South Africa &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ----
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Some 15,000 bank employees went on strike
for the second time throughout Kenya on Monday to demand the
withdrawal of a tax on their low-interest loans.
	   Their union representative Jacob Opiyo said the 7 percent tax
was leaving
	   bank workers with ``negative salaries.''
	   ``Due to unavoidable circumstances, we regret to advise we are
unable to offer full banking services,'' read a notice at the Loita
Street branch of the Commercial Bank of Kenya in downtown Nairobi.
	   Many employers provide their staff with low-interest loans,
generally to purchase homes, because the 29 percent commercial
lending rate makes borrowing impossible for most Kenyans.
	   The government now claims the loans are income and should be
taxed.
	   Opiyo said the strike would continue until the government
withdraws the tax.
	   In February, bank employees staged a five-day strike until
Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae agreed to put off the tax.
	   But he reinstated it in the 1998-99 budget in June, citing the
need to increase revenues because of economic hardship.
	   Employees of the state-owned Kenya Post and Telecommunications
Corporation have threatened to strike over the same tax.
	   ------
	   CHINHOYI, Zimbabwe (AP) _ A top government official condemned
proposed foreign investment in Zimbabwe's media, saying the move
would challenge political order in the country.
	   ``The aim of most foreign owned newspapers is to destabilize the
political order in the country,'' said Nathan Shamuyarira, Minister
of Industry and Commerce.
	   The man who is also propaganda chief for the ruling Politburo
spoke Sunday on state radio and TV.
	   Last month, an agency in Shamuyarira's ministry approved a 60
percent capital investment by outside investors for the launch of
four regional weeklies and a national paper, The Daily News.
	   A key player is Tony O'Reilly, a close personal friend of
President Robert Mugabe and a majority shareholder in Independent
Newspaper Holdings of South Africa.
	   Shamuyarira was editor of a paper also called the Daily News in
1964, when former Rhodesian leader Ian Smith's Front Government
banned it for opposing white rule.
	   Information Minister Chen Chimutengwende last week demanded
legislation to curb foreign participation in the media.
	   Most of Zimbabwe's media are owned by the parastatal Mass Media
Trust.
	   ------
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Switzerland's President Flavio
Cotti on Monday signed a 16 million rand (dlrs 2.6 million) aid
agreement to establish a fund for needy students in South Africa.
	   Starting a three-day state visit, Cotti was greeted by President
Nelson Mandela at his offices, Tuynhuys. Mandela led the visitor on
a stroll to a gate where they greeted school children _ a gesture
that has become a trademark of his presidency.
	   Switzerland is South Africa's fifth-largest investor.
	   Cotti was expected to meet Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and
retired Archbishop Desmond Tutu, chairman of the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission that is investigating apartheid-era
crimes.
	   ------
	   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) _ Zambian police are investigating reports
that international truck drivers are smuggling military weapons
into the country for use in armed robberies.
	   Police spokesman Beenwell Chimfwembe confirmed on Monday that a
syndicate
	   was responsible.
	   International truckers have allegedly sold guns to organized
gangsters currently terrorizing Lusaka in a spate of armed
robberies.
	   Chimfwembe said 68 people were robbed in Lusaka at gunpoint in
June.
	   Chimfwembe said the guns came from Angola, Burundi and Rwanda.
He would not confirm nor deny that some weapons were from South
Africa.
	   ------
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ A second round of peace talks between
military rebels and the incumbent government of Guinea Bissau have
been scheduled for Friday and Saturday, the Portuguese news agency
LUSA reported Monday.
	   The talks, to be held on a Portuguese frigate moored off the
coast of the
	   capital Bissau, follows a ceasefire agreement reached last
month.
	   The talks were negotiated by a delegation from the Community of
Portuguese Speaking Countries, or CPLP.
	   The tiny West African former Portuguese colony was plunged into
conflict
	   following a military uprising on June 7.
	   -------
	   GEORGE, South Africa (AP) _ Raging mountain fires forced the
evacuations of dozens of people before the blazes were brought
under control late Monday.
	   South African Air Force helicopters assisted in fighting the
fires and helped transport firefighters to the mountains, said
spokeswoman Lt. Col. Laverne Machine.
	   The fires occurred along the Western Cape's Garden Route in the
southern region of the country.
	   -----
	   MBABANE, Swaziland (AP) _ Fourteen people were killed and more
than 40 were injured when a bus crashed into a sugar cane truck at
Tambuti in Eastern
	   Swaziland.
	   The bus was carrying vendors home from Durban in South Africa
when it crashed on Saturday into a broken-down tractor and veered
into the loaded sugar cane truck.
	   The drivers of the bus and the truck were among the dead.
	   ------
	   GABORONE, Botswana (AP) _ Long known for its financial prudence,
the Botswana government has increased salaries of public servants
by as much as 43 percent.
	   The increase is the largest in the history of Botswana, which
has one of Africa's most successful democracies and economies.
	   The move drew fire from the local Gazette newspaper, that wrote:
``This will go down in the history of Botswana as the year in which
prudent financial management was thrown out of the window to be
replaced by help yourself economics.''
	   The former British protectorate ranked among the world's 10
poorest countries at independence in 1966. Today, its 1.5 million
people enjoy per capita income of dlrs 3,000, putting Botswana in
the upper half for the world and the top ranks for Africa.
	   The government claimed a budget surplus the last nine years.
	   (var-pr)	   
