<HEADLINE>
Blood-spattered actors rub entrails in artistic happening
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS number of paying guests on Monday. &QL; 
 &UR; By ROLAND PRINZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRINZENDORF, Austria (AP) _ After a bull was slaughtered at
sunrise to a cacophony of bells and brass, naked people strapped
onto crosses were fed and spattered with blood.
	   The bloody scenes marked the bizarre start Monday of a six-day
artistic happening conceived and directed by Austrian Hermann
Nitsch, a self-described action painter whose works are on display
in art galleries around the world.
	   Nitsch's extravaganza aroused widespread outrage before it
began. His chief critics are right-wing politicians, a Vienna
tabloid, animal rights activists and Catholic bishops.
	   But about 200 of the expected 1,000 paying guests watching at
dawn apparently did not mind. They included friends, art students,
artists and intellectuals from several European countries and the
United States.
