w2864 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Algeria 2ndLd-Writethru   08-03 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll reaches 69 since start of U.N. fact-finding mission
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with death count during U.N. mission totaling 69,
mission wraps up probe; ADDS background
 &UR; By RACHID KHIARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Armed men in military fatigues stopped a
bus at a fake roadblock, then slit the throats of passengers and
the driver, killing 12 people, authorities announced Monday.
	   The latest killings blamed on Muslim militants brought to 69 the
number of civilians who died since a U.N. mission investigating the
insurgency arrived nearly two weeks ago. The panel wrapped up its
mission on Monday.
	   Army troops killed at least a dozen suspected Islamic militants
after the Sunday afternoon attack that also left six civilians
wounded near Saida, 400 kilometers (250 miles) southwest of
Algiers, authorities said in a statement.
	   The U.N. panel, looking into the massacres and bombings that
have killed an estimated 75,000 people in this petroleum-rich
nation since 1992, finished its visit Monday after a meeting with
President Liamine Zeroual. No details of the meeting were
immediately available.
	   ``The panel is particularly appreciative of the government and
the people of Algeria,'' a U.N. statement said, adding the
six-member mission would leave for Lisbon on Tuesday.
	   The U.N. mission, led by former Portuguese President Mario
Soares, has met with political leaders in the governing coalition
as well as the opposition, generals, public figures, human rights
activists and victims' families.
	   It visited the main prison in Algiers as well as two massacre
sites, and met with three lawyers from the banned Islamic Salvation
Front.
	   In the meantime, the panel remained tight-lipped, though sources
close to the mission said they were asked tough questions about how
the government was protecting civilians. The government has been
accused of failing to prevent the massacres, and rights groups say
the army is responsible for the disappearances of thousands of
people.
	   While the Algerian government had granted the group more freedom
than to previous foreign delegations, it expressed irritation as it
awaited the results of the probe.
	   The U.N. investigation could ``free the terrorists of guilt,
while they themselves admit to their odious crimes and claim
them,'' the official Algerian Press Agency APS said.
	   Accompanying Soares on the mission were former U.S. ambassador
to the U.N. Donald McHenry; former Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral; former Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Karim Kabariti;
Kenyan Attorney General Amos Wako; and former French Health
Minister Simone Veil.
	   The insurgency began after the army-backed government canceled
parliamentary elections in January 1992 that the Islamic Salvation
Front was expected to win on voter discontent with corruption and
high unemployment.
	   (rk-parf-cb)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
