<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Fighting, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0514 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition says Taliban will get fight in Mazar-e-Sharif
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lead, UPDATES with radio report of Taliban fighters 40
kilometers east of Mazar-e-Sharif. TRIMS previous. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo KAB101 &QL; 
 &UR; By ZAHEERUDDIN ABDULLAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) _ The Taliban religious army pushed
ahead Monday in its drive to seize control of all of Afghanistan,
closing in on a major opposition stronghold a day after it captured
a nearby town.
	   Though the Taliban met little resistance when it took Shebergan
on Sunday, the militia will get a fight in Mazar-e-Sharif, a
northern alliance spokesman said Monday.
	   ``Our forces are ready to defend Mazar-e-Sharif. If the Taliban
try to capture Mazar-e-Sharif, they will face heavy resistance,''
said Zabet Saliy, spokesman for anti-Taliban military leader Ahmed
Shah Masood. ``They will repeat the mistake they committed last
year.''
	   Taliban fighters briefly held Mazar-e-Sharif last May,
retreating after street battles that left several hundred Taliban
soldiers dead. It is believed that as many as 2,000 Taliban
prisoners of war were later massacred.
	   Taliban fighters have been bolstered by a series of recent
victories and appear poised to capture the remaining northern part
of Afghanistan they do not control.
	   Taliban leaders have imposed a strict version of Islamic law in
territory they control. Since capturing Kabul in 1996, Taliban
officials have barred girls from school and confined most women to
their homes.
	   The fractious anti-Taliban coalition is made of mostly of
Afghanistan's minority ethnic and religious groups.
	   Taliban radio reported late Monday that fighters were just 40
kilometers (25 miles) east of Mazar-e-Sharif, within rocket range
of the city's airport, which was reported closed.
	   Wekil Ahmad Muttawkil, a Taliban spokesman at the militia's
headquarters in the southern city of Kandahar, said leaders had not
yet decided whether to attack Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Last year's tough battle for the town contrasts with sketchy
descriptions of Sunday's fall of Shebergan, the stronghold of
warlord Rashid Dostum that is located 100 kilometers (60 miles)
west of Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Dostum has joined Masood and the Hezb-e-Wahadat militia that
controls Mazar-e-Sharif against the Taliban, but his fighters also
clashed with Hezb-e-Wahadat in Mazar-e-Sharif last year.
	   Taliban officials said casualties were low and a large number of
prisoners were captured. Dostum's forces reportedly set fire to
Shebergan airport as they left, destroying several fighter jets.
	   Saliy, speaking by satellite telephone from northern
Afghanistan, said Dostum's men put up little resistance after some
of their commanders were paid off by the Taliban. Such mercenary
switching of loyalties has long been a hallmark of the Afghan civil
war.
	   Dostum retreated to Hayratan, about 60 kilometers (40 miles)
east of Mazar-e-Sharif on Afghanistan's border with Uzbekistan and
was trying to reorganize his forces, Saliy said.
</TEXT>
