<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Polar Bear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Warning issued against wounded polar bear in Svalbard
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ Tourists and tour operators in the Norwegian
Arctic archipelago of Svalbard have been warned against a wounded
polar bear which could be dangerous.
	   The bear was shot Saturday when it attacked a group of British
tourists in the Bille Fjord area. The group's Norwegian guide shot
the bear in the neck with his revolver when it got into a fight
with one of the group's dogs in the tourists' tent camp.
	   The bear dissappeared into the icy wilderness, leaving a bloody
trail in the snow.
	   ``We called off a helicopter hunt for the bear on Sunday, but
are still keeping a look-out for it,'' said John Starheimseter of
the Norwegian governor's office to The Associated Press.
	   Governor Ann-Kristin Olsen, who also is chief of police in the
Arctic territory, 700 miles (1100 kilometers) north of the
mainland, warned people against going to the area, about 30 miles
(50 kilometers) from the capital of Longyearbyen.
	   None of the six British tourists or their Norwegian guide were
hurt in the incident.
	   Polar bears are a protected species, and all hunting for the
bears was banned some 25 years ago. The govenor's office will now
launch an investigation to determine whether the shooting Saturday
was legal self-defense.
	   Although encounters with polar bears are rare in the more
accessible areas of Svalbard during the summer, everybody who
ventures outside Longyearbyen is strongly recommended to carry a
gun for protection.
	   In 1995 two people, a French tourist and a Norwegian woman, were
killed by polar bears in two different incidents in Svalbard. The
young Norwegian woman met the bear on a glacier right outside
Longyearbyen.
	   Most areas of Svalbard are off limits for tourists unless they
are well equipped for polar exploration and have a permit, or take
part in an organized tour.
	   Svalbard is Norwegian territory, but under the Svalbard treaty
all signatories can carry out commercial and scientific activities.
Besides Norway, only Russia has significant commercial interests in
two large coal mines.
	   (nfm-jh)
</TEXT>
