<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Saddam's Son, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq says some of Odai's attackers captured
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES throughout with government statement, two
assailants apprehended, three still at large, ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraqi security forces have captured two of
the five men who shot and seriously wounded President Saddam
Hussein's eldest son in 1996, the government said Monday.
	   The two men who were arrested carried out the actual attack on
Odai Hussein, the General Directorate of Security said in a
statement carried by Iraq television. The three others still at
large provided cover and support, the directorate said.
	   The statement accused a ``neighboring foreign country'' of
masterminding the attack but stopped short of naming it. Odai, in
an interview from his hospital bed after the attack, had pointed
the finger at Iran. Iran has denied any involvement.
	   ``The organs of a foreign neighboring country have been involved
in this treacherous operation,'' the statement said.
	   The names of the two men were released, but the statement did
not give their background or say when they were arrested. It said
two of the three men at large are hiding in a neighboring country.
	   Odai, 34, was shot about 10 times on Dec. 12, 1996, while he
waited alone in his car in an upscale Baghdad neighborhood.
	   In April 1997, surgeons operated on his shattered left leg. He
has since been shown on television walking with the aid of a cane.
	   Two opposition groups claimed responsibility for the attack: the
Iranian-backed Al-Dawa Party, a Shiite opposition group, and the
Mohammed Madhlum al-Dulaimi Group, named after an Iraqi air force
general executed for plotting against Saddam.
 &UR; lb-as
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Iraq-Saddam's Son, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
