<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Strikes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Attorney General says threatened crackdown on strike is illegal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Zimbabwe's attorney general declared on
Monday that the government had acted improperly when it said it
would clamp down on a threatened strike by the country's largest
labor federation.
	   The statement by Attorney General Patrick Chinamasa left many
observers in confusion.
	   ``I don't know what to believe,'' said Morgan Tsvangirai,
secretary general of the Zimbabwe Congress of Trades Unions, which
is considering a five-day national stoppage to protest tax hikes,
runaway inflation and government corruption and mismanagement.
	   Chinamasa said notices in the official Government Gazette which
declared virtually all the formal sector economy ``essential
services'' and threatened to impose 10-year jail terms for people
inciting or supporting a strike were ``erroneous and invalid.''
	   An International Monetary Fund delegation is to arrive in Harare
on Tuesday and is to consider giving more aid to the country's
economy. Chinamasa's comments may be a sign the government had a
change of heart about the threatened strike and is worried that a
crackdown would threaten an international aid package.
	   (mh-aos)
</TEXT>
