<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Worlds, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lithuania in quarterfinals joining Greece, Spain, Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS to Argentina in lead; ADDS quotes from Kanisovas,
Puerto Rico coach Carlos Morales &QL; 
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS Greece (AP) _ Lithuania, bronze medalists in the last two
Olympics, booked a place in the quarterfinals of the World
Basketball Championship Monday with a second-round victory over
Argentina 84-75.
	   Lithuania joined Yugoslavia, Greece and Spain _ unbeaten
entering their late second-round games Monday _ in the coveted
quarterfinals.
	   Russia (3-1) and the United States (3-1) _ also playing late
Monday _ looked likely to reach the final eight with the last two
places up for grabs among Italy, Argentina, Puerto Rico and
Australia.
	   Lithuania (4-1) led Argentina (2-3) almost from the start and
was up 41-33 at halftime and then pulled away steadily. Salulis
Stombergas had 19 to lead the Lithuanians with 14 from Darius
Lukminas. The team's top scorer in the tournament _ Arturas
Karnisovas had 11.
	   ``Because they paid so much attention to me, I had to distribute
the ball instead of shooting it,'' the former Seton Hall star said.
``We kept going to Stombergas because they couldn't stop him one on
one. He was too quick.''
	   Argentina, which had two players foul out _ Alejandro Montecchia
and Juan Ignacio Sanchez _ was topped by Juan Alberto Espil with
18.
	   In Monday's other early second-round game, Puerto Rico (2-3)
stayed alive for a quarterfinal berth with a 94-81 victory over
Canada (1-4).
	   Eddie Casiano topped Puerto Rico with 23 and Jose Ortiz added 15
and 10 rebounds. The Canadians were led by Greg Newton with 25
points and eight rebounds.
	   ``This is the first time we have been able to play the game we
are capable of playing,'' said Puerto Rico coach Carlos Morales.
``We are small so we go hard for the boards and try to penetrate
and shoot from the outside.''
	   In games to determine 13th to 16th place, Nigeria claimed 13th
with a 70-60 victory over Japan. Senegal finished 15th, beating
South Korea 75-72.
	   In late second round games Monday it was: Brazil (1-3) vs.
Australia (2-2), Italy (2-2) vs. Yugoslavia (4-0), United States
(3-1) vs. Spain (4-0), Greece (4-0) vs. Russia (3-1).
	   The team to beat? Look to the silver medalists two years ago in
Atlanta.
	   Sure, the United States is missing all of its NBA stars, but
Yugoslavia is almost as hamstrung without Vlade Divac, former NBAer
Predrag Danilovic and injured playmaker Aleksandar Djordjeciv.
	   After a four-year absence caused by sanctions during the war,
Yugoslavia returned in '95 to win the European title and repeated
it two years later.
	   This team _ stars or no _ is just as good, said coach Zeljko
Obradovic.
	   ``Certainly the absence of players such as Zoran Savic (retired
from international play) and Danilovic and Divac is consideable,''
Obradovic said. ``But I believe this team has a quality equivalent
to that of '95 when all those players were present.''
	   As for the starless Americans, who fell last week by two points
to Lithuania.
	   U.S. coach Rudy Tomjanovich has watched his team dip and climb
as it tries to tie together its CBA, college and European roots.
	   ``You can say we've had some ups and downs,'' Tomjanovich said.
	   ``Our intensity level coming into the game wasn't where it
should be,'' he added. ``We talked a little about us representing
the United States and also what this can do for players
personally.''
	   (scw) 	   
</TEXT>
