<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Mine Rescue, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hope fades for 10 men buried for 17 days in Austrian mine
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with focus of rescue efforts switching
from rescuing survivors to retrieving bodies. Trims, changes
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QC; 
 &UR; By MELISSA EDDY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ Rescue teams searching for 10 men buried
last month in an Austria mine have shifted the focus of their
efforts from saving survivors to retrieving bodies, officials said
Monday.
	   ``We won't give up hope,'' said Alfred Zechling, spokesman of
the rescue team in the mining village of Lassing, 190 kilometers
(120 miles) southwest of Vienna. But he also made clear there was
little hope any survivors would be found.
	   The decision to change tactics came after cameras and
microphones lowered into an emergency shaft failed to detect signs
of life in a chamber where it was hoped some of the men were able
to survive.
	   Relatives of the missing and residents of Lassing were depressed
at the news, and asked the rescue teams not to ease up on their
search, ``even if only to retrieve the dead,'' the Austrian Press
Agency reported.
	   The 10 were sent into a talc mine in Lassing on July 17 to
rescue miner Georg Hainzl, who was buried in a massive landslide
unleashed by torrential rains. But a second, larger landslide
trapped the nine miners and one geologist.
	   Talc is a soft mineral that is refined into talcum powder and
lubricants.
	   Rescue efforts intensified after Hainzl was found alive and in
relatively good condition July 26. He had taken refuge in another
chamber closer to the surface.
	   The only remaining hope is a series of other air pockets that
have been detected from the surface, where the miners might have a
chance of surviving because there would be enough oxygen. Boring
through to them, however, will be a long, slow ordeal, as they are
located under the original stone surrounding the mine.
	   (pvs/me/dc)
</TEXT>
