w2920 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Canada-IndianTreaty     08-03 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Indian Treaty,0591 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British Columbia split over historic treaty with Indians
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAVID CRARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) _ Rewarded for 111 years of
persistence, the Nisga'a Indians sign a historic treaty Tuesday
giving them land, cash and self-government in a remote and
spectacular mountain valley.
	   It is a time of celebration for the 5,500 Nisga'a, who have
sought a treaty since 1887, but many British Columbians don't share
their joy. Critics contend that history of this magnitude should be
made only with voters' consent.
	   If ratified, it will be the first treaty this century for any of
the 51 Indian communities in British Columbia. Unlike the rest of
Canada, treaties in the Pacific Coast province were not signed
during colonization.
	   The province's two main opposition parties are demanding a
referendum on the treaty. It will cost taxpayers more than dlrs 300
million (dlrs 200 million U.S.) and likely serve as a blueprint for
settlements with dozens of other tribes.
	   ``We are creating a whole new order of government, we are
creating new rights, we are entrenching inequality based on race,''
said Gordon Campbell, leader of the opposition B.C. Liberal Party.
``The least they could do is allow the public a say.''
	   The Nisga'a will get to vote on the treaty later this year. It
also must be ratified by Parliament and British Columbia's
legislature.
	   The treaty is strongly backed by the federal government of Prime
Minister Jean Chretien and the provincial government of Premier
Glen Clark.
	   The province is spending dlrs 2.3 million (dlrs 1.5 million
U.S.) to promote the treaty. A key selling point is that British
Columbia _ its economy now reeling _ needs treaties to end the
uncertainty for mining and forest companies considering projects on
land claimed by Indians.
	   The Nisga'a treaty, which took two decades to draft, gives the
Indians dlrs 190 million (dlrs 126 million U.S.) in cash over 15
years, plus title to 1,930 square kilometers (745 square miles) of
rugged land in northwestern British Columbia. Other programs, plus
forgone government revenue, push the cost of the treaty higher.
	   The chief Nisga'a negotiator, Joe Gosnell, says the cost to
taxpayers is dwarfed by value of fish, timber and minerals taken
from Nisga'a territory in past decades. Lack of control over those
resources has helped boost the Nisga'a jobless rate above 60
percent.
	   Gosnell admits some Nisga'a are bitter because negotiators
settled for one-tenth of their original land claim and agreed to
relinquish their tax-exempt status.
	   The treaty provides the Nisga'a with the right to
self-government and the authority to make laws governing their own
affairs. It envisions a Nisga'a justice system, with its own
judges, police force and jails.
	   The treaty's critics say the 100 or so non-Indians living in
Nisga'a territory will become second-class citizens, excluded from
voting for tribal governments.
	   Keith Martin, a Parliament member with the right-wing Reform
Party, said the treaty could lead to creation of mini-states for
each of British Columbia's native communities.
	   ``Apartheid or separate development failed in South Africa and
it will fail in B.C.,'' he said.
	   But government officials insist the treaty does not create
racial inequality.
	   ``There is no taxation without representation,'' said Clark,
noting that non-Indians in Nisga'a territory will pay taxes to the
provincial government, not the tribal council.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Canada-Indian Treaty; CT:i; 
