<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 08/03/1998 13:22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2924 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Rwanda-Congo-Rebellio 4thLd-Writethru   08-03 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Congo-Rebellion, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eastern Kivu region in open rebellion against Kabila
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES in grafs 3-5 with comments from Congolese
military commander in Bukavu; raises background on Banyamulenge
rebellion; Edits slightly; no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) _ The Kivu region of eastern Congo is in
open rebellion against the government of President Laurent Kabila,
a Rwandan official said Monday.
	   The official, who spoke on condition that he not be further
identified, said the 700-kilometer (435-mile) stretch between
Kalemie and Beni in South and North Kivu provinces was up in arms.
	   Contacted by telephone in Bukavu, the capital of South Kivu
province, Maj. Ilunga Kabambi, the commander of the Congolese army
in the South Kivu region, said he and members of the 222nd Brigade
were ``not in agreement with the president.''
	   He said the city at the south end of Lake Kivu was calm after
``some trouble'' and confirmed reports that several dozen
Banyamulenge or ethnic Tutsi officers and soldiers, who had been
court-martialed and jailed for insubordination, had been freed from
Bukavu prison.
	   ``This is a generalized movement,'' Kabambi said, cutting short
the conversation.
	   Officers and troops from the Rwandan Patriotic Army were
instrumental, in collaboration with the Banyamulenge ethnic Tutsis
from Kivu, in launching and carrying out the eight-month rebellion
that brought Kabila to power in the former Zaire in May 1997 and
ousted dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   The rebellion began among the Banyamulenge in October 1996
around Uvira, 110 kilometers (68 miles) south of Bukavu.
	   Humanitarian sources in the Kivu region said Monday the movement
against Kabila _ and his Baluba kinsmen from southeastern Katanga
province _ appeared to have overcome recent rifts between the
Banyamulenge in the Congolese army and soldiers from tribes
indigenous to the area.
	   A humanitarian source who could not be further identified said
Rwandan soldiers and officers were seen in Bukavu Monday, including
Col. James Kabarere, who as Col. Kabari was, until he was dismissed
by Kabila last month, the chief of staff of the Congolese army.
	   The sources said it appeared that the majority of the 9,000
Rwandan soldiers who were supposed to have returned to Rwanda last
month had stayed on in the region.
	   The private Rwandan News Agency said earlier Monday that the
radio station in Goma, capital of North Kivu province, had
broadcast a communique from mutineers saying the army had decided
to remove Kabila from power.
	   Goma is 100 kilometers (60 miles) north of Bukavu.
	   There were unconfirmed reports that the rebellion had also
spread to Kindu, capital of Maniema province, 130 kilometers (80
miles) west of Bukavu.
	   In Kigali, Rwandan government spokesman Maj. Wilson Rutaisire
told The Associated Press no Rwandan troops were involved in the
current rebellion because they had all left the Congo last week at
Kabila's request.
	   However, he acknowledged that the departure of the unspecified
number of Rwandan troops may have played a role in the current
unrest.
	   Analysts have been predicting major problems in North and South
Kivu for some time because of the competition for land and power
among the Banyamulenge and other ethnic Tutsis who have lived in
the region for generations with ethnic Hutus _ also originally from
Rwanda _ and the so-called indigenous tribes like the Bahunde, the
Banyanga and the Babembe.
	   Writing in the July issue of Le Monde Diplomatique, French
researcher Gerard Prunier said Kivu was on the verge of explosion,
``and no one is looking for scissors to cut the fuse.''
	   (var/sl)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Rwanda-Congo-Rebellion, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
