<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Gypsy Holocaust, 1st Ld-Writethru,0445 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
All-night vigil for Gypsy victims of the Nazis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEX BANDY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) -- In an all-night ceremony that ended at
dawn Monday, about 300 people mourned those killed 54 years ago
when the Nazis slaughtered thousands of Gypsies during the
Holocaust.
	   From the night of Aug. 2, 1944, until the next morning, the
Nazis massacred 4,500 Hungarian Gypsies in the notorious
Auschwitz-Birkenau concentration camp in Poland to make room for
more Jews.
	   SS guards with dogs led Roma, as Gypsies prefer to be called,
from their barracks and gave them salami and bread, telling them
they were to be transferred to another camp.
	   Instead, the Gypsies were swiftly herded into gas chambers.
	   The annual ceremony has been expanded to honor all of the
European Gypsies who were murdered by the Nazis during World War
II. The exact number of victims is unknown because they were often
registered by the country where they were living.
	   Scholars believe the number is between 200,000 and a half
million. Of the 23,000 Gypsies taken to the Auschwitz-Birkenau
prison camp, only about 2,000 survived, according to Franciszek
Piper of the Auschwitz State Museum.
	   Gypsies refer to the Holocaust as Poraymos -- or the Devouring.
	   As dusk fell Sunday over the square in front of the Gothic-style
national parliament, Erika Mate sang a Gypsy lament: ``Dear God,
let the day come when all the slaves are freed. Punish, the
Germans, oh God, for they have killed the people...''
	   The vigil included the reading of a message from President Arpad
Goencz, an ecumenical religious service and the reading of names of
thousands of Gypsy victims.
	   Speakers said that although the world has become aware of the
Nazi massacre of 6 million Jews, many remain unaware of the Nazi
slaughter of Gypsies, homosexuals, Marxists and the mentally
impaired.
	   ``My grandfather was rounded up by the Hungarian police and he
was turned over to the Germans,'' said Aladar Horvath, 34. ``When
he could not play the tune they wanted on his violin, they locked
him in the ice shed. He froze to death.''
	   The Roma settled in Hungary in the 13th century and are the
country's biggest ethnic minority _ 500,000 out of a population of
10.2 million. They are nomadic people with a distinct language and
ancient folklore and are found mostly in Spain, Hungary and the
Balkans.
	   Andras T. Hegedues, a Budapest expert on minority affairs, said
Hungarian records indicate 50,000-60,000 Hungarian Gypsies were
deported to death camps in the last two years of World War II. 	   
</TEXT>
