w2935 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Greece-Fires 2ndLd-Writethru   08-03 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Fires, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forest fire sends cloud over Athens
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with bigger fire under control, some houses destroyed
by fire &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ More than 150 firefighters struggled
Monday to control a wind-whipped forest fire that threatened a
German World War II cemetery and sent a cloud of reddish smoke over
central Athens.
	   The blaze began late Sunday at the foot of Mount Pendeli about
four kilometers (2 1/2 miles) northeast of Athens' northern
suburbs, officials said.
	   By evening firefighters managed to bring most fronts sparked by
the big fire under control, while others smoldered around the
mountain.
	   ``At one point the fires threatened nearly 200 houses. We lost a
couple of the houses,'' said Panaghiotis Fourlas, fire chief for
the greater Athens area.
	   He said that the blaze started in different places at the same
time and speculated that some could have been started by arsonists.
	   ``I can't accept that all these fires started by chance,''
Fourlas told Athens' private Mega channel.
	   Authorities evacuated a home for disabled children and an army
hospital. A main road in the area was closed, reports said.
	   Four planes and a Chinook helicopter assisted 155 firefighters,
who managed to bring the blaze under control as it swept towards
the village of Rapentosa, and a cemetery for German soldiers killed
during World War II.
	   But strong winds hampered firefighting efforts from the air,
local media reported, with planes unable to continue flights for
long.
	   No injuries due to the fire were reported. Blazes in the area in
past years have left much of the mountainside a landscape of
charred stumps.
	   Several other fires also raged around Greece, with a blaze on
the 2,900-meter (9,570-foot) Mount Olympus in northern Greece
entering its third week. The fire on the legendary home of the
ancient gods has destroyed 1,000 hectares (2,471 acres) of forest
so far, local media reported.
	   Two weeks ago, three firefighters and a volunteer firefighter
were killed battling a blaze that scorched the eastern edge of
Athens.
	   Wildfires are common during the hot and dry summers in Greece.
But this season has been called one of the most devastating in
decades, with fires burning daily for the past month.
	   (eb-bm)
</TEXT>
