<SLUG> BC-Angola-Landmine Death, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British landmine expert killed in accident in Angola
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Bailey in third graf, fixes coding

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ A British landmine expert was killed in
Angola while demonstrating how to defuse a mine, the Foreign Office
in London said Monday.
	   Justin Bailey, 27, was training Angolans in how to make mined
areas safe as part of a program run by a non-governmental
organization called Norwegians Peoples Aid, Foreign Office
spokeswoman Clare Davies said by phone.
	   The accident happened July 28 and Bailey's body has since been
flown back to his home in Gloucester, west England, Davies said.
	   A estimated 10 to 14 million land mines were laid in Angola
during a two-decade-long civil war that pitted UNITA rebels against
government forces. An estimated 70,000 Angolans lost limbs from
land mine explosions.
	   Princess Diana, who died last year, had visited landmine victims
in Angola to publicize the devastation that these weapons can
cause.
	   The government and UNITA signed a tenuous peace deal in 1994. A
recent sharp rise in tension, including reports that new mines are
being laid, has triggered fears that the country may slide back
into war.
	   A top United Nations envoy arrived in the country Friday on an
emergency six-day peacemaking mission.
	   (jt/dw)
</TEXT>
