<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Pay TV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kirch challenges EU decision to bar its pay TV plans
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ German media company Kirch is challenging
European Union regulators' decision to block its digital TV
alliance with competitor Bertelsmann in a lawsuit filed Monday at
the European Court.
	   Kirch said it planned to argue before the Luxembourg court that
the EU's approval process was unfair and that regulators had viewed
the proposal negatively from the start.
	   Kirch said EU regulators in Brussels relied on arguments of
potential competitors to block the plans without giving the
applicants enough access to those arguments.
	   Bertelsmann's subsidiary CLT-Ufa said it agreed generally with
Kirch's position but that wouldn't be worth it to join the lawsuit,
arguing that the court proceedings could take up to five years.
	   The European Union's executive agency decided in late May to bar
plans by Kirch and CLT-Ufa to merge their pay television
operations, saying the plan did not adequately guarantee an open
digital TV market in the long term.
	   Kirch launched Germany's first digital service in 1996 to much
fanfare, but people were reluctant to buy the expensive decoder
boxes necessary to receive it, and the unprofitable service has
attracted only 160,000 customers.
	   To keep DF1 going, Kirch wanted to merge it with Premiere,
CLT-Ufa's analog pay-TV service with 1.6 million subscribers. Kirch
and Bertelsmann would each then own 50 percent of Premiere.
	   (im)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Germany-Pay TV; CT:f; 
