<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Dieting by Smoking </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Study links teen girls' pursuit of thinness with smoking
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MARA BELLABY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Most teenage girls who take up smoking do so to
lose weight, according to a study released Monday.
	   Past studies have shown a connection between young smokers and
eating disorders, but the new research is the first to directly
link teen girls' pursuit of thinness with smoking, said Lesley
Walker, head of science information for the Cancer Research
Campaign, which funded the study.
	   The researchers surveyed almost 2,800 girls in Britain and
Canada ranging in age from 11 to 18, 20 percent of whom smoked.
	   Most of the smokers said weight control was the principal reason
they took up the habit. More than 30 percent of them feared they
would eat more and put on weight if they tried to give up
cigarettes, researchers said.
	   Researchers also found that the girls who smoked were 30 percent
more likely than their non-smoking peers to be overweight and twice
as likely to be concerned about their bodies and to vomit
frequently after overeating.
	   Young girls are ``trading pounds off their weight for years off
their life,'' said Arthur Crisp, the professor at London's St.
George's Hospital Medical School who conducted the study.
	   The study, published in the Postgraduate Medical Journal, comes
at a time when the number of young female smokers continues to
grow. The most recent figures available from the Office of National
Statistics in England found that a quarter of girls aged 11 to 15
were occasional or regular smokers in 1996, up from 20 percent in
1982.
	   The researchers interviewed 1,936 girls in London and 832 in
Ottawa, Canada. Of the smokers, 15- and 16-year-olds were the most
likely to be puffing away.
	   The study also found that girls were three times more likely to
start smoking after beginning menstruation, when normal body
changes might be considered ``puppy fat'', said Ms. Walker, with
the Cancer Research Campaign, one of Britain's largest cancer
research charities.
	   Action on Smoking and Health, a British anti-smoking group,
blamed tobacco advertising for making smoking so attractive.
	   ``Cigarette ads don't show you images of smoke-filled rooms or
someone hacking away,'' Ash spokesman Phil Rimmer said. ``Instead,
you see wide-open spaces and glamorous, happy smokers.''
	   Crisp's research did not investigate whether girls were more
susceptible to tobacco advertising than other groups, but it did
conclude young women clearly identified smoking with thinness.
	   ``Sometimes you'd rather not publish these findings out of fear
it might encourage a few girls to take up the smoking habit or put
off others thinking about quitting,'' Ms. Walker said. ``But the
way to develop a body shape with which they feel comfortable is
exercise, not smoking.''
	   (mb-kg)
</TEXT>
