<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian president gives formal approval of new military plan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin formally inaugurated a new
era for the Russian armed forces on Monday, signing a document
outlining the principles of a new, leaner military.
	   ``This is the first time in Russian history we have laid out the
fundamental principles of Russia's policy in the field of military
development,'' said Andrei Kokoshin, secretary of the Security
Council, which helped draft the new strategy.
	   The principles in the so-called ``military concept'' have been
publicly debated for months.
	   The main goal is to shrink and professionalize Russia's
inefficient conscript army. Personnel will be cut by 500,000
soldiers, leaving Russia with a 1.2 million-man army by 2005.
	   The strategy also calls for streamlining Russia's command
structure and developing new, less expensive weapons systems,
including nuclear weapons.
	   The plan has been in the works since May 1997, when Yeltsin
appointed Gen. Igor Sergeyev as defense minister and charged him
with reforming Russia's military to bring it in line with current
needs and resources.
	   (mr/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
