<SLUG> BC-Italy-Ansaldo-Daewoo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks between Italian and South Korean groups break down
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Talks between South Korean Daewoo Group and Italy's
state-owned engineering group Finmeccanica SpA aimed at setting up
a joint venture involving energy and transport unit Ansaldo SpA,
have broken down, Finmeccanica said Monday.
	   Italy's giant state-holding company Istituto per la
Ricostruzione Industriale SpA, which controls Finmeccanica, and
Daewoo had been negotiating since late last year.
	   IRI chairman Gian Maria Gros-Pietro said in July that the
success of a deal would depend on the completion of Ansaldo's
restructuring plan, which involved around 2,000 job cuts. According
to industry sources, Daewoo had wanted more money put into Ansaldo
as part of the deal.
	   Finmeccanica said the talks ended because of ``different views
regarding the financial structure at the basis of the planned
global joint venture.''
	   The joint venture would have involved fields of power
generation, industry automation and transport, Finmeccanica said.
	   (dj-fd)
</TEXT>
