<BODY>
<SLUG> Uganda-Cobalt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebel attacks in western Uganda should not affect cobalt project
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ The insurgency in western Uganda
shouldn't prevent a dlrs 110 million cobalt project from concluding
construction in November, an official at the project told Dow Jones
Newswires Monday.
	   J.C. Coudere, a senior official at Kasese Cobalt Company Ltd.
(KCCL), said the two-year-old insurgency near the project site in
Kasese, 380 kilometers (235 miles) west of Kampala, has had little
effect on operations. He said the plant should be finished in
November if the insurgency doesn't escalate.
	   Construction of the plant started in August last year. He said
KCCL plans to commence the export of cobalt cathode in March next
year.
	   Allied Democratic Front rebels raided Kasese and nearby Kilembe
on Saturday and Sunday, killing at least 35 people, reports said.
	   ``We are still on schedule, construction of the plant is
continuing, and we expect to conclude it in November,'' said
Coudere by telephone. ``None of our workers nor contractors have
left the site. I talked to them this morning and they are all at
work.''
	   There had been reports that foreign workers _ Filipinos or South
Koreans _ at the plant were among those injured in the attacks.
	   He could not readily disclose how much has been invested so far,
and what level of development the project has reached. By January
this year, dlrs 24 million had been invested mainly in excavating
and stripping top soil.
	   Officials say dlrs 44 million will be financed by stakeholders
while dlrs 66 million will come from debt financing.
	   Banff Resources Ltd. (V.BFF) of Canada controls 55 percent of
the project while the state-run Kilembe mines owns 25 percent.
	   (dj/sl)	   
</TEXT>
