w2981 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Romania     08-03 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Romania,0390 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Romanian premier: Romania willing to return property to Jews
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos JRL102-103
 &UR; By VITA BEKKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile, who is
visiting Israel, said Monday he would push legislation to return to
Jews and others property that was stolen during and after World War
II.
	   Vasile said that the legislation, which he intends to introduce
in Parliament next month, would be open only to Romanian citizens.
	   ``The bill presents a global solution for Romania to return
property to all former owners, not only Jews,'' said Vasile, who
arrived Sunday for a four-day visit to Israel.
	   Vasile met with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Monday
afternoon. Netanyahu described his meeting with Vasile as
``excellent,'' and praised the Romanian premier's sensitivity
towards Jews.
	   Meanwhile, in Bucharest, Romania's capital, a committee to
return Jewish property met Monday for a second time.
	   About 400,000 Jews _ half Romania's Jewish population at the
time _ died in World War II, when Romania was allied with Nazi
Germany.
	   After the war, the communist government inherited Jewish
property stolen by the Nazis, and Jewish organizations say the
government then confiscated even more.
	   Although only 12,000 Jews are left in Romania, Romanian Jews
living outside the country are expected to apply for lost property
as well, Romania's Foreign Minister Andrei Plesu said.
	   Naftali Lavi, vice-chairman of the World Jewish Restitution
Organization, said several thousand public properties and perhaps
hundreds of thousands of private properties owned by Jews were
seized by the Nazis and the communists.
	   ``We were singled out for the confiscation of our property,''
Lavi said. ``Therefore we have to be singled out for restitution as
well.''
	   Vasile said five houses belonging to Jews had been returned to
their owners this year, and that three or four more would be
returned soon.
	   Romania's president, Emil Constantinescu, won praise from
Romanian Jewish leaders last year for publicly acknowledging the
country's complicity in the Holocaust.
	   Also on Monday, Israel and Romania pledged to work toward a
free-trade agreement between their countries, and to increase
trade, which stands at about dlrs 250 million a year.
</TEXT>
