<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 7th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Butler says disarmament talks with Iraq on verge of collapse
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Aziz saying no progress, quotes. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Planned
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Talks between Iraq and the United Nations
on dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction have reached an
impasse and may not resume, the chief U.N. inspector said Monday.
	   Richard Butler, speaking at the end of a second round of talks,
said Iraq turned down his proposal for a plan of action to end the
inspections that began after the 1991 Gulf War.
	   ``We did not make the progress I have hoped for,'' Butler told
reporters. ``I do not know whether we are going to meet tomorrow.''
	   His comments followed harsh criticism by Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz, who said Butler was ``serving the American
policy'' by trying to prolong punishing sanctions on Iraq.
	   Aziz said Iraq has no remaining weapons of mass destruction. ``I
asked Mr. Butler to tell the Security Council the truth,'' he said
after the evening talks, which lasted about two hours.
	   Aziz said he rejected Butler's new plan as useless ``if you
(Butler) are going to repeat the same tricks and the same games.''
	   The U.N. Special Commission, which Butler heads, is responsible
for ensuring that Iraq has eliminated its weapons of mass
destruction, as required by U.N. resolutions after the Gulf War.
	   Until Monday, there was some optimism that the two sides were on
track to ending the inspections.
	   The Security Council has said that the sanctions _ including a
ban on air travel and limits on the sale of oil _ will not be
lifted until the commission ensures the weapons have been
destroyed.
	   Neither Aziz nor Butler gave specifics on what was discussed
Monday, but the ``blueprint'' Butler presented the Iraqis during
his last visit in June calls for further disclosures about the
country's missile program and biological and chemical weaponry.
	   Earlier, Aziz accused Butler's team of ignoring the country's
progress in eliminating its weaponry and instead focusing on
``minor issues which make no sense from the angle of disarmament.''
	   Last month, Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein said that the sanctions
must be lifted this year _ the first time he had set a deadline.
Iraq says the sanctions have caused widespread poverty,
malnutrition and illnesses among its 22 million people.
	   Butler was scheduled to remain in Baghdad until Wednesday.
	   Iraq's refusal to open presidential sites to U.N. inspectors
earlier this year brought the region to the brink of war.
	   The United States and Britain sent warplanes and ships to the
Gulf, threatening military action to force Iraq to cooperate. The
crisis was defused in February through an agreement negotiated by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
 &UR; lb-as
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Iraq, 7th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
