<SLUG> BC-UN-Afghanistan,0262 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. planning aid workers evacuation from northern Afghanistan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The United Nations is planning the
evacuation of aid workers in northern Afghanistan after renewed
fighting there, officials said Monday.
	   U.N. spokesman Juan Carlos Brandt said that the United Nations
was studying plans to evacuate workers for 11 organizations based
in Mazar-e-Sharif, where the opposition to the Taliban militia is
based.
	   The largest group based in the city is Medecins Sans Frontiers,
the French medical assistance program, Brandt told reporters at
U.N. headquarters in New York. He did not say how many aid workers
were based there altogether.
	   Taliban troops closed in on the major opposition stronghold on
Monday, a day after they captured a nearby town.
	   Opposition leaders promised heavy resistance, although it was
not clear whether the Taliban intended to press ahead into the
Mazar-e-Sharif.
	   Taliban fighters briefly held the city last May, retreating
after street battles that left several hundred Taliban soldiers
dead. It is believed as many as 2,000 Taliban prisoners of war were
later massacred.
	   Aid workers were caught by surprise during that battle and were
forced to remain in the city during heavy fighting.
	   Taliban leaders have imposed a strict version of Islamic law in
the 85 percent of Afghanistan they control. Since capturing Kabul
in 1996, Taliban officials have barred girls from school and
confined most women to their homes.
</TEXT>
