w1003 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Algeria 3rdLd-Writethru   08-03 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. probe wraps up; violence during visit leaves 69 dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; UPDATES with more on U.N. visit
 &UR; By RACHID KHIARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ A U.N. mission investigating a Muslim
insurgency met with President Liamine Zeroual as it wrapped up its
visit Monday, while officials reported a massacre that left at
least 12 more civilians dead.
	   The latest killings blamed on Muslim militants brought to 69 the
number of civilians who died since the U.N. mission arrived nearly
two weeks ago.
	   In the attack Sunday afternoon, armed men in military fatigues
stopped a bus at a fake roadblock, then slit the throats of
passengers and the driver, authorities said.
	   Army troops killed at least a dozen suspected Islamic militants
after the massacre that also left six civilians wounded near Saida,
400 kilometers (250 miles) southwest of Algiers, authorities said
in a statement.
	   It was the kind of attack the U.N. panel was trying to get to
the bottom of, looking into massacres and bombings that have killed
an estimated 75,000 people in this petroleum-rich nation since
1992.
	   There were no immediate details from the six-member panel's
meeting with Zeroual.
	   ``The panel is particularly appreciative of the government and
the people of Algeria,'' a U.N. statement said, adding the mission
would leave for Lisbon on Tuesday.
	   The U.N. panel, led by former Portuguese President Mario Soares,
on Monday released a list of dozens of people it met with,
including government ministers, political leaders, generals,
newspaper editors, human rights activists and victims' families.
	   It visited Serkadji, the main prison in Algiers, as well as two
massacre sites and spoke with survivors. It met with three lawyers
from the banned Islamic Salvation Front.
	   In the meantime, the panel remained tight-lipped, though sources
close to the mission said they asked tough questions about how the
government was protecting civilians. The government has been
accused of failing to prevent the massacres, and rights groups say
the army is responsible for the disappearances of thousands of
people.
	   While the Algerian government had granted the group more freedom
than to previous foreign delegations, it worried about the results
of the probe.
	   The U.N. investigation could ``free the terrorists of guilt,
while they themselves admit to their odious crimes and claim
them,'' the official Algerian Press Agency APS said.
	   Accompanying Soares on the mission were former U.S. ambassador
to the U.N. Donald McHenry; former Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral; former Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Karim Kabariti;
Kenyan Attorney General Amos Wako; and former French Health
Minister Simone Veil.
	   The insurgency began after the army-backed government canceled
parliamentary elections in January 1992 that the Islamic Salvation
Front was expected to win.
	   (rk-parf-cb)
</TEXT>
