<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caspian Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Caspian oil pipeline consortium submits feasibility study
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Caspian Pipeline Consortium has submitted the
a feasibility study to local Russian authorities, seeking their
approval for construction of an oil pipeline, the consortium said
Monday.
	   The plan for the 1,580-kilometer (980-mile) pipeline from the
vast Tengiz field in Kazakstan to the Russian port of Novorossiisk
also needs approval from Russian federal authorities, the
consortium said in a press release.
	   ``We are certain that the committees will approve the drafts,''
said Natalya Prutkovskaya, a consortium spokeswoman. ``All the
principal issues have been agreed.''
	   Construction of the pipeline should start either late this year
or at the beginning of 1999, Prutkovskaya said. The pipeline is
expected to begin operations some time in 2001.
	   The building of the dlrs 2 billion artery has been delayed
because of bureaucratic wrangling over permits and disputes over
funding within the consortium.
	   The planned capacity of the pipeline is 67 million metric tons a
year.
	   The CPC is half-owned by the governments of Russia, Kazakstan
and Oman. The remaining stake is held by a group of international
oil companies, including Chevron Corp., LUKARCO (a partnership of
Lukoil and U.S.-based Arco), Rosneft-Shell, the U.K.'s BG PLC,
Mobil, Italy's Agip, Oryx and Kazakstan Pipeline Ventures LLC.
	   (dj/mr)
</TEXT>
