<SLUG> BC-India-Building Collapse,0214 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At least seven people die in building collapse
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ A seven-story building collapsed in a
Bombay suburb on Monday, killing at least seven people, a local
government official said.
	   Another 13 people were rescued by police and fire brigade, said
Shridhar Joshi, additional municipal commissioner. The building was
nearly 20 years old.
	   ``There was a huge thud and the structure came crashing down,''
said Vishveshwar, who uses one name, when reached by phone. He
lives in a nearby building.
	   Up to 35 people were feared trapped under the debris which was
being cleared by rescue workers, police said.
	   Many residents were at work when the building collapsed,
Vishveshwar said. The Govind Tower in congested northwest Bombay,
India's financial capital, comprises shops, a hotel and apartments.
	   Residents said they had complained to local authorities five
months ago about the structural defects in the building which
appeared to be leaning to one side. But nothing was done.
	   ``See what has happened,'' said Bal Sawant, a local lawmaker.
	   Rescuers already have found seven bodies, Sawant said.
	   Poor construction and maintenance have led to the collapse of
several buildings in Bombay in recent years. 	   
</TEXT>
