w1012 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Angola-UNEnvoy     08-03 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Angola-UN Envoy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angolan government assures U.N. it is committed to peace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; by CASIMIRO SIONA
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ The Angolan president assured a senior
U.N. envoy on Monday that his government was committed to peace
despite signs that the country is sliding back into civil war.
	   ``The president and the government reaffirmed their commitment
to the full implementation of the 1994 peace accord,'' U.N. envoy
Lakhdar Brahimi told reporters after meeting with President Jose
Eduardo dos Santos in the Angolan capital.
	   Brahimi arrived in Luanda Friday on an emergency mission
prompted by a recent escalation of tension, including the massacre
of 100 civilians in a remote northern village and reported military
buildup on both sides.
	   He spent the weekend conferring with western diplomats and U.N.
officials before his Monday meeting with Dos Santos.
	   The envoy's agenda for Tuesday is dominated by talks with Jonas
Savimbi _ the leader of the former UNITA rebel movement and the
other main figure in the simmering conflict.
	   A U.N.-brokered accord signed in 1994 sealed a tenuous end to a
two-decade-long war between the government and UNITA rebels that
was fueled by Cold War geopolitics.
	   But successive deadlines for full implementation of the
agreement have passed unheeded, and in recent weeks the entire
peace process has appeared in danger of collapse.
	   After his talks with Dos Santos Monday, Brahimi met with
government officials and UNITA representatives on the Joint
Commission that was formed to monitor implementation of the peace
accord.
	   The commission includes representatives from the government,
UNITA, the U.N. and diplomats from United States, Russia and
Portugal.
	   ``We felt great openness from the United Nations but we will
only be able to draw conclusions after tomorrow,'' when Brahimi has
met Savimbi, UNITA representative Haracio Junjuvili said after
meeting the envoy.
	   Brahimi was due to travel Tuesday morning by air to meet Savimbi
at his highland stronghold 480 kilometers (300 miles) north of the
capital of this former Portuguese colony.
	   UNITA's reluctance to relinquish its rural strongholds in
compliance with the 1994 accord has triggered harsh U.N. sanctions.
Savimbi has refused to move his base to the capital for personal
security reasons.
	   The government has also accused UNITA of not fully demobilizing
its 70,000-strong guerrilla army and maintaining troops hidden in
the bush.
	   But in recent weeks the government, as well as UNITA, have been
accused of preparing for another war with forced recruitment drives
in this immense southwest African country.
	   Junjuvili denied reports that UNITA had hired over 300
mercenaries from the South African company Executive Outcomes.
	   ``There are no mercenaries on UNITA's side'' he said.
	   (cs/jt/dw) 	   
</TEXT>
