----
US: COURT MARTIAL -  APTV covers the start of court martial
proceedings in Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, for the four U-S
Marines involved in the February in-flight accident which sent an
Italian ski gondola crashing to the ground, killing 20 people.
(North America Update 1830)
----
US: SCANDAL - The White House has said it will go to the Supreme
Court seeking to block testimony by presidential confidant Bruce
Lindsey.  APTV covers the latest on the sex scandal from Washington
(North America Update 1830) with any updates further in the night.
----
US: IBM CHIP - U-S computer giant I-B-M says it has a new
microprocessor chip that can speed up computers by more than a
third.  Item includes b-roll of the new superfast chip, plus comment
from a spokesman with I-B-M and a business analyst about how the
announcement will affect the industry.  (North America Update 1830)
----
US: SPANISH - APTV goes inside the classroom at a California school
where native Spanish-speaking students are spending their first day
under English-only instruction. The state law, passed in June,
imposed a ban on bilingual education in the state.  (North America
Late 1930)
----
US: PASTRANA - Colombia's President-elect Andres Pastrana proclaimed
a new era in Colombian-U-S relations after his meeting in Washington
meeting with President Bill Clinton at the White House.  Pastrana
takes office on Friday. (Latin America 1900)
----
UN: ETIMOR - Coverage of activity at United Nations headquarters in
New York, where the Indonesian and Portuguese foreign ministers are
meeting to discuss the status of East Timor.  (F-L-A-S-H tba)
----
KASHMIR: WRAP - APTV has a wrap with pictures from both the Indian
and Pakistan borders with Kashmir after shelling continues to force
refugees out of the disputed area.  Item includes pictures of
refugees and those injured in the fighting after the failure of
peace talks aimed at ending the 50-year conflict.  (North America
Update 1830)
----
KOSOVO: WRAP - A wrap of our earlier pieces on the renewed fighting
in Kosovo, showing refugee and soldier activity in the Drenica
region, a soundbite from a Kosovo Liberation Army fighter, the
funeral for a Serb policemen in his native town of Pec, and comment
from U-S Defence Secretary William Cohen from the Philippines
reasserts NATO's hope for a diplomatic solution.  (First Run Europe
Late 1500)
----
JERUSALEM: ROMANIA -  Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile has said
during a visit to Israel that he will submit legislation in
parliament next month to return property to Jewish Romanian citizens
whose property was seized by the Nazis during World War II, and by
the Communist regime after 1945.  APTV covers their meeting in
Jerusalem.  (F-L-A-S-H tba)
----
MIDEAST: PEACE 2 -  Israel's cabinet met on Monday, hours before
another session of Israeli-Palestinian negotiations on Middle East
peace.  Includes soundbite from Ahmed Tibi, an adviser to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who says it is up to Israel to
make the next move to salvage talks.  Also includes a demonstration
by Palestinian families in the Gaza Strip demanding the release of
Palestinian prisoners held in Israeli jails (First Run 1130 Europe
Update) and updates with comment from Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu. (North America Update 1830)
----
PANAMA: PROPERTY - Panamanian Government ministers have been taking
over luxury properties vacated by departing American U-S military
personnel in a high class district called Quarry Heights.
Opposition leaders have reacted angrily as the properties were never
put on the open market. APTV has politicians' comments over the
issue.  (Latin America 1900)
----
EL SALVADOR: FIESTA - A one week religious festival has begun in El
Salvador's capital, San Salvador, in honour of the patron saint of
the city.  This year's annual festival is dedicated to drawing
attention to nature and the environment. APTV covers the
celebrations. (Latin America 1900)
----
MEXICO: TWINS -  A world convention for twins, triplets and
quintuplets continues in Queretaro, north of Mexico City.  APTV
covers the convention where many are seeing double, or triple - or
more.  (Latin America 1900)
----
MEXICO: ELECTIONS - Mexico's ruling P-R-I party scored victories in
two out of three state elections for governor over the weekend, but
lost a third state to a political novice from the conservative
opposition in voting billed as a key indicator of the 2000
presidential race. APTV covers the election fallout. (Latin America
1900)
----
AUSTRIA: ART -  A bizarre artistic event is set to take place in
Austria, where a native artist - whose sponsors include David Bowie
and Yoko Ono - will slaughter a series of animals before 2000 people
in what he is calling the culmination of his life's work. Three
bulls, and six pigs will be killed, crucified and disemboweled
during Hermann Nitsch's 'Six Day Orgy Mystery Theatre' at his castle
near Mistelbach. Item includes arrivals and protests outside the
castle.  (Europe Early 0300)
----
RUNNING:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
IRAQ: BUTLER 2 - U-N chief weapons inspector Richard Butler is in
Baghdad for more talks with Iraqi Deputy Tariq Aziz, who accuses the
weapons chief of dragging out the inspections.  The start of the
talks (First Run Europe Late 1500) is followed by earlier soundbites
from Baghdad citizens on the UNSCOM programme in Iraq and comment
from Butler on the eve of his talks.  (First Run 0900 The Americas)
----
IRAQ: UDAY FILE - Iraqi State media reports that the country's
security forces have caught the men who shot President Saddam
Hussein's eldest son two years ago.  Includes file of Uday Hussein,
before and after the shooting incident.  (First Run Europe Late
1500)
----
UK/SPAIN: BIRDS - Clean-up efforts are still underway after a lethal
mixture of toxic waste covered one of the most important wetlands in
Europe at Donana in Spain in April.  But the clean-up operation has
been hampered by politics and pointless bureaucracy and
environmentalists fear the problem may return if the approaching
rainy season spreads more toxins over the area.  (First Run Europe
Late 1500)
----
TURKEY: PALACE - APTV has visited an archaeological site in Turkey
where diggers have uncovered the remains of a 6th century Byzantine
palace.   In addition to pictures from the site, we talk to the head
of the archaeological team and an independent American archaeologist
about the discovery.  (Europe Late 1500)
----
KOSOVO: FUNERAL - One of the two Serb policemen who was killed near
the Kosovo village of Prilep was buried in his native town of Pec on
Monday.  He died fighting to secure control of one of the key roads
in the area.  (First Run Europe Late 1500)
----
KOSOVO: BODIES 2 - Serbian government forces press on in their
attacks against ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo.  APTV has
pictures from the Drenica region and comment from a Kosovo
Liberation Army soldier.  (First Run 0900 The Americas) Updated with
comment from the Philippines by U-S Defence Secretary William Cohen,
who said NATO was still reviewing military options in Kosovo but
still hopes for a diplomatic solution.  (First Run 1500 Europe Late)
----
UK: REES-JONES -  Trevor Rees-Jones - the only survivor of the car
crash which killed Diana, Princess of Wales, Dodi Fayed, and their
driver - has talked on television for the first time. He spoke
exclusively to APTV in advance of the first anniversary of the fatal
crash on August 31. (Available to all broadcasters but not other
video agencies. Non-APTV clients must super caption: Pictures
courtesy APTV)  (First Run 0900 The Americas)
----
REES-JONES: BACKGROUNDER - APTV has a backgrounder piece on Trevor
Rees-Jones and the car crash he survived which killed Diana,
Princess of Wales.  It accompanies the exclusive APTV interview with
Jones. (First Run 0900 the Americas)
----
UK: SAUDI - As King Fahd of Saudi Arabia remains in hospital amid
rising fears over his health, his youngest son, Prince Abdulaziz bin
Fahd, insists in an APTV interview that his father is fit and well.
The King, whose condition is stable, has raised concerns in the
MidEast over his health after being hospitalised on Sunday for what
was being called routine 'medical testing.'  The prince spoke to
APTV during a visit to Edinburgh, Scotland.  (First Run 1130 Europe
Update)
---
RUSSIA: NUCLEAR - Russia has announced a plan to build new, safer
power stations and close down aged ones.  Includes news conference
by nuclear officials about the plan, pictures of construction going
on, file of the Chernobyl reactor and comment from a Greenpeace
activist who foresees problems unless the West provides technical
help. (First Run Europe Late 1500)
----
P'PINES: COHEN 2 - U-S Secretary of Defence William Cohen has said
U-S ships joining any future joint military exercises in the
Philippines will not carry nuclear weapons.  As Cohen met his
Philippine counterpart Orlando Mercado, activists demonstrated
outside the military headquarters against a renewal of joint
military exercises with the U-S. (First Run 1215 F-L-A-S-H)
