<SLUG> BC-Austria-Bloody Art,0337 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Actors covered with bull's blood in artistic happening
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Note contents &QL; 
 &UR; By ROLAND PRINZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRINZENDORF, Austria (AP) _ Naked people strapped to crosses
were spattered with the blood of a freshly slaughtered bull Monday
to mark the beginning of a six-day event conceived by Austrian
artist Hermann Nitsch.
	   Nitsch, a self-described action painter whose works are on
display in art galleries around the world, said he planned the
spectacle to show the range of human experience from happiness to
cruelty and ``bestial destructiveness.''
	   The show was staged at Nitsch's castle outside this small
village, some 65 kilometers (40 miles) north of Vienna.
	   About 200 paying spectators watched 100 actors and 180
musicians, including two Czech brass bands, perform from the
1,595-page script of the ``Orgy Mystery Theater'' festival.
	   The script calls for body painting, the display of thousands of
flowers and chamber music played under chestnut trees in a park. It
also features Gregorian chants and boozy scenes with 13,000 liters
(3,500 U.S. gallons) of wine.
	   The performance began with a cacaphony of earsplitting rattles,
coach whistles, bass drums and other instruments as three
professional butchers slaughtered and skinned the bull at dawn
Monday.
	   After being hoisted on a wall in the large castle courtyard, the
bull was disemboweled with the help of the actors.
	   About 10 white-clad actors rubbed animal bowels and other organs
against the dead bull, while some of them soaked everyone with the
animal's blood.
	   Several blindfolded, naked men and women, strapped to wooden
crosses, were carried to the scene and covered with blood.
	   A handful of protesters who blocked some cars from reaching
Nitsch's castle held up a streamer saying: ``The animals' dignity
is untouchable.'' The spectacle has also been condemned by Roman
Catholic bishops, right-wing politicians, a Vienna tabloid and
animal rights activists.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Austria-Bloody Art; CT:i; 
