<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tour de France-Doping, 3rd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dutch team appears before police, claim innocence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with all but one TVM member released
 &UR; By EMMANUEL GEORGES-PICOT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   REIMS, France (AP) _ A day after the Tour de France ended in
Paris, members of the Dutch team TVM were questioned by police
Monday about banned drugs found in their possession.
	   TVM team members had pulled out of the race on Friday, two days
before the ending, saying they had neither the physical nor the
mental strength to continue.
	   Six cyclists, along with other team staff members, were
questioned Monday morning in Reims, north of Paris. Already the
team director, Cees Priem, and its doctor, Andrei Mikhailov, and a
masseur have been placed under formal investigation _ a step short
of being formally charged _ on doping charges.
	   Team official Guido Calster emerged early afternoon after being
questioned, and said the team had been ``treated well.'' He said
they were being asked ``personal questions.''
	   By late Monday evening, all but a trainer remained in custody.
But he, too, was expected to be released, said Jacoba de Jong, the
team's lawyer.
	   De Jong said everyone questioned Monday said they were innocent
of any possible doping charges. She said they were not asked about
the results of drug tests, which would take several weeks.
	   ``They were heard as witnesses,'' she told reporters. ``They
fear nothing, or they wouldn't have come. They have nothing to
hide.''
	   Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``The TVM investigation,''
	   (parf-cb)
</TEXT>
