<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Elections, 11th Ld-Writethru,0843 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Changes in Mexico reflected in more competitive elections
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with latest information.
Gonzalez Gonzalez is cq in 2nd graf &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By KEN GUGGENHEIM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AGUASCALIENTES, Mexico (AP) _ One is the son of a former
president, an ex-senator and television mogul. The other a local
businessman who never entered politics until this year.
	   Both Miguel Aleman and Felipe Gonzalez Gonzalez scored
impressive victories in gubernatorial elections Sunday that were
crucial for their parties' chances in Mexico's 2000 presidential
election. Their successes show how much Mexico has changed _ and
how much it hasn't.
	   In what was expected to be a tight race, Gonzalez, of the
center-right National Action Party, won easily in the small central
state of Aguascalientes.
	   With 80 percent of the vote counted, Gonzalez had 53 percent of
the vote, according to state electoral council figures. Hector Hugo
Olivares Ventura of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, known as the PRI, had 36 percent.
	   The win was a huge boost to National Action. The party, known as
the PAN, lost one of its six gubernatorial seats when it was
defeated by the PRI in last month's election in Chihuahua.
Aguascalientes was seen as the PAN's best chance to make up for the
defeat.
	   Until recent years, a political novice like Gonzalez would never
have been able to defeat a candidate like Olivares, a former
senator and federal deputy whose family has long been a political
force. For most of its 69-year history, the PRI has dominated
Mexican politics, using patronage, strong-arm tactics and cheating
to crush opponents.
	   But reforms in recent years have made elections more
competitive. The Aguascalientes elections were seen as generally
fair and open.
	   ``The results of the elections in Aguascalientes are very
encouraging to the PAN,'' the party's national executive committee
said in a statement in Mexico City. ``They contribute to the
democratic process that Mexico is undergoing, to which we are fully
committed.''
	   ``For the first time we are seeing elections that are closer to
an ideal, that each day are more credible, that are now beginning
to show a respect for the will of society,'' Gonzalez said in an
interview last week.
	   In a news conference Monday, Olivares acknowledged defeat, but
said his party will bounce back.
	   ``In democracy, you win or you lose, but you don't keep winning
or losing forever,'' he said.
	   In the Gulf coast state of Veracruz, the PRI effectively
trampled over the opposition _ just as it did in its glory years.
With 98 percent of the vote tallied, Aleman had 49 percent. Luis
Pazos of National Action finished second with 27 percent.
	   Veracruz has long been a PRI stronghold, but until a few months
ago, the party was in danger of losing there. It suffered heavy
losses in last year's municipal elections and was hurt by internal
disputes. A defeat there would have devastated the PRI: Veracruz is
Mexico's third largest electorate and could prove crucial in
presidential ballotng.
	   In selecting Aleman, the PRI found someone the whole party could
support. His name _ the same as his father's _ was a huge
advantage. In Veracruz, his business success raised hopes that he
could lure businesses to the state, one of the nation's poorest.
	   Traditional bastions of PRI support such as unions and
agricultural organizations rallied around him. Critics said the
party's heavy spending and media domination gave him an unfair
advantage.
	   Aleman was also helped by divisions in the center-left
Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD. The party decided against a
PRI defector, former attorney general Ignacio Morales Lechuga, as
its candidate. Morales Lechuga ran under the banner of two small
parties. He finished fourth; the PRD candidate finished third with
18 percent of the vote.
	   The PRI on Sunday also won the governor's race in the southern
state of Oaxaca, although the PRD is challenging the count. It
claimed that results were altered after the computer system crashed
for 40 minutes on election night.
	   PRD national director Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador said the party
would not validate an election ``plagued by irregularities, that
was not clean nor free and in which the vote was manipulated.''
	   With 89 percent of the vote counted, PRI candidate Jose Nelson
Murat Casab had 48 percent of the vote; PRD candidate Hector
Sanchez had 37 percent.
	   ``My government will be plural, inclusive y democratic,'' Murat
Casab said Monday in a telephone interview. ``I will call together
all of Oaxaca's political forces and citizens of all ideologies to
work together in a project for progress.''
	   Even if the results stand, the Oaxaca elections offer some
encouragement to the PRD.
	   The party's strength in the state has steadily grown throughout
the decade. And if the PRD is to be a force in 2000, it will need
support in the rural south, traditionally a PRI stronghold. 	   
</TEXT>
