<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnappings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yemen's president approves capital punishment law for kidnappers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Yemen's president approved a law Monday that
imposes a possible death penalty for people carrying out
kidnappings, the latest attempt to curb abductions of foreigners.
	   Since 1991, tribesmen have kidnapped more than 250 foreigners to
pressure the government to provide better services and money. So
far, government efforts to stop the abductions, including sending
armed guards with tourists, have proved futile.
	   The law, signed by President Ali Abdullah Saleh, imposes the
death penalty on anyone leading a group which organizes a
kidnapping, on anyone taking part in the kidnapping itself and on
anyone carrying out highway robberies endemic to parts of Yemen.
	   Executions in Yemen are usually carried out by firing squad.
	   Kidnappers acting on their own face 12 to 25 years in prison.
Attempted kidnappings can bring 12 to 15 years in prison.
	   The law was passed earlier this month by parliament.
	   Large swaths of Yemen are ruled by tribesmen armed with
everything from rifles to artillery. But the hostages _ often oil
workers, diplomats or tourists _ are usually treated as guests and
emerge from the ordeal inconvenienced but unhurt.
	   The last kidnapping occurred July 22 when tribesmen abducted two
Belgian tourists. They were released the next day.
 &UR; str-mae-as
</TEXT>
