w1053 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-Obit-Schnittk 2ndLd-Writethru   08-03 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Obit-Schnittke, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German-Russian composer Alfred Schnittke dies at 63
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with comments from cellist Rostropovich, Sept.
10 funeral date. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HAMBURG, Germany (AP) _ Alfred Schnittke, one of the former
Soviet Union's most prolific composers whose works ranged from
symphonies to movie themes, died Monday in Hamburg. He was 63.
	   Schnittke, the son of a Russian mother and a German-Jewish
father, died at Hamburg's University Hospital, where he had been
admitted after suffering his fourth stroke over a period of many
years, his wife, Irina, said.
	   A creator of ``polystylism,'' or mixture of musical forms, he
was spurned in his homeland at the beginning of his career, but by
the 1980s had won over Soviet cultural authorities.
	   Russian cellist Mstislav Rostropovich, who conducted and played
in premieres of many of Schnittke's pieces, said ``a genius
composer, and the most outstanding of my friends has died.''
	   ``This is one of the last losses in my life. I have nobody and
nothing to lose now,'' Rostropovich said.
	   Russian President Boris Yeltsin sent a telegram Monday to Irina
Schnittke in Hamburg saying he shared her family's ``huge grief.''
	   ``A great composer of modern times has departed. With his
creation, Alfred Schnittke carried out a genuine revolution in
music,'' Yeltsin wrote. ``He brought glory to the culture of his
homeland and enriched the tradition of the Russian classical music
school with his unique, innovative ideas.''
	   The unorthodox composer was among five winners in 1992 of the
prestigious Praemium Imperiale for lifetime achievement in the
arts, given by the Japan Art Association.
	   Schnittke's final composition, the Ninth Symphony, had its world
premiere this spring in the Great Hall of the Moscow Conservatory.
Schnittke was seriously ill, unable to talk or move much, by the
time he composed it, Russian media reports said. The right-handed
composer wrote the piece with his left hand.
	   The ITAR-Tass news agency said the composer is to be buried
Sept. 10 at Moscow's Novodevichye cemetery _ a high honor in
Russia.
	   Schnittke was born on November 24, 1934, in Engels, a small town
on the Volga River in what was then called the Volga German
Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic, an area that had been settled
by Germans in the 18th century.
	   The son of Harry Schnittke, a German-born Jew of Latvian
descent, and Maria Vogel, a Volga-German Catholic, he was
influenced by both the Russian and German cultures.
	   Music did not play a big role in his life until 1946, the year
his family moved to Vienna, where his father began working for a
Soviet German-language paper.
	   One of the first pieces Schnittke heard on the radio in Vienna
was Shostakovich's Ninth Symphony, which he found, in his words,
``very refreshing, but also very strange.''
	   Increasingly obsessed with music, he started taking piano
lessons with a local teacher, Charlotte Ruber, and he soon
developed an interest in composition.
	   The two years his family spent in Vienna were of ``decisive
importance'' in his life, he once wrote.
	   ``I recall a basic musical tone, a certain Mozart-Schubert sound
which I carried within me for decades and which was confirmed upon
my next stay in Austria some 30 years later,'' he said.
	   Returning to the Soviet Union with his parents in 1948,
Schnittke enrolled at the Institute of the October Revolution, a
music preparatory school in Moscow.
	   Five years later, he entered the Moscow Conservatory, where the
composers Nicolai Rakov and Evgeny Golubev were among his
instructors.
	   As part of his graduation requirements, he composed an oratorio,
Nagasaki, that included an atomic blast as part of the score,
offering an early glimpse of the unorthodox musical approach he
would adopt in later years.
	   In 1961 he joined the faculty himself, and for the next 10 years
taught instrumentation, polyphony, and composition at the
conservatory.
	   Schnittke's long list of compositions includes five symphonies,
a piano concerto, four violin concertos, five concerto grossos, two
concertos each for viola and cello, two oratorios, six ballets,
numerous choral, chamber, and instrumental pieces, and arrangements
of works by Shostakovich, Berg, Scott Joplin, and others.
	   He also has about 60 Soviet film scores to his credit, most of
them written between 1961 and 1984.
	   Schnittke is survived by his wife, Irina Katayeva, and a son.
The couple divided their time between homes in Moscow and Hamburg.
	    &UR; (gb-pfg-im)
</TEXT>
