<SLUG> BC-Norway-Polar Bear,0216 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tourists warned about wounded polar bear in Norway
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ Tourists and tour operators in the Norwegian
Arctic archipelago of Svalbard have been warned that a wounded
polar bear is on the loose and could be dangerous.
	   A Norwegian guide shot the bear in the neck Saturday when it
attacked a group of British tourists in the Bille Fjord area.
	   The bear disappeared into the icy wilderness, leaving a bloody
trail in the snow.
	   Governor Ann-Kristin Olsen, who also is chief of police in the
Arctic territory, 700 miles (1,100 kilometers) north of the
mainland, warned people not to travel to the area about 30 miles
(50 kilometers) from Longyearbyen.
	   None of the six British tourists or their Norwegian guide were
hurt in the incident.
	   Polar bears are a protected species, and hunting them was banned
some 25 years ago. The governor's office is looking into whether
the shooting Saturday was self-defense.
	   Although encounters with polar bears are rare in the more
accessible areas of Svalbard during the summer, people who venture
outside Longyearbyen are strongly recommended to carry a gun for
protection.
	   In 1995 a French tourist and a Norwegian woman were killed by
polar bears in two different incidents in Svalbard. 	   
</TEXT>
