<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Today In History, 1st Ld-Writethru,0595 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saturday, August 8
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS day of week and year in overline. &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Today is Saturday, August 8, the 220th day of 1998. There are
145 days left in the year.
	   Highlights in history on this date:
	   1549 - France declares war on England.
	   1567 - Duke of Alba arrives in Netherlands as military governor
with 10,000 veteran Spanish and Italian troops.
	   1570 - Peace of St. Germain-en-Laye ends third Civil War in
France, whereby Huguenots gain greater concessions; Turkish forces
sack Nicosia, Cyprus.
	   1588 - British sea forces under Sir Francis Drake destroy
Spanish Armada in battle off France.
	   1647 - Irish forces are defeated by British Parliamentary forces
at Dangan Hill in Ireland.
	   1815 - France's Napoleon Bonaparte sails for St. Helena to spend
remainder of his life in exile.
	   1832 - East India Company under William Bentinck annexes Cathar
after residents ask for British protection.
	   1940 - Germany begins concentrated bombing of Britain in World
War II.
	   1953 - United States and South Korea sign mutual defense treaty.
	   1960 - United Nations demands evacuation of Belgian troops from
Congo.
	   1964 - Turkish planes attack Cyprus.
	   1965 - City of Singapore withdraws from Federation of Malaysia
and becomes independent state.
	   1974 - U.S. President Richard M. Nixon announces his
resignation, under threat of impeachment.
	   1986 - Car bomb explodes in busy shopping street in Muslim west
Beirut, killing 17 people and wounding 84.
	   1988 - Iran's President Ali Khamenei says eight-year-old Gulf
War with Iraq ``is apparently coming to a close.''
	   1990 - Iraq formally annexes Kuwait after U.S. President George
Bush says Iraq must vacate that country and British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher orders British air and naval forces to gulf at
King Fahd's request.
	   1991 - Lebanese kidnappers free British TV producer John
McCarthy after holding him hostage for five years.
	   1992 - President Denis Sassou-Nguesso loses his seat in Republic
of Congo's first presidential election since 1963.
	   1993 - Four U.S. servicemen are killed in Somalia when a mine
destroys their vehicle.
	   1994 - Israel and Jordan open first road linking the two
nations.
	   1995 - The ``AIDS gang,'' a group of bankrobbers who are secure
in the knowledge that they cannot be jailed under Italian law
because they have AIDS, are freed again after their fourth hold-up
in three weeks. Their latest heist is done in full view of security
cameras, with no face masks and only a pocket knife.
	   1996 - In Spain flash floods race through a Pyrenees Mountain
camp jammed with hundreds of vacationers, carrying away cars, tents
and campers in rivers of mud and debris, killing at least 67
people.
	   1997 - Waving the red and yellow flags of the country's
democracy movement, students block the entrance to Myanmar's
Embassy in Bangkok and chant denunciations of the military regime
on the ninth anniversary of a democracy uprising crushed by
soldiers in Myanmar.
	   Today's Birthdays:
	   Sir Godfrey Kneller, English artist (1646-1723); Francis
Hutcheson, Scottish philosopher (1694-1746); Esther Williams, U.S.
swimmer-actress (1923--); Dustin Hoffman, U.S. actor (1937--);
Connie Stevens, U.S. actress (1938--); Peter Weir, Australian film
director (1944--).
	   Thought For Today:
	   Man adjusts to what he should not; he is unable to adjust to
what he should. Jean Toomer, African-American author-poet
(1894-1967).
</TEXT>
