w1080 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Caribbean-DeathRow     08-03 0229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Death Row,0228 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
English-speaking Caribbean has 250 people on death row, group says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ English-speaking nations in the Caribbean now
have 250 people on death row out of a population of about 5 million
_ one of the highest death-sentence rates in the world, the human
rights group Amnesty International says.
	   Trinidad and Tobago accounts for 104 of the cases, the group
said in a report released Monday. Jamaica is next with 47 cases,
the Bahamas has 40, Guyana has 24 and Belize has nine.
	   There are 26 people on death row in Barbados and the countries
that make up the Organization of Eastern Caribbean States _ Antigua
and Barbuda, Dominica, Grenada, St. Kitts and Nevis, St. Lucia and
St. Vincent and the Grenadines.
	   The death row rate is almost four times that of the United
States, which has 260 million people and 3,300 convicts awaiting
execution, the group said.
	   Britain and international human rights groups have been
pressuring former British colonies to eliminate the death penalty.
Caribbean countries have resisted, saying capital punishment helps
deter crime caused by drug traffic through the region.
	   The countries are planning to create a regional supreme court to
replace the British Privy Council, which serves as the final court
of appeal for the former colonies and has moved to limit
executions. 	   
</TEXT>
