<HEADLINE>
Some residents defy Mother Teresa's order
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CALCUTTA, India (AP) _ Some local residents on Monday petitioned
a court for permission to install a bronze statue of Mother Teresa
in this city next month to commemorate the first anniversary of her
death.
	   The residents, who have formed a committee, approached the court
after Mother Teresa's Missionary of Charities objected to their
raising funds in the name of the nun. Calcutta was for decades the
home of Mother Teresa, who worked for the dying and the destitutes.
	   High Court Judge Prabir Samanta said he would hear the
petitioners on Wednesday.
	   Sister Nirmala, who succeeded Mother Teresa as the
superior-general of the Missionaries of Charity, has disapproved of
the committee's plans, saying Mother Teresa herself had warned
people not to use her name to raise funds after her death.
	   The Missionaries of Charity planned a simple mass and prayer on
Mother Teresa's death anniversary. 	   
</TEXT>
