<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian, 1st Ld,0353 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinians say latest round of talks could be the last
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with talks over, no comments from either side,
Palestinian delegation briefing Arafat in Gaza; ADDS in graf 9
comment from senior official &QL; 
 &UR; By DANNA HARMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel and Palestinian negotiators met Monday
night in a round of talks that Palestinians said could be the last
if no progress was made toward an overdue West Bank troop
withdrawal.
	   The talks between chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and
Israeli envoy Yitzhak Molcho lasted several hours at an undisclosed
location in Jerusalem, and neither negotiator was reachable for
comment at their conclusion.
	   Erekat and his staff then left for Gaza where they were expected
to brief Palestinian Authority leader Yasser Arafat on the talks,
Arafat's office said.
	   Ahmed Tibi, an adviser to Arafat, said earlier Monday that if
the Israelis did not bring new ideas, ``this kind of meeting cannot
continue.''
	   ``We are waiting to see a change in the attitude of the
Israelis,'' Tibi said. ``If not, this means (Prime Minister
Benjamin) Netanyahu has said no to the last chance to revive the
peace process.''
	   Israel radio reported that the Palestinians were considering
whether to continue talks Tuesday and promised the Israelis an
answer after a late night briefing with Arafat.
	   Senior negotiators from the two sides have been meeting for the
past two weeks, after months without direct talks, in an effort to
come to an agreement on a West Bank troop withdrawal. Talks resumed
Monday night in Jerusalem.
	   The Palestinians have complained that no progress has been made,
and that Israel has continued to resist an American proposal for a
13 percent withdrawal.
	   A Palestinian official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the Palestinians would not accept a reported Israeli proposal for a
10 percent withdrawal plus an additional 3 percent that would be
considered a ``nature reserve'' and where the Palestinians could
not build.
	   Palestinian Planning, 7th graf pvs 	   
