w1131 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 8thLd-Writethru   08-03 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 8th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serbs press attacks in Kosovo after vowing that offensive is over
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with U.S. announcing possibility of using NATO fire
power in final grafs.
 &UR; AP Photos &QC; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Sweeping Serb military attacks on
ethnic Albanian rebels have created a refugee population that puts
Kosovo province ``on the verge of a humanitarian catastrophe,''
U.S. envoy Christopher Hill said Monday.
	   With tens of thousands of refugees living in the woods or in
isolated villages without food or water, Hill said it was essential
that the international community be allowed to help people safely
return to their homes.
	   Serb forces took another Albanian stronghold Monday, a Serb
source told The Associated Press. The source said police cautiously
entered the village of Lausa, some 35 kilometers (20 miles)
northwest of Pristina, which has been under control of the
secessionist Kosovo Liberation Army since March.
	   The attack came just days after Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic vowed that his military push against the KLA had stopped.
	   Milosevic also promised last week to ``personally guarantee''
access for refugee agencies trying to bring aid to displaced ethnic
Albanian civilians. Nevertheless, U.N. refugee official Mons Nyber
said Monday that access had been ``on and off.''
	   In Geneva, the spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, Kris Janowski, said the fighting had so disrupted
transport and communications that ``we are back to square one,''
unable to reach pockets of refugees. The agency estimated that at
least 50,000 people fled the weekend fighting, swelling the number
of refugees to 200,000 since the government launched its crackdown
on Albanian militants in March.
	   U.S. envoy Hill has proposed that diplomatic monitors be allowed
to escort refugees back to their homes, saying it was necessary to
show ethnic Albanian civilians that the international community
supports them. Milosevic has agreed to the plan, but some diplomats
question whether he actually would permit it.
	   Albanian sources said Serb forces continued an offensive in the
border area between Djakovica and Junik, a key rebel stronghold,
which came under grenade fire for eighth day Monday.
	   Serb sources also said troops continued to lay siege to Junik, a
key rebel stronghold. Serb military sources said police entered
Smonica early Monday, after troops had been shelling the Albanian
border village for days. The fighting killed at least a dozen KLA
fighters, the military said.
	   A woman and her son were killed late Sunday when trying to cross
from the Serbian province into Montenegro, the other Yugoslav
republic, Albanian sources said.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9
	   The U.N. refugee agency also was planning a convoy Tuesday or
Wednesday for ethnic Albanians in villages near Malisevo. Many of
those refugees had fled villages destroyed by Serb shells.
	   In Albania's capital, Tirana, a Kosovo Albanian party accused
the Serb-led Yugoslav government of trying ``to make it impossible
for thousands of Albanians to return to their homes.''
	   But a senior diplomat questioned assertions that the Serb
campaign against Albanian civilians was reminiscent of ``ethnic
cleansing,'' the forcible removal of rival ethnicities that marked
conflicts in the former Yugoslav republics of Bosnia and Croatia
earlier this decade.
	   The diplomat, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said it
appeared that Serbs were clearing only those villages near key
roads that the KLA had blocked in recent months. He also said the
Serbs were likely to insist they had indeed ceased their military
attacks, and that police forces were merely securing their hold on
former KLA territory.
	   KLA leaders were expected to announce this week whether they
will accept a U.S. plan to join Albanian politicians in peace
negotiations with Milosevic. While rebels and politicians share a
goal for independence, politicians say they would accept autonomy
as a first step.
	   Rebels have so far opposed this plan, and the current Serb
offensive appears designed to deliver a strong blow against the
rebels and force them to negotiate from a position of weakness.
	   Milosevic has offered only to restore Kosovo's autonomy, and
major world powers also oppose independence for the province. The
United States and European nations fear independence could lead to
demands by Albanian speaking communities in Macedonia and
Montenegro to establish a ``greater Albania'' in the southern
Balkans.
	   In Washington, the administration of U.S. President Bill Clinton
said a new Serb offensive could result in the use of NATO firepower
against Serb forces in the province.
	   There was no immediate word on what would trigger an attack by
NATO. Nor was it clear whether the administration was trying mostly
to unnerve Milosevic by raising the threat again publicly.
	   Officials at NATO headquarters in Brussels said the alliance has
been putting the final touches on a number of options, but these
plans were nothing new.
	   (pvs/me) 	   
</TEXT>
