<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Old Debt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In Spanish mountains, a mouse roars
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANAR, Spain (AP) _ This mountain hamlet has a very old bone to
pick with the government.
	   The mayor of Canar -- population 300 or so -- is pressing Madrid
to honor a promise that King Felipe II made in the late 16th
century. In today's money the bill comes to about 140 dollars.
	   Nearly 400 years ago the monarch put a price on the head of a
Moorish bandit blamed for a massacre of Christians in southern
Spain.
	   The people of Canar captured him, and were rewarded with a royal
decree granting them 180 reales, the currency at the time, per year
in perpetuity.
	   They got the money until 1883, by which time Spain's currency
was the peseta. That year the government decided the king's
arrangement was outdated, and made a lump-sum payment to cover the
next 20 years.
	   After that the funds dried up. Now, Canar wants the installments
for the last 115 years.
	   ``A mayor has to have a goal,'' said the mayor, Manuel Mesa
Torres, 36.
	   He said that on Tuesday the town council will send Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar legal papers asking him to make good on
King Felipe II's pledge. Canar is acting now because 1998 marks the
400th anniversary of the king's death, Mesa said.
	   The debt -- 115 years of arrears at 180 pesetas per year --
stands at 20,700 pesetas. That's 138 dollars.
	   ``We hope the prime minister or a member of his cabinet will see
fit to pay up,'' said Mesa.
	   Asked about the interest accrued over all these years, he said
it would be nice if the government added three zeros to the bottom
line. ``Zeros to the right, of course,'' he said.
	   dw
</TEXT>
