<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-German Police,0670 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Patroling with U.S. cops eye-opener for Berlin policemen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITS to ADD photo numbers &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY188-189 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRIS TOMLINSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MONTCLAIR, New Jersey (AP) _ Gun violence shocked them, so did
the prevalence of bullet-proof vests and the Russian mafia. But the
concept of community policing, unknown back home in Germany, taught
them the most.
	   Two Berlin policemen who spent a month studying U.S. police
techniques in urban areas say they're taking back crime-fighting
ideas that could be applied to their own city.
	   Hartmut Zander, 31, and Olaf Gratzke, 22, were the guests of
police chief Thomas Russo in Montclair, New Jersey, a middle class
city across the Hudson River from New York City.
	   Their American study tour, paid from their own pockets, included
stops in New York, Boston, Newark, New Jersey, and Manchester,
Connecticut.
	   ``The police work in general is the same, in detail there are a
lot differences,'' Zander said Saturday, a day before flying home
to Berlin. ``In America every patrolman wears a (bulletproof) vest,
it is not the same in Germany.''
	   Zander pointed to America's liberal gun laws as the main
difference in crime in America and Germany.
	   ``America has a gun problem,'' said Zander, who will become a
homicide detective next year. ``In Berlin, we have 100 murders a
year and we have 3 1-2 million people. Chicago has 800 a year'' _
and less than 3 million residents.
	   While the gun violence shocked the Germans, Zander and Gratzke
said they learned the most from community policing, a program that
integrates police work with community involvement. He found
Boston's use of the technique, and its results, especially
interesting.
	   ``Community policing was one of the very, very, very impressive
things here,'' Zander said. ``How the police fight crime, meet the
youngsters and know people by name was very good.''
	   American police take a more informal approach to law enforcement
compared to German police, Gratzke said. He said the New York
Police Athletic League's basketball program, where officers coach
and play teen-agers, was not only interesting, but fun.
	   ``I would like to take this experience back to Europe and wonder
if there are other ways to solve the problems there,'' he said.
	   The Berliners were able to see community policing in a variety
of settings, ranging from relatively prosperous Montclair to the
impoverished Fort Apache neighborhood in the South Bronx of New
York City. Zander said the police knew the people they policed,
which also allowed them to know where the crime was coming from.
	   ``We went on patrol in the real bad area,'' Zander said. ``It
was terrible, the people are very poor, there is lots of crime and
it's very dangerous.''
	   They noted that crime has become more international, requiring
police from both sides of the Atlantic Ocean to work together.
	   ``Your cocaine is our cocaine, it comes from the same place. Our
heroin is your heroin. Money laundering is a worldwide business,''
Zander said.
	   He also noted that Russian-based organized crime is another
shared problem.
	   ``We have a lot of Russians in Berlin and the head of the FBI,
the (police) commisioner in New York and the head of the Boston
police said that Russian gangs are also here,'' Zander said.
	   While Zander and Gratzke had to volunteer their vacation days
and pay their own expenses, they said the experience will help
their chances for promotion if they decide to move into
international police work.
	   Both police officers agreed that American police could also
benefit from a few weeks working with their German counterparts.
	   ``American police have problems and they have found some good
answers to those problems. In our country we have different
problems and we have found solutions to our problems,'' Zander
said. ``I am sure the big police departments will be working
together in the future more and more.''
</TEXT>
