<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Obit-Bartok </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eva Bartok, 1950s movie actress, dies at 69
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Eva Bartok, Hungarian-born film actress of the
1950s and '60s, has died in London at age 69.
	   Miss Bartok died Saturday at St. Charles' Hospital in London
after being ill for some time, a hospital spokesman said. The cause
of death was not given, but news reports said she had had heart
trouble.
	   Although she never became a major star, Miss Bartok made nearly
40 films, including ``Operation Amsterdam'' with Peter Finch and
``The Crimson Pirate'' with Burt Lancaster.
	   Miss Bartok had a daughter, Deana, in 1957, when she was married
to German actor Curt Jurgens, but in recent years claimed the
girl's father was Frank Sinatra. She said Sinatra never
acknowledged the claim.
	   Born Eva Ivanova Szoeke in Kecskemet, Hungary, in 1929, she was
imprisoned in a concentration camp as a teen-ager and married to a
Nazi, The Daily Telegraph said, adding that the marriage was
annulled on the grounds of coercion of a minor.
	   Her second husband, Alex Paal, was a Hungarian producer. Eva
arrived in London in 1948, where director Alexander Korda met her
and changed her name to Bartok.
	   Her first film was ``A Tale of Five Women,'' produced by Paal,
in 1951. The following year, she appeared in ``The Venetian Bird''
with Richard Todd.
	   Her marriage to Paal broke up and she married Bill Wordsworth, a
public relations man. That marriage came apart while she was in
Rome making her most famous movie, ``The Crimson Pirate,'' in 1952.
	   She met British aristocrat the Marquess of Milford Haven at a
London dinner in 1952. They embarked on a highly publicized
relationship that lasted for several years.
	   Miss Bartok met Jurgens when they made a movie together in
Germany and her relationship with the marquess broke up. She and
Jurgens married in 1955, but that marriage began to founder by the
following year.
	   In 1956, Miss Bartok said, she met Frank Sinatra at a party
while she was in Hollywood making her first American film, ``Ten
Thousand Bedrooms'' with Dean Martin.
	   Sinatra's marriage to Ava Gardner had broken up. Miss Bartok
said she had very brief affair with the singer.
	   In the last years of her life, she lived in a London hotel.
	   She is survived by her daughter, who lives in Australia, and two
grandchildren. Funeral plans were not immediately made known.
	   (acw) 	   
</TEXT>
