<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Full Monty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wallabies didn't keep their hats on
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) _ Australian rugby union players
Tim Horan and Phil Kearns celebrated their Bledisloe Cup win over
New Zealand on Saturday with a nude dip in the Avon River.
	   Horan and Kearns _ along with a puzzled Christchurch cabbie and
a set of hotel towels _ ventured into the night about midnight
Saturday night.
	   Delighted with their 27-23 Bledisloe Cup win, the Australians
traveled by taxi to the edge of the Avon River, where they stripped
off and jumped in, wearing nothing but their victorious smiles.
	   ``It was a lot warmer than I thought it was going to be,''
Kearns said. ``No one saw it, other than a shocked cabbie. It was
all well-planned.''
	   The 65-test veteran explained the tradition of the skinny-dip.
Horan and then-captain Nick Farr-Jones went the Full Monty in
Wellington Harbor after the Wallabies' 21-9 win over the All Blacks
at Athletic Park in 1990.
	   ``It's tradition. We thought we may as well continue it,''
Kearns said. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
