<SLUG> BC-Venezuela-Bank Scandal,0240 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former head of bank sentenced to 15 years in prison
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ The former president of a bank whose
collapse helped set off one of the largest banking scandals in
recent Latin American history was sentenced Monday to 15 years in
prison.
	   Gustavo Gomez Lopez, who headed Banco Latino when it went under
in January 1994, was found guilty of five charges including
diversion of public funds and falsifying documents to cover up
fraudulent activities.
	   Judge Maria Inmaculada Perez Dupuy also ordered Gomez Lopez to
repay the government an amount still to be determined, that could
reach several million dollars.
	   Four other former high-level officials of the bank also were
convicted in the case, and 31 former employees were absolved.
	   Gomez Lopez, who fled Venezuela and is living overseas, plans to
appeal the decision, said his lawyer, Jose Morris Sierralta.
	   Banco Latino and 17 other banks were taken over by the
government in 1994-95 after they nearly went bankrupt from
mismanagement and corruption. The government pumped dlrs 8 billion
_ about half the national budget at the time _ into the system to
avoid a complete collapse.
	   In the aftermath, about 200 bankers fled the country and are
believed to be living in the United States and Europe. Authorities
issued arrest warrants for most of them, but just a couple have
been detained.
</TEXT>
