w1237 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Chiapas     08-03 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas,0282 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebel supporters criticize presence of U.S. military attache in
</HEADLINE>
Chiapas &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Backers of leftist
rebels in this southern state say revelations that a U.S. military
attache has visited the state prove U.S. meddling in the conflict.
	   Leaders of major political parties last week condemned the visit
by Maj. Thomas Gillen, an assistant attache at the U.S. Embassy who
was detained for several hours on July 26 by government supporters
in the Chiapas village of Los Platanos.
	   The leftist Zapatista National Liberation Army didn't like the
news of the visit very much either.
	   ``This is proof that the gringos are up to their elbows in the
armed conflict,'' said Javier Elorriaga, coordinator of the
Zapatista National Liberation Front, a group which says it is
allied with but separate from the rebel army.
	   Gillen was blocked from leaving because he refused to let
pro-government villagers inspect his luggage. He and another
embassy employee were released after about 4 1/2 hours.
	   The U.S. State Department has said Gillen was in Chiapas as part
of ``normal fact-finding'' duties.
	   Elorriaga claimed such visits are proof that ``they (Americans)
are the one who are training most of the Mexican officers in
counterinsurgency and arming them.''
	   The Mexican government cautioned the embassy on the risks
involved in traveling to Chiapas and asked for advance notice of
future visits.
	   The Zapatista National Liberation Army staged a brief armed
uprising in January 1994 demanding greater democracy and Indian
rights. Talks between the government and the rebels have been
stalled for the last two years. 	   
</TEXT>
