</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Army Wedding </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli army hosts wedding for young immigrant soldier
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Pvt. Arieh Torliansky got an order from
Israel's defense minister Monday that he couldn't refuse: Take your
bride for a honeymoon anywhere in Israel on me.
	   Torliansky, a 24-year-old immigrant from the former Soviet Union
didn't have enough money for a wedding, so his army commanders and
fellow soldiers threw one for him at his army base on the Lebanese
border Monday.
	   Living on a soldier's meak salary while his wife, Yanina
Tashnikov, also a recent immigrant studying at a local college, the
couple, which has few relatives in Israel, could not afford a
wedding, the Israeli army said.
	   So army cooks worked up a feast, a military chaplain performed
the ceremony and an Army radio disc jockey volunteered to play the
music for free.
	   After the ceremony, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
telephoned the young couple to congratulate them and gave
Torliansky a three-day weekend furlough with his bride at any hotel
in the country at the minister's expense.
 &UR; jk-dl 	   
</TEXT>
