<SLUG> BC-Grenada-Castro's Friend, 1st Ld-Writethru,0627 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spirit of executed revolutionary haunts Grenada 15 years later
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS 6 new grafs with Castro rally. TRIMS old material, no
pickup &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo GRD101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHELLE FAUL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) _ Fifteen years have passed, but the
execution of charismatic Cuban-allied revolutionary Maurice Bishop,
and the bloody U.S. invasion that followed, still haunt this island
perfumed by frangipani and nutmeg.
	   ``The same people he helped turned and killed him,'' the former
leader's mother, Alimenta Bishop, said Monday before meeting with
Cuban President Fidel Castro.
	   Castro's visit, part of a historic Caribbean tour, has stirred
memories of the complex and confusing October of 1983.
	   Castro received a warm welcome from thousands of supporters at
an outdoor rally Monday afternoon held at a sports field decorated
with small red, green and yellow flags.
	   As he stood up to speak, thunderous chants of ``Fidel. Fidel''
roared from the crowd. Before he could speak, the audience starting
singing a song from the 1979 Grenadian Revolution: ``Forward march.
Forward march against imperialism.''
	   Castro referred to the anniversary of the abolition of slavery
in the British-ruled Caribbean 160 years ago, then likened the
oppression of slavery to the U.S. embargo against Cuba.
	   ``Those who took a part of our wealth later, they are the great
countries, the rich countries now ... thanks to the sweat and blood
of slaves and natives,'' he said. ``If slavery could not last
forever, the blockade cannot last forever.''
	   He and Grenadian Prime Minister Keith Mitchell congratulated
Grenada's Caribbean neighbors for defying U.S. pressure and said
they believed the embargo's end was near. ``The American people
themselves, the same way they did during the war in Vietnam, the
American people themselves will put an end to that cruel and unfair
action,'' Castro said.
	   Mitchell also endorsed Cuba for acceptance back into the
Organization of American States, which has shunned the communist
island.
	   Earlier, Mrs. Bishop hugged Castro and took him into her home.
Afterward, neither she nor her guest would discuss their meeting.
	   But in an interview with The Associated Press, Mrs. Bishop, 83,
agreed to talk about her son's last days, saying she blamed his
death only on hard-line Marxists in his New Jewel Movement who
betrayed him _ not the United States, or Cuba, or the Cold War.
	   In 1979, Bishop ousted the corrupt and dictatorial regime of
Eric Gairy, believed here to have used powers from the dark side of
the African-inherited Obeah religion.
	   The handsome revolutionary, who won the hearts of many
Grenadians, rankled Caribbean neighbors and the United States with
his close ties to Castro. But when he was ousted in early October
1983, it was by allies who thought him ideologically too soft.
	   Hundreds of supporters formed a human shield around Bishop when
he was taken from house arrest to the military headquarters at Fort
George several days later.
	   But their protection was inadequate: tanks moved in and soldiers
lined Bishop and his colleagues _ including his lover and Education
Minister Jacqueline Creft _ against a stone wall and shot them.
Many jumped from the back wall of the fort, some to their deaths.
Fire trucks had to wash the blood from the wall.
	   The United States had never been enamored of Bishop, but liked
his fearsome successors even less. A few days after the execution,
President Ronald Reagan sent a U.S.-led invasion force to the
island.
	   Armed Cuban construction workers who had been building an
airport were kicked out after what was the only American-Cuban
fighting of the Cold War. 	   
</TEXT>
