<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0616 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Stocks fell sharply Monday after another late
selloff as the market's steep slide entered a third week. The Dow
Jones industrial average fell 96.55 points _ or 1.1 percent _ to
8,786.74 despite two fleeting forays into positive territory during
the day. The blue-chip barometer now sits about 550 points below
the record of 9,337.97 set on July 17. Broader stock indicators
also suffered hefty losses, with the smaller-company sector
continuing to draw the heaviest selling. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Americans kept spending at a strong pace in
June even though their incomes posted the smallest increase in 3
1/2 years. The combination of weak income growth and strong
spending pushed the personal savings rate down to an all-time low.
The Commerce Department reported Monday that personal incomes rose
by just 0.2 percent in June, just half of the 0.4 percent May gain.
The big decline reflected in part a loss of dlrs 2 billion, at an
annual rate, in wages because of the General Motors strike, which
was not settled until last week. A closely watched barometer of the
manufacturing sector, the National Association of Purchasing
Management's composite index, retreated again in July, dropping to
49.1 percent, down from 49.6 percent in June. (US-ECONOMY)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ With its coffers temporarily filled by a loan from
the International Monetary Fund, Russia announced Monday that it
would not hold a government bond auction this week. ``The ministry
simply didn't announce an auction for this week because it doesn't
need the money,'' a Finance Ministry spokeswoman said. Yields on
the benchmark one-year treasury bills, known as GKOs, rose to
between 75 percent and 78 percent on Monday, from 68 percent
Friday. Stocks closed at 145.64 points, down 2.7 percent from
Friday's close of 149.65 points. Volume was minute at dlrs 12.5
million, down from dlrs 25.8 million Friday. The Russian ruble
closed lower against the dollar in slow trading as investors sold
government bonds. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   ROCHESTER, New York (AP) _ Eastman Kodak Co. is buying the
medical imaging business of Imation Corp. for approximately dlrs
520 million in cash. The deal gives Kodak manufacturing facilities
in White City, Oregon, and Oakdale, Minnesota, as well as all the
outstanding shares of Imation's Cemax-Icon subsidiary in Fremont,
California. Imation's medical imaging business has annual sales of
dlrs 500 million. Approximately 1,600 of Imation's 9,500 employees
will transfer to Kodak. Imation will retain its manufacturing
facility in Ferrania, Italy, where the company will manufacture
X-ray and wet laser medical imaging film for Kodak under a supply
agreement for a minimum of two years. Under a separate supply
agreement, Kodak will supply document imaging products to Imation.
(US-KODAK-IMATION)
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ President Mohammad Khatami has called for
reducing government monopolies on goods and services, eliminating
the red tape holding back foreign investment and cutting the
country's reliance on oil revenues. The moderate cleric, who took
office one year ago, said Iran's ``sick'' economy has suffered from
several decades of mismanagement and needs fundamental changes,
such as reducing government intervention. He outlined his
long-awaited economic proposals in a speech broadcast on state
radio late Sunday. The remarks were reported Monday in the Iran
News. (IRAN-ECONOMY)
</TEXT>
