r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PeopleandPlaces     08-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0809 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Tiger Woods, speeding ferry, Caught in the
Act, George Bush, and Kathie-Lee Gifford. Some items may have moved
as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   DETROIT (AP) _ The father of golfer Tiger Woods says parents
must set a good example and listen to their children if they want
to earn their respect.
	   ``It's surprising how infrequently parents listen to their
kids,'' Earl Woods said Sunday.
	   Woods spoke to about 2,500 people at Hartford Memorial Baptist
Church. He was in Detroit for a golf clinic sponsored by the Tiger
Woods Foundation.
	   ``People will listen and try his advice because his son turned
out so well,'' church member Margaret Betts said.
	   Tiger Woods provided golf tips at the clinic Monday for about
125 young golfers from Detroit, Flint and Toledo, Ohio.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) _ The Cat's owners boast that it's the
fastest car ferry in North America _ a dlrs 44 million vessel that
can hit 55 mph (88 kph) as it shuttles between the United States
and Canada.
	   And now it's got its first speeding ticket.
	   Harbor Master Eddie Monat cited The Cat's captain, Kenneth
Smith, for ``imprudent speed'' after two Massachusetts boaters were
injured by its wake Saturday afternoon. Smith is scheduled to be
arraigned Sept. 19.
	   Monat said the boat dropped out from under the boaters, sending
them five feet (1.5 meters) into the air. Debra Kelley landed on
her face, and Joanne Kelley, her sister-in-law, fell on her ankle.
Both were treated at a hospital.
	   The harbor has no speed limit, but boaters are responsible for
their wakes. It wasn't clear how fast The Cat was going, but Monat
said it only hits top speed on the open ocean.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   GULFPORT, Mississippi (AP) _ Showgirls dancing at two casinos on
the Mississippi Gulf Coast have been ordered to show less skin.
	   State Alcohol Beverage Control agents called for more modesty
after taking a peek at some of the Las Vegas-style shows.
	   Costumes were altered to add fabric to thongs at Biloxi's Grand
Theatre and the Grand Showroom in Gulfport, according to Jean
Herbert-Wiesenburg, spokeswoman for Grand Casino.
	   ``We will comply, but the regulations do not allow any latitude
and we will work vigorously to change these regulations,'' she
said.
	   ABC agent Mark Ford said his office suggested changes to some
costumes but did not file formal charges.
	   The agents were dispatched to the shows, he said, after patrons
complained.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Caught in the Act, one of Europe's
most successful boy groups, will make a quick farewell tour this
month before disbanding after six years together, a spokeswoman
said Monday.
	   The two Dutch members, Eloy de Jong and Batsiann Ragas, and
Benjamin Boyce and Lee Baxter of Britain, all now in their mid-20s,
will hit the road Saturday and play their final show in Magdeburg,
in eastern Germany on Aug. 16, said the spokeswoman for ZYX Records
in Frankfurt.
	   The four singers, whose hits include ``You Know,'' ``Do It for
Love,'' and ``Baby Come Back,'' also plan a greatest hits album in
September.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The House of Representatives agreed Monday
with the Senate to rename the Central Intelligence Agency's
headquarters after George Bush, the only president whose resume
includes a stint as CIA director.
	   During brief debate, lawmakers from both parties extolled Bush's
long service to the nation, from his days as a World War II Navy
pilot to his years in the White House. The legislation was adopted
by voice vote.
	   The Senate already has voted to rename CIA headquarters in
Langley, Virginia, the George H. W. Bush Center for Central
Intelligence.
	   When informed of the House's action, Bush said he was ``very
pleased,'' said spokesman Michael Dannenhauer.
	   Bush became CIA director in 1976, while the agency was under
congressional investigation for abuses of power. During his year
there, Bush was credited with restoring morale to the agency's
beleaguered staff.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ It was ``Live With Winnie and Kathie Lee,
and Tigger, too.''
	   U.S. talk-show host Kathie-Lee Gifford appeared at the United
Nations on Monday to celebrate ``Pooh Friendship Day.''
	   The Walt Disney Corp. brought in 50 pairs of friends _ 25 pairs
of kids and 25 pairs of adults _ from as far afield as Australia
and Japan to celebrate international friendship day with Winnie the
Pooh and his pals Tigger, Kanga, Eeyore and Piglet.
	   Ms. Gifford _ accompanied by kids Cody and Cassidy _ sang
standards from the Pooh repertoire, along with Tyler Collins,
another stalwart of Disney albums for children.
	   The original stuffed animals on which A.A. Milne's beloved
stories are based are in a display case at the New York Public
Library.
</TEXT>
