w1326 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Golf-LPGAduMau     08-03 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA du Maurier,0735 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
On road to stardom, weary Pak makes rest stop
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DOUG FERGUSON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Golf Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) _ On the eve of the du Maurier Classic,
with a chance to become the first rookie to win three majors in one
year, Se Ri Pak was a weary soul surrounded by distractions.
	   She sat in the middle of a round table tucked in the corner of
an Asian restaurant, picking at her food as a stream of people came
and went _ a Korean reporter, her father, and manager Steven S.Y.
Kil.
	   There was business to be discussed _ Kil said two endorsements
from U.S. companies are in the works, and dozens of offers from
Asian firms are being considered. But Pak looked as if her mind was
far away.
	   Four days later, she was looking forward to a week off at home
with her beagle puppy, Happy. She was never in contention at the du
Maurier, finishing 13 strokes behind winner Brandie Burton.
	   ``I say every time maybe I'll play next week more better, next
week more better,'' she said. ``I'm thinking every time like that.
The important thing is to rest sometimes.''
	   The strain brought back memories for Annika Sorenstam, who was
paired with Pak the first two rounds.
	   A year ago at Pumpkin Ridge, Sorenstam of Sweden had a chance to
become the first woman to win three consecutive U.S. Opens. She was
consumed with winning to the point that she played her worst golf
of the year and missed the cut.
	   ``I put a lot of pressure on myself, and I couldn't handle it,''
Sorenstam recalled. ``Se Ri is probably a little brighter than I
am, and I don't think it's bothering her too much. It doesn't seem
to be.''
	   Pak came into the LPGA's final major of the season having won
three of the past four weeks, starting with her 20-hole playoff
victory over amateur Jenny Chausiriporn of the United States in the
longest U.S. Women's Open in history.
	   The du Maurier was her sixth tournament in six weeks, and the
schedule took its toll. After closing with a 1-over-par 73 at Essex
Golf and Country Club, Pak knew it was time for a break.
	   ``I think that's why sometimes my shot is not perfect because my
body is a little heavy or something,'' she said. ``I need rest and
will get more better. I have to learn many things.''
	   When Pak won the Open a month ago, she became the youngest woman
to win two majors and brought women's golf to front pages, similar
to Tiger Woods' impact when he won the Masters last year.
	   But Woods proceeded to take the next four weeks off, then showed
up in Dallas and won the Byron Nelson.
	   Pak won the Open, then traveled to Ohio and set an LPGA record
with a 61 on her way to tying the 72-hole scoring record by winning
the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic. Then it was on to the JAL Big Apple
Classic in New York, back to Ohio for the Giant Eagle LPGA Classic
and another win.
	   But it all caught up to her at the du Maurier.
	   Lost in the hype over Pak was a brilliant short game by Burton,
who got up-and-down on the last two holes for a one-stroke victory
over Sorenstam.
	   Burton also crashed the LPGA Tour at an early age. She left
Arizona State after one year, won rookie of the year at 19 and had
won four times, including the du Maurier, by the time she turned
22.
	   Injuries helped keep Burton winless since 1993, along with her
single-mindedness about the game.
	   ``I was so locked into golf,'' Burton said. ``I wasn't having
fun. I'll make sure I enjoy this one.''
	   There wasn't much for Pak to enjoy about the du Maurier.
	   She began rubbing her left shoulder after opening with a 69, and
said Friday it still felt ``heavy'' from too much play. A day
later, Pak had had enough of cameras and microphones thrust into
her face and sneaked off into the locker room.
	   Kil, her agent, said the six straight weeks was designed for Pak
to ``test herself to overcome toughness.''
	   Instead, she never had a chance to become the first woman since
Pat Bradley in 1986 to win three majors in a year, the first player
since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three in a row.
	   ``I think she now realizes that after six weeks, she needs to
have a break,'' Kil said. ``She's 20 years old, she's experiencing
the American tour. As she goes through this kind of experience, it
will help her to accomplish something more, something better,
something big _ winning three majors, maybe next year.''
</TEXT>
