<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Worlds-Notebook,0482 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Senegal improves on last-place finish 20 years ago
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ The last time Senegal was in the World
Basketball Championship it finished last. That was 1978. This time
the African champions finished 15th of 16 teams, beating South
Korea Monday 75-72.
	   In the game to decide 13th place, Nigeria defeated Japan 70-60.
	   Senegal features several players from the U.S. college ranks,
including Makhtar Ndiaye, who played at North Carolina.
	   But the country's isolation from the hotbeds of basketball is
still a hindrance.
	   ``The most important problem we have is the lack of contact with
international basketball,'' coach Bassirou Badji said. ``European
teams get ready by playing each other. In the future, we need to
focus more on that kind of competition.''
	   And what about being 15th instead of 16th and last?
	   ``The only good position in my mind is first place,'' he said.
``Obviously finishing on top is everyone's aim.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   NO. 1 FAN: Dimitris Kapaniris is 16 and Greece's No. 1 fan.
	   During the first week of the tournament, he's been the first fan
in the arena and the last to leave.
	   His trademark is the blue and white, hand-painted canvas sign he
hangs amid thousands of other fanatic Greek fans. It reads, in
Greek of course, ``The Great Greece, We Are With You.''
	   He picks Greece to win Sunday's final, but under one condition.
	   ``If we play Yugoslavia we can lose,'' he admitted. ``If we play
anybody else we can win since there's no Dream Team.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BLISTERING: Athens has been baking for a week. It's been around
38-40 degrees Celsius (100-104 Fahrenheit) daily with no relief in
sight.
	   The sizzling temperatures have set off fast-spreading forest
fires in the mountainous Pendeli region about 20 miles (30
kilometers) north of downtown Athens with vast blankets of smoke
easily visible Monday from the 18,000-seat Olympic stadium _ one of
two sites for the championship.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SOME GAMES, SOME PLAY: Greek newspapers have been reporting on
the whereabouts of various players after the games. Guess what?
They've been spotted in Athens' many clubs, restaurants and bars
along the seafront.
	   According to the Eleftheros Typos newspaper, the Americans were
seen at a club called Romeo near the beach, where they were
listening to traditional music called ``bouzouki.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   NO TEAM: Canadian guard Sherman Hamilton is the only player on
the 16 national teams who doesn't have a professional team to play
for.
	   A 1996 graduate of Virginia Commonwealth, he was drafted by
Sioux Falls of the CBA but released. A few months ago he had a
one-month tryout with a club in Finland, but said couldn't recall
the team's name.
	   ``I'm just trying to get (a job) for this fall,'' he said.
Anything's fine.''
</TEXT>
