<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Chronology,0226 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Key recent events in Congo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Congo &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Here are the major recent events in Congo history:
	   _September 1996: Tutsis in eastern Zaire revolt after local
officials try to expel them. Laurent Kabila, who led a previous
unsuccessful revolt, assumes control of the rebellion.
	   _January-May 1997: Rebels sweep westward across Zaire. Peace
talks fail between strongman Mobutu Sese Seko and Kabila. Mobutu
gives up presidential powers.
	   _May 17, 1997: Kabila's rebel forces march virtually uncontested
into the capital, Kinshasa. Kabila declares himself president and
orders the country renamed the Democratic Republic of Congo.
	   _Nov. 1997: United Nations human rights report cites massive
violations and ``climate of terror'' in Kabila's Congo.
	   _April 17, 1998: U.N. war massacre investigators withdraw from
Kinshasa, citing ``total absence of cooperation'' from Kabila
government.
	   _May-July, 1998: Kabila purges cabinet; sacks James Kabari, a
Rwandan Tutsi, as his top military commander.
	   _July 22: Government announces Kabila has ordered all Rwandan
troops to leave the country.
	   _Aug. 3: Gunfire echoes through Kinshasa as rival soldiers
battle in military barracks. Military officers in eastern province
of North Kivu openly revolt against Kabila.
</TEXT>
