<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Schroeder Washington Trip,0781 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Leading polls at home, Schroeder tests foreign policy muscle in
</HEADLINE>
Washington &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo FRA103 &QL; 
 &UR; By COLLEEN BARRY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HANOVER, Germany (AP) _ Gerhard Schroeder is a man at ease. The
front-runner all year in the race to govern Germany, he strides
confidently into a room packed with foreign journalists, smoking
his trademark cigar.
	   Seven weeks before voters decide whether he will end Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's 16 years in office, Schroeder is ahead in the polls
and _ by his account _ calling the political shots in a heated
campaign.
	   ``This is of course a comfortable position,'' Schroeder said
during an interview Monday at Lower Saxony's administration
offices, from which he has governed the state since 1990.
	   Confident that he leads the battle at home, Schroeder heads to
Washington on Tuesday to take on Kohl in the one area where the
chancellor holds the advantage: experience on the world stage.
	   Hoping to neutralize that shortcoming, Schroeder promises to
stay Kohl's course.
	   ``We don't intend to fundamentally change foreign policy,''
Schroeder said. ``No matter what government emerges after the Sept.
27 elections, Germany is interested in maintaining maximum
continuity in European and trans-Atlantic relations.''
	   His broad reassurances are what Kohl's camp calls vague
platitudes aimed at convincing centrist voters that he can energize
Germany's economy without destabilizing its social net.
	   Schroeder is aware of the criticism, and deftly seizes on it
when asked to outline his vision for Germany, using Britain's Tony
Blair's campaign as an example.
	   Laughing at the suggestion that Blair's concept of a ``modern
nation'' was concrete, he quipped, ``Mine is just as concrete.'' He
did not elaborate.
	   While in the United States, Schroeder will meet with President
Bill Clinton, give a foreign policy speech at Georgetown University
and sign an agreement with officials from Indiana's Purdue
University to open a satellite business school in Lower Saxony.
	   As the election nears, Schroeder's public statements
increasingly sound like an incumbent's. He claimed credit last
month when economic indicators showed improvements, saying the
turnaround was the result of expectations that there would be a new
government, run by him.
	   And it's not just the Social Democrats' steady lead in the polls
_ holding at 41 percent to 37 percent for Kohl's Christian
Democrats in the latest released Friday _ that has fueled
Schroeder's confidence.
	   His assertive campaign has put Kohl on the defensive _ a
position Schroeder contends has weakened the government's position
with voters.
	   Schroeder's appointment of a shadow Cabinet also included some
unlikely choices, who have generated headlines on their own.
	   Economics Minister-designate Jost Stollmann called for trimming
the social welfare system and would-be cultural czar Michael
Naumann suggested that Kohl's plans for a Holocaust memorial in
Berlin should be scrapped.
	   Those ideas and others brought ``violent shrieks'' from Kohl's
camp, Schroeder noted.
	   ``I have the impression that the others are the opposition,''
Schroeder said. ``The government, oddly enough, is in a situation
where they react.
	   ``That has something to do with the expectations. A third of
Germans expect, want, a change of government.''
	   During his 24-hour visit to the United States, Schroeder said he
won't be looking for direct models to ease the country's record
unemployment. Bound by Social Democratic ideals of social justice,
Schroeder shrinks from a purely market-based system.
	   ``I think that you can learn a lot from the dynamics of the
American economy, from the readiness to decisively and quickly
adopt new ideas, and to discuss chances and risks.
	   ``The question is, `How we can make that work in Germany?''
	   He points to innovations at Volkswagen, where he sits on the
board, that allowed for shorter work weeks _ at less pay _ in
return for guarantees of no layoffs.
	   And Schroeder pointed out that American workers at Chrysler will
gain a direct voice in management of a merged DaimlerChrysler with
a seat on the board, a strictly German concept.
	   ``It became clear that one could bring together two corporate
cultures. This can become an example for future cooperation and
mergers,'' he said.
	   Perhaps his clearest statement on the limits transcending
German-American relations was unwitting. He held up the cigar which
he smokes freely in German government chambers, but which is
strictly forbidden in American offices, and joked, ``This is the
last one for two days.''
</TEXT>
