<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar higher in Tokyo, Japanese stocks lower
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar rose against the yen in early
trading Tuesday on nagging concerns over the anemic Japanese
economy's recovery prospects. Tokyo stocks fell.
	   The dollar bought 145.72 yen, up 0.08 yen from late Monday in
Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of 145.60 yen
overnight.
	   In New York, the dollar continued to rally against the yen
Monday in reaction to worrisome economic news from Japan released
late last week, including record high unemployment in June, traders
said.
	   The U.S. currency's gains were stemmed in Tokyo trading,
however, on profit-taking triggered by remarks early Tuesday from a
Japanese Finance Ministry official who warned Japan may take
measures to buoy the sagging yen, they said.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, meanwhile, share prices dropped in
line with the yen's weakening against the dollar overnight and a
decline in U.S. stocks traded on Wall Street Monday, traders said.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average declined 97.10
points, or 0.60 percent, to 16,067.98 in the first half hour of
trading. On Monday, the index lost 213.89 points, or 1.31 percent.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section lost 7.92 points, or 0.64 percent, to 1,237.32. It
fell 16.80 points, or 1.33 percent, the previous day.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 1.215 percent from Monday's finish of 1.225 percent,
driving its price up to 111.69 yen from 111.62 yen.
 &UR; (cd-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
