r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Mauritius-BacktoA     08-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Mauritius-Back to Africa,0857 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indian Ocean island nation once again needs Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NAI104-107 &QL; 
 &UR; By SUSAN LINNEE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PORT LOUIS, Mauritius (AP) _ When Mauritius became independent
30 years ago, it joined the Organization of African Unity, even
though Africa lies 1,600 kilometers (1,000 miles) to the west
across the Indian Ocean.
	   Since then, and despite the fact that African slaves were once
the majority on the island, Mauritians _ 51 percent of whom are now
Hindus from India _ have had little contact with or interest in
Africa.
	   But riding the crest of economic prosperity fueled by the
production and export of textiles and sportswear, the
2,000-square-kilometer (790-square-mile) island is again turning
toward Africa _ for land, labor, and investment opportunities.
	   ``(Former Prime Minister) Seewoosagur Ramgoolam sought to give
Mauritius the African vision and in 1976 hosted the OAU summit.
Now, it's the economic and functional that bring Africa to the
fore,'' said Uttama Bisoondoyal, director of the Mahatma Gandhi
Institute.
	   In addition to training teachers, accountants and artists, the
institute also aims to help the 1.1 million citizens of Mauritius _
whose roots are in Africa, France, India, Britain and China _ to
understand themselves and their history.
	   ``Africa is likely to become extremely important in our
future,'' Bisoondoyal said. ``There may only be a small group here
with African origins, but a greater knowledge of Africa will help
us all.''
	   Thanks to tax-free export processing zones first established in
1970, Mauritius managed to get out from under the yoke of total
dependence on sugar, which has dropped to third place in foreign
currency earnings. In 1996, it had an annual economic growth rate
of 6.1 percent.
	   The Geneva-based World Economic Forum ranked Mauritius No. 1 in
its 1998 Africa Competitiveness Report. And at about dlrs 3,690 a
year, the per capita annual income of Mauritius is 10 times that of
most continental African nations.
	   Some 90,000 people are employed in the tax-free export zones, or
about 20 percent of the workforce, most of them in the textile and
apparel sector, the country's leading foreign currency earner.
Tourism is second.
	   But labor costs are rising in Mauritius, while the economic
crisis in Southeast Asia is driving down production costs in the
regional textile sector.
	   Maurice Vigier de la Tour, director of Floreal Knitwear, which
after Benneton is the world's second-largest manufacturer of woolen
sweaters, called Africa ``the natural expansion area for this
business.''
	   Floreal employs 12,000 people in Mauritius and another 5,000 in
Madagascar. The company is planning to set up knitwear operations
in Mozambique, Lesotho and Namibia where salaries and costs are
lower than in Mauritius, a former British colony.
	   Vigier de la Tour is also head of the Mauritius Export
Processing Zone Association, which is pushing hard for passage of
U.S. President Bill Clinton's African Growth and Opportunity Act.
	   Mauritian textile exports to the United States, like those of
Kenya and several other African nations, are limited by quota. The
trade bill would remove the quotas.
	   ``The bill would allow Mauritius and Africa to gear up for
competition from Southeast Asia, Mexico and the Caribbean when
quotas throughout the world are lifted after 2004,'' Vigier de la
Tour said.
	   Mauritius and Mozambique have signed an agreement under which
Mauritian firms will be able to use 100,000 hectares (250,000
acres) of Mozambican land to set up factories, processing plants or
to grow crops.
	   Mauritian sugar companies are also expanding into Africa where
the Mon Loisir group has formed a consortium with the French Union
St. Aubin to rehabilitate a sugar factory in the West African
nation of Benin. Another consortium involving Mon Loisir will
rehabilitate a sugar mill in Mozambique.
	   In a recent editorial, the country's largest newspaper,
L'Express, said Mauritian-African cooperation should not be limited
to breathing new life into sugar refineries.
	   ``It should also be a sharing of the experience acquired in
economic management, to motivate African countries to grow on their
land ... the products that we need.''
	   Africans have been in Mauritius since the mid 1630s when the
Dutch attempted to establish a settlement on the uninhabited
volcanic island. They introduced sugar cane and deer from Java,
brought in rats and exterminated the dodo, a large flightless bird
whose meat was fancied by Dutch sailors. They also imported slaves.
	   The French replaced the Dutch and began serious sugar cane
production, with the labor of more African slaves. After the
British assumed control, they abolished slavery in 1835 and brought
in thousands of indentured Hindus from India to work in the cane
fields.
	   Although Africans were the majority in Mauritius 250 years ago,
today there are only about 30,000 Afro-Mauritians. Most live in the
southwestern corner of the country in Riviere Noire district where
they are fishermen and day laborers.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Mauritius-Back to Africa; CT:f; 
