<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Bankruptcy Declines,0660 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Personal bankruptcies peaking, study says, but root causes remain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PATRICIA LAMIELL &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Personal bankruptcy filings, which have grown to
record levels in recent years, will level off this year and decline
in 1999, according to a recent study.
	   The decline in filings reflects a drop in interest rates, which
has enabled consumers to refinance debt at lower monthly payments,
according to the study by SMR Research Corp.
	   But it warns that the root causes of the boom in bankruptcies _
such as too much debt _ continue to worsen.
	   ``Bankruptcy remains a serious problem,'' said Stuart A.
Feldstein, president of SMR Research. ``Other than interest rates,
all the other basic drivers behind bankruptcy look worse. When
rates rise again, we'll probably see record bankruptcy filings
again.''
	   The SMR warnings are in line with projections released in July
by Visa USA, the brand with the largest number of credit cards.
Visa said that despite slower growth during the first six months of
this year, total personal bankruptcy filings would hit a new high
of 1.35 million in 1998 and continue growing to 2.2 million a year
by 2001.
	   In 1997, an all-time high of 1.332 million personal bankruptcies
were filed in the United States.
	   SMR forecasts that the growth rate will flatten this year, with
total filings between 1.25 million to 1.35 million, and decline
next year to between 1.15 and 1.28 million. Those estimates will be
lowered if tougher bankruptcy legislation currently before Congress
is passed, Feldstein said.
	   For the time being, falling interest rates have slowed the
growth of bankruptcies by lowering housing costs, which are ``the
vast majority of consumer debt,'' Feldstein said.
	   Total home mortgage debt in the United States exceeds dlrs 4
trillion. All other consumer debt combined, including credit card,
auto loans, and mobile home loans, comes to less than dlrs 1.3
trillion, SMR figures show.
	   Personal bankruptcy filings began to climb in 1984, when they
reached 282,105. They increased steadily to 893,248 in 1992, then
declined 13 percent to 773,111 in 1994.
	   Higher interest rates and consumer debt levels in 1994 and 1995
pushed up the bankruptcy again.
	   ``The main causes of bankruptcy are a host of socio-economic
problems that can lead to personal financial disaster,'' SMR said.
The study also cites other problems related to consumer attitudes
toward debt, such as the growth of legal gambling and aggressive
advertising by lawyers handling bankruptcy cases, which has helped
reduce the stigma of such filings.
	   In addition, the number of Americans lacking health insurance
reached 15.6 percent in 1996, up from 12.9 percent 10 years prior,
in 1987, according to the most recent census data.
	   ``This raises to more than 41 million the number of people at
risk of bankruptcy in the event they require hospitalization and
cannot pay the bills,'' SMR said.
	   Divorce often triggers bankruptcy, as divorced people typically
face income and expense pressures greater than married people face.
	   The average number of adult Americans over age 18 who are
divorced reached an all-time high of 9.9 percent in March 1997, and
by mid-1998 should exceed 10 percent, SMR said.
	   Proposed federal legislation, if it passes, could cut down on
bankruptcy filings, SMR said. A bill passed in June by the House,
would require bankruptcy filers above a certain income to pay back
at least part of their debts rather than having them all dismissed.
Prospects are unclear for a milder measure pending in the Senate.
	   Credit card issuers say they have tightened restrictions on who
gets credit. But consumer groups have blamed the issuers for the
rise in bankruptcies, saying they flood consumers' with enticing
offers, issue credit to people who can't pay it back, and raise
charge limits to inappropriate levels.
</TEXT>
