<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Castro,0760 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Castro visits late Grenadian leader's mother at end of Caribbean
</HEADLINE>
tour &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Recaps previous to UPDATE with Castro predicting end to trade
embargo; ADDS Clinton administration comment. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos GRD101-02 &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHELLE FAUL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) _ Wrapping up a Caribbean tour that
helped shatter Cuba's isolation from its neighbors, Fidel Castro
visited with the mother of a leftist leader whose death at the
hands of hard-liners in his own movement prompted the U.S. invasion
of Grenada.
	   Castro's visit with Alimenta Bishop stirred the woman's memories
of her son Maurice, a former Cuban ally, and she hugged the bearded
leader and welcomed him into her home.
	   Over the past six days, Castro has also stopped in Jamaica and
Barbados, island nations that once shunned him but are now
receptive to his demands for an end of almost four decades of
U.S.-led economic sanctions against Cuba.
	   At a rally in St. George's on Monday evening, Castro predicted
an end to the embargo.
	   ``The blockade cannot last forever,'' Castro said to roars of
approval from the crowd. ``The same way they did during the war in
Vietnam, the American people themselves will put an end to that
cruel and unfair action.''
	   Sensitive to his hosts, Castro did not once refer to Maurice
Bishop in his 95-minute speech.
	   Later this month, Castro plans to travel to the Dominican
Republic, where about 20 Caribbean leaders are gathering at a
special summit, apparently called solely to further the regional
reintegration of Cuba.
	   After Castro finished his chat with Mrs. Bishop, neither he nor
his host would comment about the visit.
	   But in an interview with The Associated Press before Castro's
arrived, Mrs. Bishop agreed to talk about her son's last days,
saying she blamed his death only on hard-line Marxists in his New
Jewel Movement who betrayed him _ not the United States, or Cuba,
or the Cold War.
	   ``There were a lot a rumors going around,'' the 83-year-old Mrs.
Bishop recalled. ``There are a lot of things I didn't know myself
because my son never wanted me to be involved too much.''
	   Bishop had ousted the corrupt and dictatorial regime of Eric
Gairy in 1979. Gairy died last year.
	   A handsome revolutionary, Bishop won the hearts of many
Grenadians, but rankled Caribbean neighbors and the United States
with his close ties to Castro. But when he was overthrown in early
October 1983, it was by allies who thought him ideologically too
soft.
	   Several days after he was placed under house arrest, soldiers
shot Bishop and his colleagues _ including his lover and Education
Minister Jacqueline Creft.
	   ``He trusted ... those Judases,'' lamented Bishop's sister Ann,
waiting for Castro with her mother. Keith Bishop, who bears a
striking resemblance to his dead cousin, added: ``He was too kind
and too soft, and that's why the hard people took over.''
	   The United States had never been enamored of Bishop, but liked
his fearsome successors even less. A few days after the execution,
President Ronald Reagan sent a U.S.-led invasion force to the
island, saying American medical students there were in danger.
	   Armed Cuban construction workers who had been building an
airport were kicked out after what was the only U.S.-Cuban fighting
of the Cold War. A democratic regime was installed. And Bishop's
killers were thrown in jail for life. The death toll included 45
Grenadians, 29 Cubans and 18 Americans.
	   U.S. strategists had feared the airport would give Cuba's air
force deep reach into South America. But with the Cubans out, the
Americans completed it, giving Grenada a direct link to the world
that Premier Keith Mitchell calls ``a gateway to development.''
	   On Saturday, Castro unveiled a plaque at the airport
commemorating Cuba's contribution to it.
	   Mitchell, once a Castro foe, said Castro's visit was ``an
opportunity to pursue the question of reconciliation.''
	   As Castro wound up the tour, the Clinton administration,
meanwhile, chided the countries he visited for not insisting on
democratic change as a condition for inviting him.
	   It also said the funds Castro used to carry out his tour might
have been better spent on meeting the needs of his deprived
countrymen.
	   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the
administration strongly believes that Caribbean governments that
engage Cuba ``ought to condition such engagement on fundamental,
systematic change by the Cuban government and respect for human
rights.''
</TEXT>
