<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Climbing Accident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French woman injured climbing Philippine volcano
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LEGAZPI, Philippines (AP) _ Rescuers on Tuesday were trying to
reach a French woman reportedly injured after falling off a ravine
while climbing a volcano, disaster officials said.
	   Two air force helicopters with paramedics were sent to the
eastern side of the Mayon volcano which the woman and her two
companions had climbed early Monday.
	   The woman reportedly suffered head and leg injuries but it was
not immediately known how serious her condition was, said Cedric
Daep, the Albay provincial disaster operations officer.
	   The three French tourists, whose names were not immediately
available, hired a local resident to guide them up the 2,462-meter
volcano (8,125-foot) volcano.
	   The woman apparently slid off a ravine after they became
separated from their guide. The guide later found them about 500
feet (151 meters) up the slope of the mountain Monday afternoon and
reported the incident to local authorities, Daep said.
	   The other tourists were a man and woman.
	   Governor Al Francis Bichara said the tourists did not use
certified guides from the local tourism office and did not inform
local authorities they had planned to climb the volcano, about 320
kilometers (200 miles) southeast of Manila.
	   Mayon, one of the most active volcanoes in the Philippines, last
erupted in February 1994 killing at least 70 people.
	   After the 1994 erutpion, the government declared an area six
kilometers (3.75 miles) around the summit as a permanent danger
zone off limits to tourists and local residents. 	   
</TEXT>
