<SLUG> BC-Japan-Politics-Polls, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two major surveys show support for Obuchi at just 25 percent
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; UPDATES with reports of finance minister hinting at permanent tax
cuts &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Only one in four voters questioned support Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi's Cabinet, two major newspapers said Tuesday,
making it the second least popular start for a new administration.
	   The respected Nihon Keizai business daily said its nationwide
survey conducted over three days after the launch of Obuchi's
Cabinet on July 30 showed a 25.1 percent approval rating for the
new administration.
	   Another poll taken by the mass-circulation Mainichi showed
support for the Cabinet at 25 percent, with 48 percent of
respondents saying they disapproved of the new administration.
	   In recent decades, only the short-lived government of
scandal-tainted Prime Minister Sosuke Uno in 1989 had lower ratings
at its start. The 48 percent disapproval rating was the worst ever
for a new Cabinet, the Mainichi said.
	   The polls come as the new administration scrambles to convince a
skeptical public it is serious about its pledges to lift Japan out
of recession and clean up the bad loan mess in the country's
banking system.
	   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, the lynchpin of Obuchi's
self-styled ``economic recovery Cabinet,'' hinted Tuesday that the
government may introduce 4 trillion yen (dlrs 27.4 billion) in
permanent income tax cuts next year, Kyodo News reported.
	   The government has already implemented special income tax relief
worth 4 trillion yen (dlrs 27.4 billion) for 1998.
	   The surveys conducted by the Mainichi and the Nihon Keizai
follow similar polls released earlier this week.
	   On Monday, an Asahi newspaper poll gave support for Obuchi's
administration at 32 percent, while one published Sunday by the
Yomiuri, Japan's largest newspaper, put it at a slightly higher
33.1 percent.
	   The Mainichi survey also said that for the first time the main
opposition Democratic Party had become Japan's most popular
political party. It garnered 26 percent support, compared with 19
percent for Obuchi's ruling Liberal Democratic Party.
	   The Nihon Keizai said its poll showed the two parties virtually
neck and neck, with 28.2 percent supporting the Democrats and 28
percent supporting the LDP.
	   The LDP suffered devastating losses in July 12 elections for the
upper house of Parliament, which forced Ryutaro Hashimoto to step
down as prime minister. Hashimoto's administration was widely
blamed for deepening Japan's severe economic crisis.
	   In a bruising leadership battle, Obuchi, a veteran LDP consensus
builder, won his party's support to become Japan's new prime
minister. But opinion surveys showed he was the least popular of
the three party candidates to take the helm of the government.
	   The Nihon Keizai polled 1,770 eligible voters nationwide between
July 31 and August 2. The Mainichi conducted its nationwide survey
on August 1 and 2, but did not say how many people it questioned.
As is customary with Japanese polls, no margin of error was given.
 &UR; (js) 	   
</TEXT>
