<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Slayings Arrest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian officials vow to speed trial of alleged Khmer Rouge
</HEADLINE>
killer &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodian justice officials said
Tuesday that they are working to speed up the trial of a former
Khmer Rouge guerrilla suspected of ordering the killing of three
Western tourists in 1994.
	   Nuon Paet was arrested Saturday for heading a band of guerrillas
who halted a train in the southern province of Kampot, abducted and
allegedly killed David Wilson, 29, of Australia, Mark Slater, 28,
of Britain and Jean-Michel Braquet, 27, of France.
	   Justice Minister Chem Snguon said he has requested the
provincial court of Kampot, where the slayings took place, to
transfer the case to Phnom Penh within the next few days.
	   The deputy chief of the Phnom Penh court, Nop Sophon, said once
he receives the go-ahead, ``we will start handling the case
immediately.''
	   Nuon Paet was arrested in Phnom Penh after the government lured
him to the capital from the former guerrilla stronghold of Pailin
with a bogus business deal.
	   He is being detained at the capital's dilapidated T-3 prison.
	   Though the three Western backpackers were killed in Kampot, from
where the warrant for Nuon Paet's arrest was originally issued,
Cambodian leader Hun Sen over the weekend said that he wanted the
trial to be held in Phnom Penh ``for security reasons.''
</TEXT>
